The '''Inflation Reduction Act of 2022''' ('''IRA'''), {{USPL|117|169}}, is a [[Law of the United States|United States federal law]] which aimed to [[Deficit reduction in the United States|reduce the federal government budget deficit]], lower [[Prescription drug prices in the United States|prescription drug prices]], and invest in domestic energy production while promoting [[renewable energy]]. It was passed by the [[117th United States Congress]] and signed into law by President [[Joe Biden]] on August 16, 2022.

It is a [[Reconciliation (United States Congress)|budget reconciliation]] bill sponsored by senators [[Chuck Schumer]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[New York (state)|NY]]) and [[Joe Manchin]] (D-[[West Virginia|WV]]).<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Everett |first=Burgess |date=July 27, 2022|title=Manchin and Schumer announce deal that includes energy, taxes |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2022/07/27/manchin-schumer-senate-deal-energy-taxes-00048325 |access-date=July 27, 2022 |website=Politico }}</ref> The bill was the result of negotiations on the proposed [[Build Back Better Act]], which was reduced and comprehensively reworked from its initial proposal after being opposed by Manchin.<ref>{{cite web |last=Zhou |first=Li |title=How Democrats plan to overhaul taxes, climate spending, and health care before the midterms |url=https://www.vox.com/23281547/build-back-better-joe-manchin-inflation-reduction-act |website=[[Vox (website)|Vox]] |access-date=July 30, 2022 |date=July 28, 2022}}</ref> It was introduced as an amendment to the Build Back Better Act and the legislative text was substituted. All Democrats in the Senate and House voted for the bill while all voting Republicans voted against it.<ref name=":10" /><ref name=":11" /> It was described as a landmark piece of legislation.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dennis |first=Brady |date=August 14, 2022 |title=As Congress funds high-tech climate solutions, it also bets on a low-tech one: Nature |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/climate-solutions/2022/08/14/nature-climate-solutions-inflation-reduction-act/ |access-date=August 29, 2022 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |quote=The landmark Inflation Reduction Act that passed Friday includes $369 billion in climate- and energy-related funding — much of it aimed at high-tech solutions to help nudge the world's biggest historical emitter toward a greener future.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kaufman |first1=Anna |date=September 23, 2022 |title=What is the Inflation Reduction Act 2022? Answering your common questions about the bill. |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/2022/09/23/inflation-reduction-act-2022-explained/8082806001/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230309055327/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/2022/09/23/inflation-reduction-act-2022-explained/8082806001/ |archive-date=March 9, 2023 |access-date=March 9, 2023 |publisher=USA Today |quote=The Inflation Reduction Act of 2022, a landmark piece of legislation passed this summer, has broad implications across multiple sectors of the economy. The policy package is less robust than the Build Back Better bill President Joe Biden tried to push through Congress last year but it's still ambitious in its targeting of prescription drug prices and carbon emissions.}}</ref>

According to the nonpartisan [[Congressional Budget Office]] (CBO) and [[United States Congressional Joint Committee on Taxation|Joint Committee on Taxation]] (JCT), the law will raise $738{{nbsp}}billion from [[tax reform]] and prescription drug reform to lower prices, as well as authorize $891{{nbsp}}billion in total spending – including $391 billion on [[Energy in the United States|energy]] and [[climate change in the United States|climate change]], and 64{{nbsp}}billion on three years of [[Affordable Care Act]] subsidies.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":7">{{Cite web |title=CBO Scores IRA with $238 Billion of Deficit Reduction |url=https://www.crfb.org/blogs/cbo-scores-ira-238-billion-deficit-reduction |access-date=2022-09-21 |website=Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget |date=September 7, 2022 |language=en}} Note the ''original'' September 7 CBO estimates are $391 billion for climate action, $108 billion for health care, $281 billion from health savings, and $457 billion from tax reform, for a net total of $238 billion in deficit reduction.</ref> It represents the largest investment towards addressing [[greenhouse gas emissions]] in United States history.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nilsen |first1=Ella |title=Clean energy package would be biggest legislative climate investment in US history |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2022/07/28/politics/climate-deal-joe-manchin/index.html |website=CNN |access-date=31 July 2022 |date=28 July 2022}}</ref> It also includes a large expansion of the [[Internal Revenue Service]] (IRS), including the hiring of up to 87,000 new employees to replace tens of thousands of recent departures, which led to over $1 billion being collected in past-due taxes from [[millionaire]]s and other high-wealth individuals by July 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |last=CFP® |first=Kate Dore |date=2021-05-05 |title=Biden's $80 billion plan to beef up IRS audits may target wealthy small business owners |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2021/05/05/bidens-80-billion-plan-to-beef-up-irs-audits-may-target-wealthy-small-business-owners.html |access-date=2024-07-12 |website=CNBC |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/irs-tops-1-billion-in-past-due-taxes-collected-from-millionaires-compliance-efforts-continue-involving-high-wealth-groups-corporations-partnerships | title=IRS tops $1 billion in past-due taxes collected from millionaires; compliance efforts continue involving high-wealth groups, corporations, partnerships &#124; Internal Revenue Service }}</ref>{{efn|A portion of the new IRS funding was rescinded in the [[Fiscal Responsibility Act of 2023]].}} 

The act is generally not believed to have reduced [[inflation]] in 2022 and 2023,<ref>{{cite news |author1=Josh Boak |author2=Paul Wiseman |date=August 13, 2023 |title=Yes, inflation is down. No, the Inflation Reduction Act doesn't deserve the credit |url=https://apnews.com/article/biden-inflation-reduction-climate-anniversary-9950f7e814ac71e89eee3f452ab17f71. |publisher=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>https://www.cbo.gov/system/files/2022-08/58357-Graham.pdf "Enacting the bill would affect economic activity and inflation beyond 2023. CBO has not evaluated those effects."</ref> although some economists predict the renewable energy investments will bring down inflation in the medium-to-long term.<ref name=":14">{{Cite web |last=Leber |first=Rebecca |date=2022-08-12 |title=Fight climate change. End fossilflation. Here's how. |url=https://www.vox.com/science-and-health/2022/8/12/23290488/fight-climate-change-end-fossil-fuel-inflation |access-date=2024-08-21 |website=Vox |language=en-US |quote=Reducing reliance on fossil fuels 'will significantly reduce its grip on inflation in the broader economy,' said Zandi. It's the reason why economists eventually expect the Inflation Reduction Act to live up to the bill's name.}}</ref><ref name=":4">{{cite web |last=Sahay |first=Richa |date=2022-11-01 |title=How the US Inflation Reduction Act will impact the economy |url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2022/11/how-new-laws-meet-climate-goals/ |access-date=2023-03-13 |website=[[World Economic Forum]] |publisher= |quote=In the short term, the US government and investment banks will remain invested in assets that may have higher emissions. But in the medium- to long-term, the impact of the IRA is likely to be deflationary. This is because the IRA is not promoting divestments from fossil-fuel, but rather encouraging investment in clean technologies.}}</ref>

In 2026, the first group of 10 high-cost drugs selected by Medicare will have their negotiated prices take effect.<ref name="WordBrown2022">{{cite web |last1=Strautman |first1=Alex |title=Important Health Measures in the Inflation Reduction Act |url=https://www.wordandbrown.com/NewsPost/inflation-reduction-act |website=Word & Brown |access-date=March 17, 2026 |date=September 27, 2022 |quote=Arguably, the most meaningful change coming with the IRA is the ability for Medicare to negotiate drug prices starting in 2026. It will affect 10 drugs on which Medicare spent the most money during the prior year... Drug makers that refuse to negotiate could face a tax penalty.}}</ref>

== Background ==
{{See also|Build Back Better Act|Build Back Better Plan}}
{{Joe Biden series|expanded=Policies}}
The Build Back Better Plan was a legislative framework proposed by United States president [[Joe Biden]] between 2020 and 2021. Generally viewed as ambitious in size and scope, it sought to make the largest nationwide public investments in social, infrastructural, and environmental programs since the 1930s [[Great Depression]]-fighting policies of the [[New Deal]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Build Back Better Framework |url=https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/build-back-better/ |access-date=2021-11-14 |website=The White House |language=en-US}}</ref>

The plan was divided into three parts: one of them, the [[American Rescue Plan Act of 2021|American Rescue Plan]], a COVID-19 relief spending bill, was signed into law in March 2021.<ref name=":22">{{Cite web |last=Yarmuth |first=John A. |date=2021-03-11 |title=H.R.1319 - 117th Congress (2021-2022): American Rescue Plan Act of 2021 |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/117th-congress/house-bill/1319 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210226113259/https://www.congress.gov/bill/117th-congress/house-bill/1319 |archive-date=February 26, 2021 |access-date=2021-04-29 |website=Congress.gov}}</ref> The other two parts were reworked into different bills over the course of extensive negotiations within and among Congressional entities. The American Jobs Plan (AJP) was a proposal to address long-neglected infrastructure needs and reduce America's contributions to [[climate change]]'s destructive effects;<ref name=":02">{{Cite web |date=March 31, 2021 |title=Fact Sheet: The American Jobs Plan |url=https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2021/03/31/fact-sheet-the-american-jobs-plan/ |access-date=March 31, 2021 |website=The White House |language=en-US}}</ref> the American Families Plan (AFP) was a proposal to fund a variety of [[social policy]] initiatives, some of which (e.g. paid [[family leave]]) had never before been enacted nationally in the U.S.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2021-04-28 |title=Fact Sheet: The American Families Plan |url=https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2021/04/28/fact-sheet-the-american-families-plan/ |access-date=2021-04-29 |website=The White House |language=en-US}}</ref>

The [[Build Back Better Act]] was a [[Bill (law)|bill]] introduced in the [[117th United States Congress|117th Congress]] to fulfill aspects of the [[Build Back Better Plan]]. It was spun off from the American Jobs Plan, alongside the [[Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act]], as a $3.5{{nbsp}}trillion [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Reconciliation (United States Congress)|reconciliation]] package that included provisions related to [[climate change in the United States]] (centered around Senator [[Ron Wyden]]'s technology-neutral, tax incentive-first approach)<ref name="Dayen on Wyden 2022">{{cite web | last=Dayen | first=David | title=How Policy Got Done in 2022 | website=The American Prospect | date=September 26, 2022 | url=https://prospect.org/politics/how-policy-got-done-in-2022/ | access-date=August 28, 2023}}</ref><ref name="Weissmann 2023">{{cite web | last=Weissmann | first=Jordan | title=How the Inflation Reduction Act was really born | website=Semafor | date=August 16, 2023 | url=https://www.semafor.com/article/08/16/2023/how-the-inflation-reduction-act-was-really-born | access-date=August 28, 2023}}</ref> and [[social policy]], lowered to approximately $2.2{{nbsp}}trillion. The bill was passed 220–213 by the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] on November 19, 2021.

In December 2021, amidst negotiations and [[Parliamentarian of the United States Senate|parliamentary]] procedures, Senator [[Joe Manchin]] publicly pulled his support from the bill citing its cost and a too-aggressive transition to clean energy,<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Seipel |first1=Arnie |last2=Hernandez |first2=Joe |date=2021-12-19 |title=Joe Manchin says he won't support President Biden's Build Back Better plan |language=en |work=NPR |url=https://www.npr.org/2021/12/19/1065636709/joe-manchin-says-he-cannot-support-bidens-build-back-better-plan |access-date=2022-08-31}}</ref> then retracted support for his own compromise legislation. This effectively killed the bill as it needed 50 senators to pass via reconciliation, and all 50 Republican senators opposed it.

In the summer of 2022, Manchin and [[Senate majority leader]] [[Chuck Schumer]] engaged in negotiations over a revised reconciliation bill with about $1 trillion in revenue from [[tax reform]], $500 billion in climate and health care spending, and $500 billion in deficit reduction.<ref name="Everett">{{Cite web |last=Everett |first=Burgess |title=Manchin's offer to Dems: Take a health care deal or try again later |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2022/07/14/manchin-rejects-climate-tax-elements-of-party-line-dem-bill-00046018 |access-date=2022-12-31 |website=Politico |date=July 14, 2022 |language=en}}</ref> However, Manchin announced abruptly on July 14, 2022 that he would not support new climate spending or tax reform due to his fear that the bill would worsen inflation.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Cochrane |first1=Emily |last2=Friedman |first2=Lisa |date=2022-07-15 |title=Manchin Pulls Plug on Climate and Tax Talks, Shrinking Domestic Plan |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/07/14/us/politics/manchin-climate-taxes.html |access-date=2022-12-31 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He later stated that he would be open to revisiting those elements a few months later, provided that inflation slowed meaningfully.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Weissmann |first=Jordan |date=2022-07-15 |title=Joe Manchin Just Knifed What Was Left of Biden's Agenda |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2022/07/joe-manchin-climate-spending-democrats.html |access-date=2022-12-31 |website=Slate Magazine |language=en}}</ref> Biden nonetheless conceded defeat on a climate bill, urging Congress to pass whatever Manchin would agree to (a slim, $280 billion health care bill that would acquire its revenue from allowing Medicare to negotiate prices and spend $40 billion on Affordable Care Act subsidies).<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Tankersley |first1=Jim |last2=Friedman |first2=Lisa |last3=Davenport |first3=Coral |date=2022-07-15 |title=Biden Concedes Defeat on Climate Bill as Manchin and Inflation Upend Agenda |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/07/15/climate/biden-inflation-climate-manchin.html |access-date=2022-12-31 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name="Everett"/>

Unbeknownst to nearly everyone in Washington, Manchin and Schumer reengaged in secret negotiations on July 18, 2022.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Lizza |first1=Ryan |last2=Daniels |first2=Eugene |title=Politico Playbook: How it really happened: The Inflation Reduction Act |url=https://www.politico.com/newsletters/playbook/2022/08/08/how-it-really-happened-the-inflation-reduction-act-00050279 |access-date=2022-12-31 |website=Politico |date=August 8, 2022 |language=en}}</ref> On July 27, hours after the Senate passed the [[CHIPS and Science Act]],<ref name=":0"/> the two men released a statement announcing the $891 billion Inflation Reduction Act of 2022, which included climate spending and tax reform.<ref>{{Cite web |author1=Kevin Liptak |author2=Manu Raju |author3=Ella Nilsen |author4=Alex Rogers |date=July 28, 2022 |title=How secret negotiations revived Joe Biden's agenda and shocked Washington |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/07/28/politics/manchin-schumer-biden-deal/index.html |access-date=2022-08-13 |website=CNN}}</ref>

The sudden deal was widely regarded as a "shocker", as Democrats had voiced little hope for a revival of their climate and tax priorities, in addition to Manchin himself being rather pessimistic on the prospect of an expanded bill.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Manchin's latest shocker: A $700B deal |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2022/07/27/manchin-schumer-senate-deal-energy-taxes-00048325 |access-date=2022-08-13 |website=Politico |date=July 27, 2022 |language=en}}</ref>

As the revised bill made its way through the chambers of Congress, the new reality of Biden unexpectedly having a clear path to enacting substantial portions of his domestic agenda into law led to a wide reevaluation of the success of the [[Presidency of Joe Biden|Biden presidency]] thus far and was expected to give the president and his party a boost in the [[2022 United States elections|2022 midterm elections]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Biden suddenly is piling up wins. Can Dems make it stick? |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2022/08/09/joe-biden-legislative-wins-00050461 |access-date=2022-08-13 |website=Politico |date=August 9, 2022 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Montanaro |first=Domenico |date=2022-08-12 |title=Biden's recent wins could give Democrats a boost heading into the midterms |language=en |work=NPR |url=https://www.npr.org/2022/08/12/1116745451/democrats-biden-midterms |access-date=2022-08-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Chait |first=Jonathan |date=2022-08-12 |title=Joe Biden's Best Week Ever |url=https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2022/08/joe-biden-presidency-best-week-ever.html |access-date=2022-08-13 |website=Intelligencer |language=en-us}}</ref>

==Legislative history==
[[File:P20220816CS-0389 (52386878143).jpg|thumb|President [[Joe Biden]] signing the bill into law in the [[State Dining Room]] of the White House on August 16, 2022. (L-R) Senator [[Joe Manchin]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]-[[West Virginia|WV]]), [[Party leaders of the United States Senate|Senate majority leader]] Chuck Schumer (D-[[New York (state)|NY]]), Rep. [[Jim Clyburn]] (D-[[South Carolina|SC]]), Rep. [[Frank Pallone]] (D-[[New Jersey|NJ]]), and Rep. [[Kathy Castor]] (D-[[Florida|FL]]).]]
The [[Build Back Better Act]], which passed the House on September 27, 2021, was used by the Senate as the legislative vehicle for this legislation. On August 6, 2022, Senate majority leader Chuck Schumer proposed an amendment which would replace the text of the previously passed bill with the text of the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022. This substitute amendment was later adopted.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Yarmuth |first=John A. |date=2022-08-08 |title=Actions - H.R.5376 - 117th Congress (2021-2022): Inflation Reduction Act of 2022 |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/117th-congress/house-bill/5376/all-actions |access-date=2022-08-12 |website=www.congress.gov}}</ref>

Schumer's lead staffer, Gerry Petrella, recalled the surprise phone call came from Senator Joe Manchin's office just prior to the August recess and the breakthrough negotiations occurred on the final summer weekend.<ref>Emma Dumain. (28 July 2023). "Q&A: Former Schumer aide on IRA behind the scenes". [https://www.eenews.net/articles/qa-former-schumer-aide-on-ira-behind-the-scenes/ E&E Daily website] Retrieved 29 August 2023.</ref> Some of the many experts, lobbyists and organizers who worked to refine the bill's provisions included [[Leah C. Stokes]], Adrian Deveny, Katherine Hamilton, Ari Appel, Mike Carr, Danielle Deiseroth, Ari Mathusiak, Camila Thorndike, Jamal Raad, Topher Spiro, and Yogin Kothari;<ref name="St. John 2024-11-11">{{cite web |last=St. John|first=Jeff| title=How to keep the climate fight alive through a second Trump term | website=Canary Media | date=November 11, 2024 | url=https://www.canarymedia.com/articles/politics/how-to-keep-the-climate-fight-alive-through-a-second-trump-term | access-date=November 11, 2024}}</ref><ref name="Dayen on Wyden 2022"/><ref name="Olano 2023">{{cite web | last=Olano|first=Maria Virginia|title=A behind-the-scenes look at how the Inflation Reduction Act came together| website=Canary Media | date=August 15, 2023 | url=https://www.canarymedia.com/articles/clean-energy/a-behind-the-scenes-look-at-how-the-inflation-reduction-act-came-together | access-date=November 11, 2024}}</ref> the overall approach was shaped by Manchin and Senators [[Ron Wyden]], [[Mark Warner]] and [[Chris Coons]], while Representative [[Scott Peters (politician)|Scott Peters]] worked to add pro-pharmaceutical industry limits to the Medicare drug pricing provisions, [[Bernie Sanders]] contributed the basis for the Solar for All program, and Senators [[Elizabeth Warren]] and [[Kyrsten Sinema]] negotiated on shaping an alternative minimum tax for corporate book income.<ref name="Dayen on Wyden 2022"/><ref name="Gearino 2024">{{cite web | last=Gearino | first=Dan | title=IRA's Solar for All Program Will Install Nearly 1 Million Systems in US | website=Inside Climate News | date=April 23, 2024 | url=https://insideclimatenews.org/news/23042024/inflation-reduction-act-solar-for-all/ | access-date=April 17, 2025}}</ref><ref name="Weissmann 2023"/>

On August 7, 2022, following the [[vote-a-rama]], an unlimited marathon voting session on amendments, that lasted nearly 16 hours, the Senate passed the bill (as amended) on a 51–50 vote, with all Democrats voting in favor, all Republicans voting against, and Vice President [[Kamala Harris]] [[List of tie-breaking votes cast by the vice president of the United States|breaking the tie]].<ref name=":10">{{Cite web |title=Senate passes Democrats' sweeping climate, health and tax bill, delivering win for Biden |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/inflation-reduction-act-senate-pass-climate-healthcare-tax-bill/ |access-date=2022-08-12 |website=www.cbsnews.com |date=August 8, 2022 |language=en-US}}</ref> On August 12, 2022, the bill was passed by the House on a 220–207 vote, with all Democrats voting in favor and all Republicans voting against it.<ref name=":11">{{Cite news |title=House passes Inflation Reduction Act, sending climate and health bill to Biden |language=en-US |newspaper=Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/us-policy/2022/08/12/inflation-reduction-act-house-vote/ |access-date=2022-08-12 |issn=0190-8286}}</ref> On August 16, 2022, the bill was signed into law by President Joe Biden.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Maegan Vazquez |title=Biden signs Inflation Reduction Act into law |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/08/16/politics/biden-inflation-reduction-act-signing/index.html |access-date=2022-08-16 |website=CNN|date=August 16, 2022 }}</ref>

==Provisions==
Over a period of 10 years, the law was estimated to raise revenue from:<ref name="dem_sum">{{cite web |date=August 11, 2022 |title=Summary: The Inflation Reduction Act of 2022 |url=https://www.democrats.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/inflation_reduction_act_one_page_summary.pdf |access-date=August 12, 2022 |publisher=Senate Democratic Leadership}} Estimates from the [[United States Congressional Joint Committee on Taxation]] or [[Congressional Budget Office]], depending on the number.</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author=Manu Raju and Ali Zaslav |title=Sinema says she will 'move forward' on economic bill, putting Biden's agenda on the cusp of Senate approval |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/08/04/politics/chuck-schumer-economic-bill-saturday/index.html |access-date=2022-08-05 |website=CNN|date=August 4, 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Kimball |first=Spencer |title=Passage of Inflation Reduction Act gives Medicare historic new powers over drug prices |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/08/12/drug-prices-passage-of-inflation-reduction-act-gives-medicare-historic-new-powers.html |access-date=2022-08-16 |website=CNBC |date=August 12, 2022 |language=en}}</ref>
* Prescription drug price reform to lower prices, including [[prescription drug prices in the United States#Solutions|Medicare negotiation of drug prices]] for certain drugs (starting at 10 new ones per year by 2026, increasing to more than 20 additional ones per year<ref name="KFF 2022">{{cite web | title=Explaining the Prescription Drug Provisions in the Inflation Reduction Act |last1=Cubanski|first1=Juliette|last2=Neuman|first2=Tricia|last3=Freed|first3=Meredith| website=KFF | date=22 September 2022 | url=https://www.kff.org/medicare/issue-brief/explaining-the-prescription-drug-provisions-in-the-inflation-reduction-act/ | access-date=19 January 2023}}</ref> by 2029)<ref name="Sachs 2022"/><ref name="Cutler p=e223630"/> and rebates from drug makers who [[Price gouging|price gouge]] – $281{{nbsp}}billion<ref name=":7" /><ref name="Sachs 2022">{{cite journal | title=Understanding The Democrats' Drug Pricing Package |last=Sachs|first=Rachel |journal=Health Affairs Forefront | date=10 August 2022 | url=https://www.healthaffairs.org/do/10.1377/forefront.20220810.661571/full/ |access-date=5 October 2022 }}</ref><ref name="Cutler p=e223630">{{cite journal | last=Cutler | first=David M. | title=Medicare Enters the Pharmaceutical Purchasing Business | journal=JAMA Health Forum | publisher=American Medical Association (AMA) | volume=3 | issue=9 | date=2022-09-01 | issn=2689-0186 | doi=10.1001/jamahealthforum.2022.3630 | page=e223630| pmid=36218929 | s2cid=252035393 | doi-access=free }}</ref>
* Imposing a selective 15% corporate minimum tax rate for companies with higher than $1{{nbsp}}billion of annual financial statement income – $222{{nbsp}}billion
* Increased tax enforcement – $181{{nbsp}}billion<ref name=":7" /><ref name=":3">{{Cite web |last=CFP® |first=Kate Dore |title=With 87,000 new agents, here's who the IRS may target for audits |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/08/09/with-87000-new-agents-heres-who-the-irs-may-target-for-audits.html |access-date=2022-08-10 |website=CNBC |date=August 9, 2022 |language=en}}</ref>
* Imposing a 1% excise tax on [[Share repurchase|stock buybacks]] – $74{{nbsp}}billion
* 2-year extension of the limitation on excess business losses – $53 billion<ref name=":7" />

In the same time period, it would spend this revenue on:<ref name="dem_sum" /><ref>{{Cite news |last=Shivaram |first=Deepa |date=2022-08-12 |title=Democrats passed a major climate, health and tax bill. Here's what's in it |language=en |work=NPR |url=https://www.npr.org/2022/08/07/1116190180/democrats-are-set-to-pass-a-major-climate-health-and-tax-bill-heres-whats-in-it |access-date=2022-08-12}}</ref>
* Addressing domestic [[energy security]] and [[climate change]], including funding for drought resiliency in western states – $391{{nbsp}}billion<ref name=":7" />
* Continuing for three more years the expansion of [[Affordable Care Act]] subsidies originally expanded under the [[American Rescue Plan Act of 2021]] – $64{{nbsp}}billion
* Changes to [[Medicare Part D]], low-income subsidies, vaccine coverage, and insulin – $44 billion<ref name=":7" />
* Increased funding for the IRS for modernization and increased tax enforcement, including the hiring of up to 87,000 new IRS employees – $80{{nbsp}}billion<ref name=":3" /><ref>{{Cite news |title=Democrats' $80 billion wager: A bigger IRS will be a better IRS |language=en-US |newspaper=Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2022/08/06/inflation-reduction-act-irs/ |access-date=2022-08-10 |issn=0190-8286}}</ref>

$663 billion of the law's climate action investments are embedded in the federal tax code.<ref name="Bravender 2022">Up from the CBO's original projection of $270 billion. {{cite web | title=Greenwire: Podesta, IRS get to work on climate law's tax incentives | website=Politico Pro|last=Bravender|first=Robyn | date=5 October 2022 | url=https://subscriber.politicopro.com/article/eenews/2022/10/05/podesta-irs-get-to-work-on-climate-laws-tax-incentives-00060477 | access-date=8 October 2022}}</ref> Of these, [[McKinsey & Company]] estimates that roughly half the tax savings will go to corporations.<ref name="McKinsey 2022">{{cite web | last1=Kumar | first1=Adi | last2=O'Rourke | first2=Sara Slayton | last3=Mehta | first3=Nehal | last4=Badlam | first4=Justin | last5=Silvis | first5=Julia | last6=Cox | first6=Jared | title=The Inflation Reduction Act: Here's what's in it | website=McKinsey & Company | date=October 24, 2022 | url=https://www.mckinsey.com/industries/public-sector/our-insights/the-inflation-reduction-act-heres-whats-in-it | access-date=October 24, 2024}}</ref> As part of the overall investment into [[clean energy]], the law created a [[green bank]],<ref name="Cherny 2022"/><ref name="EESI 2022"/><ref name="EPA About Page"/> extended the solar investment tax credit for 10 years<ref>{{cite web|last=Stevens|first=Pippa|date=July 28, 2022|title=Solar stocks jump as Schumer, Manchin announce climate spending deal |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/07/28/solar-stocks-jump-as-schumer-manchin-announce-climate-spending-deal.html |website=CNBC |access-date=August 7, 2022}}</ref> and invested $30 billion in [[nuclear power]] (including $700 million for high-assay low [[Enrichment of uranium|enrichment uranium]] (HALEU) fuel source research and development and $150 million for new Office of Nuclear Energy research)<ref>{{Cite web |last=Clifford |first=Catherine |date=2022-08-22 |title=What the climate bill does for the nuclear industry |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/08/22/what-the-climate-bill-does-for-the-nuclear-industry.html |access-date=2023-07-09 |website=CNBC |language=en}}</ref> and $760 million in facilitating electric power transmission siting reform.<ref name="The White House guidebook 2023">{{cite web | title=Inflation Reduction Act Guidebook | website=The White House |pages=34, 182–183 |date=January 2023 | url= https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/wp-content/uploads/2022/12/Inflation-Reduction-Act-Guidebook.pdf | access-date=May 2, 2024}}</ref> It also invests $12 billion in electric vehicle incentives, $14 billion in home energy efficiency upgrades, $22 billion in home energy supply improvements, and $37 billion in advanced manufacturing.<ref name="Hank Green infographic">{{Cite AV media|people=Green, Hank|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qw5zzrOpo2s&t=650s|date=August 12, 2022|access-date=October 6, 2022|publisher=Vlogbrothers|type=YouTube video|location=Missoula, Montana|title=The Biggest Climate Bill of Your Life - But What does it DO?|time=10 minutes 50 seconds}}</ref><ref name="dem_sum"/> (The latter amount includes $5.46 billion for a DOE program for zero-emissions industrial tech demonstrations,<ref name="Energy.gov IDP announcement 2023">{{cite web | title=Biden-Harris Administration Announces $6 Billion To Drastically Reduce Industrial Emissions and Create Healthier Communities | website=Energy.gov | date=March 8, 2023 | url=https://www.energy.gov/articles/biden-harris-administration-announces-6-billion-drastically-reduce-industrial-emissions | access-date=May 26, 2023}}</ref><ref name="Dayen 2023">{{cite web | last=Dayen | first=David | author-link=David Dayen | title=A Liberalism That Builds Power | website=The American Prospect | date=May 25, 2023 | url=https://prospect.org/api/content/4746efa0-fa57-11ed-a84c-12163087a831/ | access-date=May 26, 2023}}</ref> $10 billion for the renewed 48C tax credit,<ref>{{USC|26|48C}}</ref> and more than $5 billion to the [[United States Department of Transportation|USDOT]] and [[General Services Administration|GSA]] to lower [[embedded emissions]] in procurement.<ref name="BGA Fact Sheet">{{cite web|publisher=BlueGreen Alliance|title=Fact Sheet: Clean Manufacturing Investments in the Inflation Reduction Act|access-date=May 26, 2022|date=August 24, 2022|url=https://www.bluegreenalliance.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/BGA-IRA-Manufacturing-Investments-Factsheet-82422-FINAL.pdf}}</ref>) $19.5 billion goes to investments in [[climate-smart agriculture]], more than $5 billion goes to revising remediation programs for those affected by discriminatory [[USDA]] lending practices, $5 billion goes to forest protection and [[urban heat island]] reductions, and nearly $3 billion goes to coastal habitat protection.<ref name="DOE/OP-0018">{{cite report|title=The Inflation Reduction Act Drives Significant Emissions Reductions and Positions America to Reach Our Climate Goals|url=https://www.energy.gov/sites/default/files/2022-08/8.18%20InflationReductionAct_Factsheet_Final.pdf|publisher=United States Department of Energy Office of Policy|date=August 2022|archive-date=November 24, 2022|access-date=October 5, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221124184203/https://www.energy.gov/sites/default/files/2022-08/8.18%20InflationReductionAct_Factsheet_Final.pdf|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="Philpott 2022">{{cite magazine | last=Philpott | first=Tom | title=How the Inflation Reduction Act Affects Food and Agriculture | magazine=Wired | date=20 August 2022 | url=https://www.wired.com/story/how-the-inflation-reduction-act-affects-food-and-agriculture/ | access-date=20 October 2022}}</ref><ref name="CRS IN11978">{{cite report |author=Jim Monke |author2=Kelsi Bracmort |author3=Megan Stubbs |author4=Katie Hoover |date=August 10, 2022 |title=Inflation Reduction Act: Agricultural Conservation and Credit, Renewable Energy, and Forestry |number=IN11978|url=https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/IN/IN11978 |publisher=Congressional Research Service|access-date=August 10, 2023}}</ref> Lastly, the act gives $1.005 billion to various agencies to increase staffing levels and kickstart permitting reform, particularly of environmental reviews.<ref name="The White House guidebook 2023"/>

Alternatively, the act's climate investments can be summarized as follows: $196–372 billion in energy, $67–183 billion in manufacturing, $28–48 billion in building retrofits and energy efficiency, $23–436 billion in transportation, $22–26 billion in environmental justice, land use, air pollution reduction and/or resilience, and $3–21 billion in agriculture.<ref name="Beachy 2022">{{cite web | last=Beachy|first=Ben|title=Reconciliation: Climate, Energy, and Environmental Justice Investments | website=Google Sheets | date=August 12, 2022 | url=https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1iHbr4Ph3cD7r30Z093pWUMV2P1kLhywAeW2UilVp09U/edit| access-date=May 24, 2023}}</ref><ref name="BCG 2022-08-16"/><ref name="Zentouro 2023 spending areas"/><ref name=":9">{{Cite web |date=2023-04-27 |title=Update: Budgetary Cost of Climate and energy provisions in the Inflation Reduction Act |url=https://budgetmodel.wharton.upenn.edu/estimates/2023/4/27/update-cost-climate-and-energy-inflation-reduction-act |access-date=2023-06-12 |website=Penn Wharton Budget Model |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="Thomas 2023"/><ref name="Credit Suisse 2022"/>

However, the law also requires that for federal lands, oil and gas auctions take place before wind and solar leasing, even as it provides for the Interior Department to raise royalty rates on oil and gas projects from 12.5% to 16.7%.<ref name="Hart 2023">{{cite web | last=Hart | first=Sarah | title=Potential Impacts of the IRA's Onshore Energy Leasing Provisions | website=Harvard Law School - Environmental & Energy Law Program | date=March 24, 2023 | url=https://eelp.law.harvard.edu/2023/03/ira-onshore-leasing/ | access-date=May 16, 2024 | archive-date=May 16, 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240516055405/https://eelp.law.harvard.edu/2023/03/ira-onshore-leasing/ }}</ref><ref name="Groom 2024">{{cite web | last=Groom | first=Nichola | title=US finalizes higher fees for oil and gas companies on federal lands | website=Reuters | date=April 12, 2024 | url=https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/us-finalizes-big-reforms-federal-oil-gas-drilling-2024-04-12/ | access-date=May 16, 2024}}</ref>

The law contained provisions that cap insulin costs at $35/month and will cap out-of-pocket drug costs at $2,000 for people on [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]], among other provisions.<ref name="dem_sum" /><ref name="Sachs 2022"/><ref name="Cutler p=e223630"/> The law also extended Affordable Care Act health insurance exchange subsidies, preventing people making above four times the poverty line from ineligibility for the exchanges.

Several provisions in the initial deal between Schumer and Manchin were changed after negotiations with Senator Sinema: a provision narrowing the [[Carried interest in the United States|carried interest]] loophole was dropped, a 1% excise tax on stock buybacks was added, manufacturing exceptions were added to the corporate minimum tax (itself having been crafted by [[Elizabeth Warren]] and refined by [[Lawrence Summers]] and Natasha Sarin),<ref name="Senator Warren press release 2021">{{cite web | title=Senators Warren and King, Representative Beyer Announce Legislation To Prevent The Biggest And Most Profitable Corporations From Paying Nothing In Federal Taxes | website=U.S. Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts | date=August 9, 2021 | url=https://www.warren.senate.gov/newsroom/press-releases/senators-warren-and-king-representative-beyer-announce-legislation-to-prevent-the-biggest-and-most-profitable-corporations-from-paying-nothing-in-federal-taxes | access-date=May 3, 2024}}</ref><ref name="White 2022">{{cite web | last=White | first=Ben | title=Larry Summers emerges as the unlikeliest Democratic hero | website=POLITICO | date=August 15, 2022 | url=https://www.politico.com/news/2022/08/15/larry-summers-emerges-as-the-unlikeliest-democratic-hero-00051433 | access-date=May 3, 2024}}</ref> and funding for drought relief for western states was added.<ref name=":2">{{cite web |last=Tully-Mcmanus |first=Katherine |date=2022-08-05 |title=Sinema's tax tweaks |url=https://politi.co/3zZv8b9 |access-date=2022-08-05 |website=Politico}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Cochrane |first=Emily |date=2022-08-05 |title=Sinema Agrees to Climate and Tax Deal, Clearing the Way for Votes |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/08/04/us/politics/sinema-inflation-reduction-act.html |access-date=2022-08-05 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Bolton |first=Alexander |date=2022-08-05 |title=Sinema announces deal with Schumer on taxes and climate |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/3588988-sinema-announces-deal-with-schumer-on-taxes-and-climate/ |access-date=2022-08-05 |website=The Hill}}</ref>

== Projected impacts==

=== Economic ===

==== Short-term inflation ====
The [[Congressional Budget Office]]<ref>{{Cite web |date=August 5, 2022 |title=Inflation Reduction Act: Comparing CBO and PWBM Estimates |url=https://budgetmodel.wharton.upenn.edu/issues/2022/8/5/inflation-reduction-act-comparing-cbo-and-pwbm-estimates |access-date=2022-08-11 |website=Penn Wharton Budget Model |language=en-US}}</ref> and others<ref>{{Cite web |date=August 12, 2022 |title=Senate-Passed Inflation Reduction Act: Estimates of Budgetary and Macroeconomic Effects |url=https://budgetmodel.wharton.upenn.edu/issues/2022/8/12/senate-passed-inflation-reduction-act |access-date=2022-08-15 |website=[[Penn Wharton Budget Model]] |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=":14" /> estimated that the act would have no statistically significant effect on inflation in 2022 and 2023.

==== Medium-term inflation ====
[[File:Inflation-reduction-act-50.png|thumb|right|330px|Inflation Reduction Act summary graphic from the [[White House]]]]
The nonpartisan [[Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget]],<ref name="CRFB 1">{{cite web |date=July 28, 2022 |title=What's In the Inflation Reduction Act? |url=https://www.crfb.org/blogs/whats-inflation-reduction-act |access-date=July 30, 2022 |publisher=Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget |quote=deficit reduction, along with other elements of the bill, is likely to reduce inflationary pressures and thus reduce the risk of a possible recession.}}</ref> alongside the Swiss business lobbying group [[World Economic Forum]]<ref name=":4" /> analyzed the act and concluded that the "deficit reduction, along with other elements of the bill, is likely to reduce inflationary pressures and thus reduce the risk of a possible recession." It further estimates that the act would reduce the [[National debt of the United States|federal deficit]] by $1.9{{nbsp}}trillion over a 20-year period.<ref name="CRFB 2">{{cite web |date=August 3, 2022 |title=IRA Saves Almost $2 Trillion Over Two Decades |url=https://www.crfb.org/blogs/ira-saves-almost-2-trillion-over-two-decades |access-date=2022-08-04 |publisher=Committee for a Responsible Federal Budget}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=August 2024}}

Writing in ''[[Vox Media|Vox]],'' Rebecca Leber cites economists who predict that the act will make the US less exposed to [[fossilflation]], which is inflation caused by reliance on [[Volatility (finance)|volatile]] [[commodity market]]s like the ones for [[fossil fuel]]s.<ref name=":14" />

[[Gernot Wagner]] argues that the benefits of the act will likely not be felt before the 2024 election, but that the act is a great long-term strategy to decouple from volatile energy markets that drive inflation and that the act will reduce inflation over the medium to long-term.<ref name=":133">{{Cite news |last=Wagner |first=Gernot |date=2022-08-12 |title=Opinion {{!}} Greening Your Home Will Be Cheaper, but Expect Growing Pains |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/08/12/opinion/environment/climate-bill-house-inflation-reduction.html |access-date=2024-08-18 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=":142">{{Cite web |last=Wagner |first=Gernot |date=February 23, 2024 |title=The Ukraine War Blew Up the World's Energy Economy |url=https://heatmap.news/economy/ukraine-war-global-energy |access-date=2024-08-18 |website=heatmap.news |language=en |quote=Throughout the most recent U.S. spike in inflation in 2022, the energy category alone was responsible for around half of total inflation. And that's just counting the direct effects. Indirectly, a good portion of the food price increases ever since are also due to higher energy costs. If the farmer pays more to harvest the crop, soon those commodity prices increase as well. Of course, it isn't all fossil fuels...The IRA has not and will not cut inflation overnight. But that fight is indeed a big part of the bill's legacy: Play the long game of tackling all three types of climate-related inflation — fossilflation, climateflation, and greenflation — at their very core, and indeed justify the law's name.}}</ref><ref name=":14" />

==== Deficit reduction estimates ====
The World Economic Forum estimates that the act would prevent the [[National debt of the United States|federal debt]] from growing by $1.9{{nbsp}}trillion over a 20-year period.<ref name="CRFB 2" />

Former Biden administration staffers Natasha Sarin and Mark Mazur found that the act's investment in IRS tax collection would have increased revenues by $560 billion over 10 years before the Fiscal Responsibility Act's changes, and would increase revenues by $280 billion after them instead, though both findings were still much more than the CBO's projections.<ref name="Sarin and Mazur">{{cite web | last1=Sarin | first1=Natasha|last2=Mazur|first2=Mark | title=The Inflation Reduction Act's Impact on Tax Compliance and Fiscal Sustainability | website=Tax Notes | date=February 16, 2024 | url=https://www.taxnotes.com/featured-analysis/inflation-reduction-acts-impact-tax-compliance-and-fiscal-sustainability/2024/02/16/7j509 | access-date=September 21, 2024}}</ref>

==== Jobs estimates ====
A [[University of Massachusetts]] study projects that the law will generate 912,000 jobs per year.<ref name="CRFB 2" />

Modeling by the group [[Energy Innovation]], a nonpartisan energy and climate think tank, estimated that the law would lead to the creation of 1.4 million to 1.5 million additional jobs and increase the GDP 0.84–0.88% by 2030.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Adler |first=Ben |date=August 2, 2022 |title=Climate change bill would cut U.S. air pollution deaths by up to 3,900 per year, study finds |url=https://news.yahoo.com/climate-change-bill-would-cut-us-air-pollution-deaths-by-up-to-3900-per-year-study-finds-191755579.html |access-date=2022-08-31 |website=[[Yahoo News]] |language=en-US}}</ref>

The climate think tank [[Rocky Mountain Institute]] estimated that if businesses and consumers take sufficient advantage of the act's provisions to meet national climate goals, Texas would see investments of $131 billion creating 116,000 jobs, [[California]] would see $117 billion creating 140,000 jobs, [[Florida]] $62 billion creating 85,000 jobs and [[Illinois]] $38 billion creating 42,000 jobs.<ref name="RMI 2023">{{cite web |last1=Mills |first1=Ryan |last2=Aggarwal |first2=Ashna |last3=Corvidae |first3=Jacob |last4=Jaglom-Kurtz |first4=Wendy |date=February 6, 2023 |title=The Economic Tides Just Turned for States |url=https://rmi.org/economic-tides-just-turned-for-states/ |access-date=March 10, 2023 |website=RMI}}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=August 2024}} The same analysis notes that the states seeing the four largest per capita investments from the act, ranging between roughly $7,000 and $12,000, would be [[Wyoming]], [[North Dakota]], [[West Virginia]], and [[Louisiana]], all Republican states.<ref name="RMI 2023" /><ref name="Milman 2023">{{cite web |last=Milman |first=Oliver |date=February 22, 2023 |title=Republicans in the US 'battery belt' embrace Biden's climate spending |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/feb/22/climate-spending-republican-states-clean-energy-funding |access-date=March 10, 2023 |website=the Guardian}}</ref>

E2 projects 74,181 jobs and an estimated $86,320,800,000 in investments. That will entail 210 projects in 38 states.<ref name="E2">{{cite web |title=E2 Job Impact |url=https://e2.org/reports/clean-economy-works-2023/ |website=E2|date=August 14, 2023 }}</ref>{{Primary source inline|date=August 2024}}

=== Energy and climate change ===
====Climate action's fiscal impact====
The Inflation Reduction Act is the largest piece of federal legislation ever to address [[climate change]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Princeton energy and climate experts weigh in on the impact of the Inflation Reduction Act |url=https://www.princeton.edu/news/2022/08/25/princeton-energy-and-climate-experts-weigh-impact-inflation-reduction-act |publisher=Princeton University |access-date=27 August 2022}}</ref> According to the CBO and JCT, it will invest $783 billion in provisions relating to energy security and climate change.<ref name=":7" /> This includes $663 billion in tax incentives, and $27 billion for a [[green bank]] created by amending the [[Clean Air Act (United States)|Clean Air Act]].<ref name="Morgan Lewis 2022">{{cite web | title=Inflation Reduction Act Creates $27B 'Green Bank' Fund for Clean Energy Projects, but False Claims Risks Exist | last1=Avery|first1=W. Barron A.|last2=McCarthy|first2=Ryan A.|last3=Lorenzo|first3=Sarah-Jane|website=Morgan Lewis | date=August 16, 2022 | url=https://www.morganlewis.com/pubs/2022/08/inflation-reduction-act-creates-27b-green-bank-fund-for-clean-energy-projects-but-false-claims-risks-exist | access-date=October 22, 2022}}</ref><ref name="Burr & Forman LLP 2022">{{cite web | title=Three Ways the Inflation Reduction Act Advances Green Banking |last1=Penny|first1=William|last2=Snow|first2=Ed| website=Burr & Forman LLP | date=August 19, 2022 | url=https://www.burr.com/newsroom/articles/three-ways-the-inflation-reduction-act-advances-green-banking | access-date=October 22, 2022}}</ref><ref name="Cherny 2022">{{cite web | last=Cherny | first=Andrei | title=Commentary: This little-discussed provision in the Inflation Reduction Act just established the world's largest green lending program | website=Fortune | date=August 22, 2022 | url=https://fortune.com/2022/08/22/climate-inflation-reduction-act-national-green-bank-environment-biden-andrei-cherny/ | access-date=October 22, 2022}}</ref> However, other forecasts differ from the CBO's and JCT's reports. A report by [[Credit Suisse]] projects that the total climate spending in the act would be $800 billion,<ref name="Thomas 2023"/><ref name="Credit Suisse 2022">Liu, Alex; {{cite web | title=US Inflation Reduction Act: A catalyst for climate action |last1=Jiang|first1=Betty|last2=Mandloi|first2=Maheep|last3=Carlson|first3=Richard |last4=Hope|first4=Matt |last5=Ziffer|first5=Mike|last6=Campanella|first6=Nick|last7=Rosa|first7=Ariel|last8=Walsh|first8=John|last9=Kuske |first9=Andrew|last10=Tse|first10=Horace |last11=Kim|first11=Sang Uk|last12=Quiroga|first12=Vanessa |last13=Roberts|first13=John |last14=Chigumira|first14=Danielle |last15=Okusanya|first15=Tayo|last16=Oppenheim |first16=Dan|last17=Freshney|first17=Mark|last18=Leonard|first18=Christopher|last19=Woodworth|first19=Curt |last20=Abrams|first20=Randy|website=Credit Suisse | date=November 30, 2022 | url=https://www.credit-suisse.com/about-us-news/en/articles/news-and-expertise/us-inflation-reduction-act-a-catalyst-for-climate-action-202211.html | access-date=August 29, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Ultimate Public Climate Spending Spurred by Inflation Reduction Act Could be Over $800 Billion: Credit Suisse {{!}} American Public Power Association |url=https://www.publicpower.org/periodical/article/ultimate-public-climate-spending-spurred-inflation-reduction-act-could-be-over-800-billion-credit |access-date=2022-12-02 |website=www.publicpower.org}}</ref> [[Goldman Sachs]] predicts a total of $1.2 trillion, the [[Wharton School|Penn Wharton]] Budget Model predicts $1.045 trillion, and an analysis by the [[Brookings Institution]] finds a central case of $902 billion.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2023-03-23 |title=Goldman Sees Biden's Clean-Energy Law Costing US $1.2 Trillion |language=en |work=Bloomberg.com |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-03-23/goldman-sees-biden-s-clean-energy-law-costing-us-1-2-trillion |access-date=2023-03-26}}</ref><ref name=":9" /><ref>{{Cite web |author1=John Bistline |author2=Neil R. Mehrotra |author3=Catherine Wolfram |date=2023-03-30 |title=Economic implications of the climate provisions of the Inflation Reduction Act |url=https://www.brookings.edu/bpea-articles/economic-implications-of-the-climate-provisions-of-the-inflation-reduction-act/ |access-date=2023-06-12 |website=Brookings |language=en-US}}</ref>

====Assessments of spending by area====
The summary provided by Senate Democrats identifies primary goals as driving down consumer energy costs, increasing [[energy security]], and reducing [[greenhouse gas emissions]], with an emphasis on neutral treatment of technology choice for the energy tax credits, as described by Senator [[Ron Wyden]].<ref name="Dayen on Wyden 2022"/><ref name="Weissmann 2023"/> According to science communicator [[Hank Green]], the largest allocation areas are: $128 billion for [[renewable energy]] and [[grid energy storage]], $30 billion for [[nuclear power]], $12 billion for [[electric vehicle]] incentives, $14 billion for home energy efficiency upgrades, $22 billion for home energy supply improvements, and $37 billion for advanced manufacturing.<ref name="Hank Green infographic"/> (The latter amount includes $5.46 billion for a DOE program for zero-emissions industrial tech demonstrations,<ref name="Energy.gov IDP announcement 2023"/><ref name="Dayen 2023"/> $10 billion for the renewed 48C tax credit, and more than $5 billion to the [[United States Department of Transportation|USDOT]] and [[General Services Administration|GSA]] to lower [[embedded emissions]] in procurement.<ref name="BGA Fact Sheet"/>) An assortment of additional measures includes $32 billion for investments in rural economies, racial justice in farming, forestlands and coastal habitats, $3 billion in tax incentives for installing [[carbon capture and storage]] at existing power plants, $3 billion to electrify the [[USPS]] fleet, $3 billion to reconnect neighborhoods harmed by infrastructure potentially via [[freeway removal]], investments in [[direct air capture]], [[sustainable aviation fuel]], grants for [[high voltage]] [[electric power transmission]] and decarbonization of [[port]] equipment, [[garbage truck]]s, [[school bus]]es and [[local government]] fleets, and purchases of [[rural electric cooperative]] debt alongside other assistance to cooperatives.<ref name="Lechleitner 2022">{{cite web | last=Lechleitner | first=Liz | title=Electric and agricultural co-op leaders respond to passage of Inflation Reduction Act | website=NCBA CLUSA | date=August 23, 2022 | url=https://ncbaclusa.coop/blog/electric-and-agricultural-co-op-leaders-respond-to-passage-of-inflation-reduction-act/ | access-date=November 24, 2022}}</ref><ref name="DOE/OP-0018"/><ref name="Hank Green infographic"/><ref name="Philpott 2022"/><ref name="Stabenow one-pager"/><ref>{{USC|26|45Q}}</ref> Finally, over $1 billion is allotted to internal reform of agencies, particularly the Federal Permitting Improvement Steering Council (established by the [[Fixing America's Surface Transportation Act|FAST Act]] in 2015) and [[Council on Environmental Quality]] (established by the [[National Environmental Policy Act]] in 1969), to speed up environmental reviews for select climate-friendly projects.<ref name="The White House guidebook 2023"/>

Climate scientist Miriam Nielsen's alternative summary of the act's climate provisions, using much broader categories and rough estimates from Ben Beachy of the BlueGreen Alliance,<ref name="Beachy 2022"/> is as follows: $220 billion in energy, $67 billion in manufacturing, $48 billion in building retrofits and energy efficiency, $33 billion in transportation, $26 billion in environmental justice, land use and resilience, and $21 billion in agriculture.<ref name="Zentouro 2023 spending areas">{{cite AV media |people=Nielsen, Miriam |date=May 24, 2023 |language=English|type=YouTube video|time=3 minutes, 4 seconds|location=New York, NY |publisher=Zentouro|title=What's going on with the Inflation Reduction Act? | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g9x3UeYOJn4 | access-date=May 24, 2023}}</ref> Wharton's estimates, however, yield $372 billion in energy, $183 billion in manufacturing, $28 billion in building retrofits and energy efficiency, $436 billion in transportation, $22 billion in air pollution reduction, and $3 billion in agriculture.<ref name=":9" /> [[Boston Consulting Group]]'s executives project $196 billion from the act will be used for clean energy, $23 billion will be used for transportation, $17 billion for "clean technology" aimed at hard-to-abate emissions, and $71 billion for clean manufacturing, as well as $61 billion for other purposes.<ref name="BCG 2022-08-16">{{Cite web|url=https://media-publications.bcg.com/BCG-Executive-Perspectives-US-Inflation-Reduction-Act-16August2022.pdf|date=August 16, 2022|access-date=March 29, 2024|title=BCG Executive Perspectives: US Inflation Reduction Act: Climate & Energy Features and Potential Implications |website=Boston Consulting Group|last1=Baker|first1=Tom|last2=Dewar|first2=Alex|last3=Phillips|first3=Katherine|last4=Pieper|first4=Cornelius|last5=Seshadri|first5=Pattabi}}</ref> Credit Suisse projects at least $250 billion in advanced manufacturing tax credits and $326 billion in energy tax credits will be used.<ref name="Thomas 2023"/><ref name="Credit Suisse 2022"/>

In the specific area of direct cash payments from 2022 to 2031, the Joint Committee on Taxation forecast that of the Section 45X advanced manufacturing credit's total cost of $30.6 billion, direct cash payments would make up $14.7 billion. Of the $30 billion Section 45U nuclear power credit,<ref>{{USC|26|45U}}</ref> direct pay would make up $14.4 billion. Of the $13.2 Section 45V hydrogen credit, direct pay would make up $5.3 billion, of the $3.2 billion Section 45Q carbon sequestration credit, $1.6 billion, and of the $11.2 billion Section 45Y clean electricity production credit, $30 million.<ref name="Buffie 2024"/>

In April 2024, investment bank [[Evercore]] projected that over the next decade from that year, the share of production to investment tax credits would be 80%–20%, that credit market sizes for clean energy and for manufacturing would reach rough parity in 2028 before the former would outgrow the latter, and that the overall transferable tax credit market would jump from $47 billion a year in 2024 to over $100 billion a year in the 2030-2033 period, for a cumulative total of around $810 billion by 2033.<ref>{{cite report |last1=Bianchi|first1=Sarah|last2=Aks|first2=Matthew|date=April 28, 2024 |title=New Energy Tax Financing Market Poised to Scale as Treasury Issues Final Rules on How IRA Tax Credit Transfers Will Work – $47B in Potentially Transferable Tax Credits in 2024, Rising to Over $100B in 2030 |url=https://files.elfsightcdn.com/eafe4a4d-3436-495d-b748-5bdce62d911d/2e5f7cd5-9875-4b8e-927e-9ffd7e047fcf/Evercore-ISI-New-Energy-Tax-Finance-Market-Poised-to-Scale-3.pdf |publisher=Evercore |access-date=May 27, 2024|pages=2–4|series=Macro Notes}}</ref>

====Home energy assistance====
The act aims to decrease residential energy costs by focusing on improvements to home [[Efficient energy use|energy efficiency]]. Measures include $9 billion in home energy rebate programs that focus on improving access to energy efficient technologies, and 10 years of consumer [[tax credit]]s for the use of [[heat pump]]s, [[Rooftop solar power|rooftop solar]], and high-efficiency electric [[Heating, ventilation, and air conditioning#Energy efficiency|heating, ventilation, air conditioning]] and [[water heating]].

The act includes a 30% tax credit ($1,200 to $2,000 per year) and different types of rebates (reaching $14,000) for homeowners who will increase the energy efficiency of their homes. In some cases, all upgrade expenses will be returned.<ref name="Iacurci 2022">{{cite news |last1=Iacurci |first1=Greg |date=13 August 2022 |title=Consumers may qualify for up to $10,000 — or more — in climate tax breaks and rebates in the Inflation Reduction Act |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/08/13/how-to-qualify-for-inflation-reduction-act-climate-tax-breaks-rebates.html |access-date=8 September 2022 |agency=CNBC}}</ref><ref>{{USC|26|25D}} and {{USC|26|25C}}</ref>

The act expands select current incentives in a tier-based system, beginning in 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Rogers |first1=Jack|date=August 19, 2022|title=Inflation Reduction Act Doubles Tax Credits for Building Retrofits |url=https://www.globest.com/2022/08/19/inflation-reduction-act-doubles-tax-credits-for-building-retrofits/ |access-date=2022-08-21 |website=GlobeSt |language=en}}</ref> The act specifies that commercial buildings must update efficiency by 25%, compared to a reference building, to qualify for $0.50 per square foot of tax credit for the first tier, increasing to a maximum of $5.00 per square foot for the final tier.<ref>{{USC|26|179D}}</ref> The tax credits also extend to single and multi-family housing, requiring 50% less annual energy consumption compared to similar units.<ref name=":03">{{Cite web |title=The $369bn Climate Deal: America's Path To Climate Resilience - Renewables - United States |url=https://www.mofo.com/resources/insights/220810-369bn-climate-deal-americas-path-to-climate-resilience |access-date=2022-08-21 |website=Morrison Foerster}}</ref> Vincent Barnes, a senior vice president from Alliance to Save Energy in Washington, D.C, stated that these policies were meant to reduce energy costs and demand on the power grid.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ebeling |first=Ashlea |date=2022-08-08 |title=Inflation Reduction Act Is Big Win for Serial Green-Home Remodelers |language=en-US |work=Wall Street Journal |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/climate-and-tax-bill-is-big-win-for-serial-green-home-remodelers-11659971356 |access-date=2022-08-21 |issn=0099-9660}}</ref>

====Energy production====
There are also funds allocated to national [[Sustainable energy|clean energy]] production. This includes the continuation of the production tax credits (at least $30 billion)<ref>{{USC|26|45}}, {{USC|26|45X}} and {{USC|26|45Y}}</ref> and investment tax credit ($10 billion)<ref>{{USC|26|48}}, {{USC|26|48E}} and {{USC|26|48C}}</ref> toward clean energy manufacturing, including [[Solar power in the United States|solar power]], [[Wind power in the United States|wind power]], and [[grid energy storage]]. Modifications to these credits effectively allow the federal government to predictably and directly pay [[utility cooperative]]s, state and local governments, nonprofits and [[Public utility|publicly-owned utilities]] without them needing to attract investment firms, in a manner similar to the [[Earned Income Tax Credit]].<ref name="Cooper public power 2022">{{cite web | last=Cooper | first=Ryan | title=The Inflation Reduction Act's Quiet Revolution on Public Power | website=The American Prospect | date=August 18, 2022 | url=https://prospect.org/environment/inflation-reduction-acts-quiet-revolution-on-public-power/ | access-date=June 6, 2023}}</ref><ref name="Buffie 2024"/>

====Hydrogen====
The act changes the Section 45V tax credit to offer increased percentages to [[green hydrogen]] and [[Hydrogen production#Environmental impact|pink hydrogen]] producers for each kilogram produced via [[electrolysis of water]], allowing 100 percent coverage for very low-carbon methods, thus potentially enabling more than $100 billion<ref name="Thomas 2023">{{cite web | last=Thomas | first=Michael | title=The Climate Bill That Keeps On Giving | website=Distilled (Substack)| date=August 29, 2023 | url=https://www.distilled.earth/p/the-climate-bill-that-keeps-on-giving| access-date=August 29, 2023}}</ref><ref name="45V"/> in forgone revenue to go toward building the [[hydrogen economy]]. On December 22, 2023, the Treasury Department released its proposed guidance on eligibility. It mandates that most of these electrolyzers must be placed near new clean energy production sites (the principles of "geographic correlation"/"deliverability" and "additionality"/"new supply"), and run at the same time as peak supply periods (the principle of "hourly matching").<ref name="Jenkins December 22, 2023">{{cite web | title=Biden admin's long-awaited hydrogen rules are here | website=Canary Media | date=December 22, 2023 | url=https://www.canarymedia.com/articles/hydrogen/the-biden-administration-has-a-chance-to-do-clean-hydrogen-right | access-date=December 22, 2023}}</ref><ref name="Jenkins 2023">{{cite web | last=Jenkins|first=Jesse D.|title=The Biden administration has a chance to do clean hydrogen right | website=Canary Media | date=December 7, 2023 | url=https://www.canarymedia.com/articles/hydrogen/the-biden-administration-has-a-chance-to-do-clean-hydrogen-right | access-date=December 8, 2023}}</ref><ref name="Polly Martin 2023">{{cite web | author=Polly Martin| title=US likely to phase in strict rules for green hydrogen production, suggests White House advisor | website=Hydrogen insight | date=August 7, 2023 | url=https://www.hydrogeninsight.com/policy/us-likely-to-phase-in-strict-rules-for-green-hydrogen-production-suggests-white-house-advisor/2-1-1497384| access-date=December 8, 2023}}</ref><ref name="Stokes Op-Ed to The New York Times 2023">{{cite web | title=Opinion: Before We Invest Billions in This Clean Fuel, Let's Make Sure It's Actually Clean|last=Stokes|first=Leah C.| website=The New York Times | date=April 14, 2023 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/04/14/opinion/hydrogen-fuel-tax-credit-climate-change.html | access-date=August 25, 2023}}</ref><ref name="Meyer Op-Ed to The New York Times 2023">{{cite web | title=Opinion: A Huge, Uncharted Experiment on the U.S. Economy is About to Begin |last=Meyer|first=Robinson| website=The New York Times | date=February 12, 2023 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/02/12/opinion/economy-ira-infrastructure-clean-energy.html | access-date=August 25, 2023}}</ref><ref name="45V">{{USC|26|45V}}</ref>

====Transportation====
The act amended the $7,500 Section 30D tax credit<ref>{{USC|26|30D}}</ref> for the purchase of new [[electric vehicle]]s to two $3,750 credits based on whether or not the vehicle's critical mineral and battery component supply chains are located in countries with a free trade agreement with the United States and North America, respectively. These were designed to simultaneously continue to incentivize electric vehicle adoption while also encouraging manufacturers to use and shift their supply chains to 'friendly' nations.<ref name=alc>{{Cite journal |last=Cheng |first=Anthony L. |last2=Fuchs |first2=Erica R. H. |last3=Michalek |first3=Jeremy J. |date=December 2024 |title=US industrial policy may reduce electric vehicle battery supply chain vulnerabilities and influence technology choice |url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41560-024-01649-w |journal=Nature Energy |language=en |volume=9 |issue=12 |pages=1561–1570 |doi=10.1038/s41560-024-01649-w |issn=2058-7546|url-access=subscription }}</ref> Additionally, a new $4,000 Section 25E tax credit<ref>{{USC|26|25E}}</ref> was allocated toward the purchase of used electric vehicles, in an effort to increase low- and middle-income access to this technology.<ref name=":04">{{Cite web |last=Democrats |first=Senate |date=July 27, 2022 |title=Summary of the Energy Security and Climate Change Investments in the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022 |url=https://www.democrats.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/summary_of_the_energy_security_and_climate_change_investments_in_the_inflation_reduction_act_of_2022.pdf |access-date=August 22, 2022 |website=Senate Democrats}}</ref> A further, new Section 45W credit offered $7,500 for commercial vehicles weighing under 14,000 pounds and $40,000 weighing over,<ref>{{USC|26|45W}}</ref> which was interpreted to also include electric vehicle sold under lease.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The Tax Credit Exception for Leased Electric Vehicles |url=https://www.congress.gov/crs-product/IF12603 |access-date=2025-05-09 |website=www.congress.gov}}</ref> These credits were projected to lead to an average of $500 in savings on energy spending for every family that receives the maximal benefit of these incentives.<ref>{{Cite web |last=House |first=The White |date=2022-08-15 |title=BY THE NUMBERS: The Inflation Reduction Act |url=https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2022/08/15/by-the-numbers-the-inflation-reduction-act/ |access-date=2022-08-23 |website=The White House |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="Iacurci 2022" /> Many of these incentives have since been cancelled due to the passage of the [[One Big Beautiful Bill Act]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Domonoske |first=Camila |date=2025-09-30 |title=EV sales surge in the U.S. ahead of Sept. 30 tax credit deadline |url=https://www.npr.org/2025/09/30/nx-s1-5557153/ev-tax-credit-sales-spike |access-date=2026-04-14 |work=NPR |language=en}}</ref>

The act allocates $3 billion for helping disadvantaged communities with [[sustainable transportation]] matters, including reconnecting communities separated by transport infrastructure, assuring safe and affordable transportation "and community engagement activities".<ref name=":04"/> This should improve [[transit-oriented development]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Fact Sheet: Inflation Reduction Act Advances Environmental Justice |url=https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2022/08/17/fact-sheet-inflation-reduction-act-advances-environmental-justice/ |website=The White House |date=August 17, 2022 |access-date=14 September 2022}}</ref> Projects improving connectivity and [[walkability]] in these neighborhoods can get grants reaching 80–100% of the overall cost.<ref>{{cite web |title=How States and Cities Can Benefit From Climate Investments in the Inflation Reduction Act |url=https://www.americanprogress.org/article/how-states-and-cities-can-benefit-from-climate-investments-in-the-inflation-reduction-act/ |website=Center for American Progress |date=August 25, 2022 |access-date=14 September 2022}}</ref> The act also supports [[biking]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Banayan |first1=Noa |title=What IS in the Inflation Reduction Act for Bikes? |url=https://www.peopleforbikes.org/news/what-is-in-the-inflation-reduction-act-for-bikes |website=People for Bikes |access-date=14 September 2022}}</ref>

The act encourages [[sustainable aviation fuel]] producers to make more, through the Section 40B and 6426 tax credits<ref>{{USC|26|40B}} and {{USC|26|6426}}</ref> that give them $1.25 to $1.75 per gallon of fuel produced through December 2024. The act also includes a replacement credit called Section 45Z, to run from January 2025 through December 2028.<ref>{{USC|26|45Z}}</ref><ref name="Gallucci May 6, 2024"/>

====Agriculture, forests, marine and rural development====
Some $14 billion of the clean energy package will go to rural areas, and include building [[biofuel]] infrastructure.<ref name=":04" /><ref name="Stabenow one-pager">[https://www.agriculture.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/ag_reconciliation_one-pager.pdf Senate Agriculture Committee one-pager, retrieved October 20, 2022]</ref> This includes $9.5 billion for a new grant program called Empowering Rural America, with cooperatives encouraged to apply during a window from July 31 to September 15, 2023.<ref>{{Cite web | title=Empowering Rural America New ERA Program | date=July 27, 2023|url=https://www.rd.usda.gov/new-energy-deployment/new-era-project-announcements |publisher=USDA| access-date=12 September 2023}}</ref>

The act also allocates funds for rural communities, racial and economic justice in farming, [[marine ecosystem]]s and [[Forests of the United States|forestland]], including $19.5 billion to invest in [[climate-smart agriculture]] (split into $8.45 billion for the [[Environmental Quality Incentives Program]], $4.95 billion for the Regional Conservation Partnership Program, $3.25 billion for the [[Conservation Security Program|Conservation Stewardship Program]], and $1.40 billion for the Agricultural [[Conservation Easement]] Program, $1 billion for conservation technical assistance, $300 million for a carbon sequestration and [[emission inventory]] program, and $100 million in administrative expenses), $5 billion to invest in [[forest conservation]] and [[urban tree]] planting (split into $2.15 billion for the [[National forest (United States)|National Forest System]] and $2.75 billion for other forests including in urban areas), $3.1 billion to help farmers with high-risk operations caused by USDA-backed loans, $2.6 billion to protect and restore [[coastal habitats]], and $2.2 billion to redress proven claims from [[socially disadvantaged farmers and ranchers]] of discrimination by the [[USDA]]'s lending programs, as well as "$125 million for technical assistance, outreach, and mediation; $250 million for land loss assistance, such as heirs' property and fractionated land; $250 million for agricultural education emphasizing scholarships and career development at [[Historically black colleges and universities|historically Black]], [[Tribal colleges and universities|tribal]], and [[Hispanic-serving institution|Hispanic]] colleges; and $10 million for equity commissions at USDA".<ref name="CRS IN11978"/><ref name=":04" /><ref name="DOE/OP-0018"/><ref name="Stabenow one-pager"/><ref name="Philpott 2022"/>

====Novel financing methods====
One $27 billion competitive grant program is a [[green bank]] called the Greenhouse Gas Reduction Fund, intended to capitalize smaller regional green banks.<ref name="Prospect 2023">{{cite web | last=Harris | first=Lee | title=Green Capital Feuds With Local Lenders Over National Climate Bank | website=The American Prospect | date=January 19, 2023 | url=https://prospect.org/environment/2023-01-19-green-capital-national-climate-bank/ | access-date=January 20, 2023}}</ref> The act established it by amending the [[Clean Air Act (United States)|Clean Air Act]]. The Fund has awarded $14 billion to a select few green banks nationwide for a broad variety of decarbonization investments, $6 billion to green banks in low-income and historically disadvantaged communities for similar investments, and $7 billion to state and local energy funds for [[Distributed generation|decentralized]] [[solar power]] in communities with no financing alternatives.<ref name="Morgan Lewis 2022"/><ref name="Burr & Forman LLP 2022"/><ref name="Cherny 2022"/><ref name="EESI 2022">{{cite web | last=Yañez-Barnuevo| first=Miguel | title=New Climate Law Jumpstarts Clean Energy Financing - Article | website=EESI | date=12 September 2022 | url=https://www.eesi.org/articles/view/new-climate-law-jumpstarts-clean-energy-financing | access-date=7 November 2022}}</ref><ref name="EPA About Page">{{Cite web|url=https://www.epa.gov/greenhouse-gas-reduction-fund/about-greenhouse-gas-reduction-fund|title=About the Greenhouse Gas Reduction Fund|website=United States Environmental Protection Agency|date=June 5, 2023|access-date=June 13, 2023}}</ref> The EPA set the deadline to apply for the first two award initiatives for October 12, 2023<ref name="US EPA July 14, 2023">{{cite web | title=Biden-Harris Administration Launches Historic $20 Billion in Grant Competitions to Create National Clean Financing Network as Part of Investing in America Agenda | website=US EPA | date=July 14, 2023 | url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/biden-harris-administration-launches-historic-20-billion-grant-competitions-create | access-date=August 14, 2023}}</ref> and the Solar for All initiative for September 26, 2023.<ref name="US EPA June 28, 2023">{{cite web | title=Biden-Harris Administration Launches $7 Billion Solar for All Grant Competition to Fund Residential Solar Programs that Lower Energy Costs for Families and Advance Environmental Justice Through Investing in America Agenda | website=US EPA | date=June 28, 2023 | url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/biden-harris-administration-launches-7-billion-solar-all-grant-competition-fund | access-date=August 14, 2023}}</ref>

[[McKinsey & Company]] estimated in April 2023 that the GGRF would leverage about $250 billion in private investments with its first $20 billion. They also made five recommendations on project governance and impact tracking to ensure the Fund's success.<ref name="Buehler Eis Kingsmill Levy 2023">{{cite web | last1=Buehler | first1=Kevin | last2=Eis | first2=Jason | last3=Kingsmill | first3=Nick | last4=Levy | first4=Cindy | title=Delivering impact from US green bank financing | website=McKinsey & Company | date=April 20, 2023 | url=https://www.mckinsey.com/capabilities/sustainability/our-insights/delivering-impact-from-us-green-bank-financing| access-date=April 5, 2024}}</ref>

The nonprofit group Clean Energy States Alliance, which serves as a knowledge clearinghouse for state energy programs, extrapolated from funding applications for Solar for All in 35 states, DC and Puerto Rico, and projected the projects could add 2.9 gigawatts in power and deliver $2 billion in savings to 711,068 low-income households; 37 percent of the $7 billion would likely go to community solar projects, 32 percent to single-family housing, and 26 percent to multi-family housing. The CESA also noted that many states had planned wide variations in their implementation of Solar for All.<ref name="Clean Energy States Alliance 2024">{{cite web |last1=Bourg-Meyer|first1=Vero|last2=Garrett|first2=Allie|title=Empowering Tomorrow: A Preview of States' Greenhouse Gas Reduction Fund Solar for All Programs | website=Clean Energy States Alliance | date=February 29, 2024 | url=https://www.cesa.org/wp-content/uploads/Empowering-Tomorrow-Solar-for-All.pdf | access-date=April 5, 2024}}</ref><ref name="Takemura Leap Day 2024">{{cite web | last=Takemura | first=Alison F. | title=Low-income communities will soon get $7 billion for local solar | website=Canary Media | date=February 29, 2024 | url=https://www.canarymedia.com/articles/solar/low-income-communities-will-soon-get-7-billion-for-local-solar | access-date=April 5, 2024}}</ref>

====Pollution and emissions====
