The act provided funds toward the [[Low-carbon economy|decarbonization]] of the U.S. economy, providing various [[tax credit]]s, [[Grant (money)|grants]] and [[loan]]s toward decarbonizing the [[Industry in the United States|industrial]] sector. Among these is a program to reduce [[methane emissions]] from production and transportation of [[Natural gas in the United States|natural gas]]. The act also provides for a focus on communities and [[environmental justice]] by providing several grants targeting historically marginalized and disadvantaged communities that have been disproportionally impacted by environmental pollution and climate change.<ref name=":04" /> 

Although its potential efficacy has been contested,<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Orford |first1=Adam |title = Overselling BIL and IRA| journal=Ecology Law Quarterly | date=2021 | volume=51 | issue=3|url = https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=4617527}}</ref> the act was intended to cut global greenhouse gas emissions by a level similar to "eliminating the annual planet-warming pollution of [[Climate change in France|France]] and [[Climate change in Germany|Germany]] combined" and to contribute to limiting the warming of the planet to 1.5 degrees [[Celsius]] – the target of the [[Paris Agreement]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rathi |first1=Akshat |last2=A Dlouhy |first2=Jennifer |title=Bill Gates and the Secret Push to Save Biden's Climate Bill |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2022-08-16/how-bill-gates-lobbied-to-save-the-climate-tax-bill-biden-just-signed |access-date=19 September 2022 |agency=Bloomberg |date=August 2022}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hirji |first1=Zahra |last2=Roston |first2=Eric |title=US Climate Bill Keeps Hope Alive for Halting Warming at 1.5°C |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-08-12/us-climate-bill-keeps-hope-alive-for-halting-warming-at-1-5-c#xj4y7vzkg |access-date=22 September 2022 |agency=Bloomberg |date=13 August 2022}}</ref> With the act and additional federal and state measures, the USA can fulfill its pledge in the Paris Agreement: 50% [[greenhouse gas emissions]] reductions by the year 2030.<ref name=Rhodium/><ref name="McGinn 2022">{{cite web | last=McGinn| first=Anna|website=Environmental and Energy Study Institute | title=What the Inflation Reduction Act Means for U.S. Engagement at the U.N. Climate Talks - Article | date=October 18, 2022 | url=https://www.eesi.org/articles/view/what-the-inflation-reduction-act-means-for-u.s-engagement-at-the-u.n-climate-talks | access-date=March 24, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Mahajan |first1=Megan |last2=Ashmoore |first2=Olivia |last3=Rissman |first3=Jeffrey |last4=Orvis |first4=Robbie |last5=Gopal |first5=Anand |title=Modeling the Inflation Reduction Act Using the Energy Policy Stimulator |date=August 2022 |publisher=Energy innovation |page=1 |url=https://energyinnovation.org/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Modeling-the-Inflation-Reduction-Act-with-the-US-Energy-Policy-Simulator_August.pdf |access-date=22 September 2022}}</ref>

An assessment by the Rhodium Group, an independent research firm, estimated it would reduce national greenhouse gas emissions 32–42% below 2005 levels by 2030, compared to 24–35% under current policy while reducing household energy costs and improving energy security.<ref name=Rhodium>{{Cite web |title=A Turning Point for US Climate Progress: Assessing the Climate and Clean Energy Provisions in the Inflation Reduction Act |url=https://rhg.com/research/climate-clean-energy-inflation-reduction-act/ |access-date=2022-08-16 |website=Rhodium Group |date=August 12, 2022 |language=en-US}}</ref> Furthermore, Rhodium Group projects that the nuclear provisions in the act are likely to "keep much, if not all" of [[Nuclear power in the United States|the nation's nuclear reactors]] that are at risk of retiring, estimated to be 22–38% of the fleet, online through the 2030s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Natter |first=Ari |date= August 3, 2022|title=Manchin Deal Tosses $30 Billion Lifeline to US Nuclear Reactors |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-08-03/machin-deal-tosses-30-billion-lifeline-to-us-nuclear-reactors |access-date=2022-08-04 |work=Bloomberg}}</ref>

A preliminary analysis by the REPEAT Project of [[Princeton University]] estimated that the investments made by the law would reduce net emissions 42% below 2005 levels, compared to 27% under current policies (including the [[Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act]]).<ref>{{Cite web |last=Ebbs |first=Stephanie |title=Experts explain how the Inflation Reduction Act helps fight climate change |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/experts-explain-inflation-reduction-act-helps-fight-climate/story?id=88100442 |access-date=2022-08-18 |website=ABC News |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=princeton.edu |date=August 4, 2022 |title=Preliminary Report: The Climate and Energy Impacts of the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022 |url=https://repeatproject.org/docs/REPEAT_IRA_Prelminary_Report_2022-08-12.pdf |access-date=2022-08-18 |website=repeatproject.org}}</ref>

The Energy Innovation group estimated the reduction of greenhouse gas emissions at 37–41% below 2005 levels in 2030, compared to 24% without the act.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web |title=Modeling The Inflation Reduction Act Using The Energy Policy Simulator |url=https://energyinnovation.org/publication/modeling-the-inflation-reduction-act-using-the-energy-policy-simulator/ |access-date=2022-08-01 |publisher=Energy Innovation}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Storrow |first=Benjamin |title=How Much Will the Climate Bill Reduce Emissions? It Depends |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/how-much-will-the-climate-bill-reduce-emissions-it-depends/ |access-date=2022-08-18 |website=Scientific American |language=en}}</ref> This estimate of the greenhouse gas emission reduction lines up with the figure provided by the act's authors which is a 40% reduction in carbon emissions relative to 2005 levels.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Newburger |first=Emma |title=Schumer-Manchin reconciliation bill has $369 billion to fight climate change — here are the details |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/07/27/schumer-manchin-reconciliation-bill-climate-change-provisions.html |access-date=2022-08-01 |website=CNBC|date=July 28, 2022 }}</ref>

Modeling from the nonpartisan research institution [[Resources for the Future]] indicates the act would decrease retail power costs by 5.2–6.7% over a ten-year period, resulting in savings of $170–220 per year for the average U.S. household. The modeling also predicts that the act would tend to stabilize electricity prices.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Retail Electricity Rates under the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022 |url=https://www.rff.org/publications/issue-briefs/retail-electricity-rates-under-the-inflation-reduction-act-of-2022/ |access-date=2022-08-06 |publisher=Resources for the Future}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Axios Generate, August 5, 2022 |url=https://www.axios.com/newsletters/axios-generate-90a5dde8-7916-4c69-967c-fe1f9d1665f8.html |access-date=2022-08-05 |website=Axios}}</ref> The act would help foster a tripling in the size of the American solar power industry and provide unprecedented investment security, according to a September 2022 report by the trade group [[Solar Energy Industries Association]].<ref name="Stevens 2022">{{cite web | last=Stevens | first=Pippa | title=Solar installations will triple by 2027 thanks to climate bill, report predicts | website=CNBC | date=8 September 2022 | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/09/08/solar-installations-will-nearly-triple-over-the-next-five-years-seia.html | access-date=29 October 2022}}</ref>

In reaction to the Supreme Court case ''[[West Virginia v. EPA]]'', which limited the EPA's authority to institute a program such as the Obama-era [[Clean Power Plan]], Title VI of the IRA amended the [[Clean Air Act (United States)|Clean Air Act]] to explicitly designate [[carbon dioxide]], [[hydrofluorocarbon]]s, [[methane]], [[nitrous oxide]], [[Fluorocarbon|perfluorocarbon]]s, and [[sulfur hexafluoride]] as air pollutants to unambiguously provide the EPA congressional authorization to [[Regulation of greenhouse gases under the Clean Air Act|regulate carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases]], as well as to promote renewable energy.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/08/22/climate/epa-supreme-court-pollution.html | title=Democrats Designed the Climate Law to be a Game Changer. Here's How | newspaper=The New York Times | date=August 22, 2022 | last1=Friedman | first1=Lisa }}</ref><ref>136 Stat. 2063, {{uspl|117|169}}</ref>

===Drug prices===
One of the most consequential aspects of this act is the increased negotiating power granted to Medicare. Before the enactment of the Inflation Reduction Act, Medicare was notably restricted in its ability to negotiate drug prices directly with pharmaceutical companies. This limitation often resulted in higher costs for both the program and its beneficiaries. With the new rule, Medicare now engages directly with drug manufacturers, aiming to secure more favorable pricing agreements. This development has the potential to significantly alter the landscape of drug pricing, especially for high-cost medications under Medicare Part D.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Sullivan |first=Sean D. |date=March 2023 |title=Medicare Drug Price Negotiation in the United States: Implications and Unanswered Questions |journal=Value in Health |volume=26 |issue=3 |pages=394–399 |doi=10.1016/j.jval.2022.11.015 |pmid=36503034 |s2cid=254522229 |issn=1098-3015|doi-access=free }}</ref> The Congressional Budget Office projects the [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] drug price negotiations will save the government $98.5 billion over the next decade.<ref name="CRFB 1"/><ref name="The New York Times IRA drug announcement 2023"/> The savings will be used to increase [[Medicare Part D]] benefits.<ref name="KFF 2022"/><ref>Thread by Stacie Dusetzina, health policy analyst at Vanderbilt University. {{Cite tweet|number=1696533545081250278|user=DusetzinaS|title=Are you feeling down because the drug that you take isn't on the list that @CMSGov just released for price negotiations in #PartD? FEAR NOT. You also get to benefit from negotiation. Let me explain how. 1/4}}</ref><ref name="Schwarz 2022">{{cite web | last=Schwarz | first=Casey | title=Part D Savings in the Inflation Reduction Act Set to Increase Over Time | website=Medicare Rights Center | date=August 25, 2022 | url=https://www.medicarerights.org/medicare-watch/2022/08/25/part-d-reforms-in-the-inflation-reduction-act-set-to-increase-over-time | access-date=August 30, 2023}}</ref> Together, these drugs amounted to more than $45 billion in Medicare Part D spending from June 2022 to May 2023.<ref name=Kansteiner>{{Cite web |last=Kansteiner |first=Fraiser |date=2023-08-29 |title=Drugs from J&J, Merck, Novartis, BMS and more set for first round of Medicare price negotiations: CMS |url=https://www.fiercepharma.com/pharma/medicare-unveils-list-10-drugs-set-price-negotiations-under-ira |access-date=2023-08-31}}</ref>

====First selected drugs====
In September 2023, Medicare announced the first 10 drugs selected for negotiations under the agency's drug price negotiation program. This list includes treatments for:

* Diabetes: [[Farxiga]], [[Fiasp]]/[[NovoLog]], [[Januvia]], [[Jardiance]]
* Blood diseases: [[Eliquis]], [[Xarelto]], [[Imbruvica]]
* Heart failure: [[Entresto]], [[Farxiga]]
* Psoriasis: [[Stelara]], [[Enbrel]]
* Rheumatoid arthritis: Enbrel
* Crohn's disease: Stelara<ref name="KFF September 2023">{{Cite web |last1=Cubanski |first1=Juliette |last2=Damico |first2=Anthony |last3=Published |first3=Tricia Neuman |date=2023-09-26 |title=How Medicare's New Drug Price Negotiation Program Could Expand Access to Selected Drugs |url=https://www.kff.org/medicare/issue-brief/how-medicares-new-drug-price-negotiation-program-could-expand-access-to-selected-drugs/ |access-date=2023-11-12 |website=KFF |language=en-US}}</ref><ref name="The New York Times IRA drug announcement 2023"/>

=== Taxes and distributional impact ===
[[File:20220826 Share of unpaid taxes, by income level - area chart, treemap - NYTimes - Dept of Treasury.svg|thumb|U.S. Treasury Department estimates of unpaid taxes indicate that over half of all unpaid taxes are attributable to the top 5% of earners.<ref name=NYTimes_20220826>{{cite news |last1=Lopez |first1=German |last2=Wu |first2=Ashley |title=Conspiracy Theories / How more funding for the I.R.S. became a political firestorm |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/08/26/briefing/conspiracy-irs-tax-agency-fraud.html |work=The New York Times |date=August 26, 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220826102900/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/08/26/briefing/conspiracy-irs-tax-agency-fraud.html |archive-date=August 26, 2022 |quote=Source: U.S. Department of Treasury; Estimates from 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>]]
Excerpts from the nonpartisan JCT indicated that the legislation might lead to increased payments on personal taxes for Americans of all incomes (an increase in $16.7{{nbsp}}billion for taxpayers earning less than $200,000 a year, $14.1{{nbsp}}billion for taxpayers earning between $200,000 and $500,000, and $23.5{{nbsp}}billion for taxpayers earning over $500,000). This calculation was based on the assumption that companies would indirectly pass on parts of the minimum corporate tax to employees, an assumption that was criticized by Steven M. Rosenthal, a senior fellow at the nonpartisan [[Tax Policy Center]] (TPC).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Diaz |first1=Daniella|last2=Luhby|first2=Tami |title=Republicans argue Manchin and Schumer's energy, health care deal will raise taxes, citing nonpartisan data |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/07/31/politics/republicans-economic-bill-taxes-inflation/index.html |access-date=2022-07-31 |work=CNN|date=July 31, 2022 }}</ref> Economist [[William G. Gale]], who is also co-director of the TPC, comments that it is important to consider that the calculations by the JCT did not take into account the provisions in the act that would extend premium tax credits for health plans for low- and middle-income taxpayers, provide households with tax credits for making their property more energy-efficient, and lower the price of prescription drugs.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-08-02 |title=Putting JCT's Score of the Inflation Reduction Act Into Context |url=https://www.taxpolicycenter.org/taxvox/putting-jcts-score-inflation-reduction-act-context |access-date=2022-08-03 |publisher=Tax Policy Center}}</ref>

The [[Tax Policy Center]] estimated that the bottom 80% tax filers by income would receive a net benefit, if ACA premium tax credits (subsidies) are included. The 80th-99th percentile would incur a small cost (0-0.1% increase in average federal tax rate) while the top 1% would incur a 0.2% increase. The costs mainly are imposed indirectly as corporations facing higher taxes may reduce the wage increases or levels for workers; individual tax rates were not changed.<ref>{{Cite news|title=The Inflation Reduction Act Primarily Impacts Top 1 Percent of Taxpayers|language=en-US|work=taxpolicycenter.org|url=https://www.taxpolicycenter.org/taxvox/inflation-reduction-act-primarily-impacts-top-1-percent-taxpayers|date=2022-08-11}}</ref>

== Implementation and results ==
The Biden administration's main overseer of the act's implementation was identified as [[John Podesta]].<ref name="Kuttner 2023"/><ref name = "nyt 2022-09-02">{{cite news|last=Friedman|first=Lisa|date=September 2, 2022|title=Biden, remaking climate team, picks John Podesta to guide spending|work=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/09/02/climate/john-podesta-climate-biden.html|access-date=September 5, 2022}}</ref> From 2022 to 2024, Podesta headed the [[White House Office on Clean Energy Innovation and Implementation]], established by Executive Order 14082 to implement the act.<ref>{{Cite executive order |post=President of the United States|number=14082|access-date=2024-10-09|language=American English|date=2022-09-12 |title=Executive Order on the Implementation of the Energy and Infrastructure Provisions of the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022 |url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/presidential-actions/2022/09/12/executive-order-on-the-implementation-of-the-energy-and-infrastructure-provisions-of-the-inflation-reduction-act-of-2022/}}</ref>

=== Economy ===
Research from climate policy analyst Jack Conness has revealed that $116 billion worth of 181 climate-friendly tech manufacturing investments within the United States, have been announced by companies since the passage of the Inflation Reduction Act, creating 99,500 projected jobs {{as of|2024|11|14|df=US|lc=y}}; when considered together with CHIPS Act investments, the total comes out to 218 projects worth $388 billion creating 135,800 jobs.<ref name="Conness 2023">{{cite web | title=Inflation Reduction Act (IRA) and CHIPS and Science Act Investments | website=Jack Conness | date=November 14, 2024 | url=https://www.jackconness.com/ira-chips-investments | access-date=November 15, 2024}}</ref>{{Update after|2024|12|31}} Conness found that due to the act's incentives, [[North Carolina]] would receive the individual project with the most money ($12.6 billion from [[Toyota]] in battery plants), while [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] would host the most projects (25), the most new jobs overall (14,343), and the largest dollar amount in overall investments ($16 billion, followed by North Carolina's $15.6 billion), and [[South Carolina]] would receive the individual project with the most jobs created (4,000 from [[Scout Motors]]). More of the act's dollars went to congressional districts with Republican winners in 2024 ($96 billion) than those with Democratic winners ($17 billion). 68 percent of the act's investments were in batteries, while electric vehicle investments made up 14 percent and solar investments made up 13 percent.<ref name="Conness 2023"/><ref name="Osaka 2023">{{cite news | last=Osaka | first=Shannon | title=The unlikely center of America's EV battery revolution | newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] | date=April 17, 2023 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/climate-environment/2023/04/17/georgia-evs-battery-belt/ | access-date=May 7, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motherjones.com/environment/2023/04/electrify-everything-scope-data/ |first=Jesse D.|last=Jenkins |title=What "Electrify Everything" Actually Looks Like|date=May 2023|access-date=May 8, 2023|website=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]}}</ref> Conness found that of the top 20 job-creating IRA-linked projects, only five had faced delays, and a majority would begin production by summer 2025.<ref name="Conness 2023"/>

In a November 2023 report the interest group Environmental Entrepreneurs and the research firm BW found 210 announced projects directly linked to the Inflation Reduction Act, in the first year since its signing. They stated that the projects would create nearly 403,000 jobs, more than 100,000 of which would be permanent.<ref name="E2 2023">{{cite web | title=Analysis: IRA-Related Clean Energy Projects To Create 403,000 Direct & Indirect Jobs; Add Billions To GDP | website=E2 | date=November 1, 2023 | url=https://e2.org/releases/analysis-ira-related-clean-energy-projects-to-create-403000-direct-add-billions-to-gdp/ | access-date=November 1, 2023}}</ref> According to editor in chief Jeff St. John of [[Canary Media]], "During the projects' construction phases, assumed to last five years from project announcement to completion, the report estimates the creation of 142,300 direct jobs, 55,900 [[indirect jobs]], and 105,300 jobs induced by the direct and indirect workers spending their wages." More than 185,000 of these jobs would be in electric vehicles, 48,795 would be in battery storage, 42,100 would be in solar and wind power, 21,322 would be in clean fuels, and nearly 5,600 would be in electric power transmission and distribution.<ref name="Canary Media E2 report 2023">{{cite web | title=How many jobs is the Inflation Reduction Act spurring? A lot | website=Canary Media | date=November 1, 2023 | url=https://www.canarymedia.com/articles/clean-energy-jobs/how-many-jobs-is-the-inflation-reduction-act-spurring-a-lot| access-date=November 1, 2023}}</ref> The authors project that the act would bring about "$156 billion added to U.S. GDP, $111 billion in new wages for workers, and more than $32 billion generated in tax revenue for federal, state, and local governments."<ref name="E2 2023"/> Environmental Entrepreneurs later found in August 2024 that $125.9 billion had been invested due to the act, and 334 new projects and 109,278 jobs had been created. 62,875 jobs had been created in electric vehicles, 24,835 in batteries and storage, 29,242 in solar and wind, 3,568 in clean fuels, and 2,348 in transmission and distribution.<ref name="E2 2024">{{cite web | title=Tracking New Clean Energy Projects Across U.S. | website=E2 | date=August 2024 | url=https://e2.org/announcements/ | access-date=August 14, 2024}}</ref>

In a video dated December 6, 2023, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' found the IRA and CaSA together catalyzed over $224 billion in investments and over 100,000 new jobs by the preceding July.<ref name="FT 2023">{{cite AV media | title=How Biden's Inflation Reduction Act changed the world| publisher=YouTube|time=3:27|location=London, UK|people=Financial Times| url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cfaubxeS5HU |date=December 6, 2023| access-date=January 3, 2024}}</ref>

The next day, the Rhodium Group–[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]] partnership Clean Investment Monitor put the July 2022–September 2023 investment total at $225 billion, most of it in electric vehicle supply, though it did not explicitly mention the act. Clean investment grew by 42 percent across that period. As a share of nationwide private investment, it grew from 3.4 percent to 4.9. The states that benefited the most were [[Nevada]], South Carolina, [[Arizona]], [[Tennessee]], and [[Montana]].<ref name="The Clean Investment Monitor 2023">{{cite web | title=Clean Investment Monitor: Q3 2023 Update | website=The Clean Investment Monitor | date=December 7, 2023| url=https://www.cleaninvestmentmonitor.org/reports/q3-2023-update | access-date=March 9, 2024}}</ref> Its second-anniversary report found the total from July 2022 to June 2024 was $493 billion, with EV supply taking a large share but solar and storage catching up, and much of it due to the act. Clean investment grew by 72 percent during that period. As a share of nationwide investment, it grew from 3.4 percent to 5.5. The states that benefited the most were Nevada, [[Wyoming]], Arizona, Tennessee, and Montana; the reporters found clean investment made up above 1 percent of Tennessee and Kentucky's respective GDPs.<ref name="The Clean Investment Monitor 2024">{{cite web | title=Tallying the Two-Year Impact of the IRA | website=The Clean Investment Monitor | date=August 9, 2024 | url=https://www.cleaninvestmentmonitor.org/reports/tallying-the-two-year-impact-of-the-inflation-reduction-act | access-date=August 17, 2024}}</ref> In March of that year, Treasury Department researchers used the Monitor's data to confirm that the act had spurred a monthly average of $4.5 billion in investments in 'energy communities' formerly dependent on fossil fuel extraction, $1 billion more than the average in the rest of the nation, and that 75 percent of the act's investments went to communities under the national median income.<ref name="Treasury report March 2024">{{cite web | title=The Inflation Reduction Act: A Place-Based Analysis, Updates from Q3 and Q4 2023 | website=U.S. Department of the Treasury | date=March 13, 2024 | url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/featured-stories/the-inflation-reduction-act-a-place-based-analysis-updates-from-q3-and-q4-2023 | access-date=August 27, 2024}}</ref>

In May 2025, journalist Michael Thomas found that due to the act "78% of new solar, wind, and battery projects have been built in Republican districts. 77.7 GW of clean energy capacity has been built in these districts since August 2022, bringing in roughly $100 billion in private investment." Of the top 30 House districts benefited by new clean energy gigawatts, 25 were Republican-held.<ref name="Thomas 2025">{{cite web | last=Thomas | first=Michael | title=The Republicans Who Could Save The IRA | website=Distilled by Michael Thomas (Substack) | date=May 14, 2025 | url=https://www.distilled.earth/p/the-republicans-who-could-save-the | access-date=May 14, 2025}}</ref>

Wellesley College professor of environmental studies Jay Turner said that {{as of|2024|July|21|df=US|lc=y}} the act fostered $94.2 billion in 121 new investments in the electric vehicle supply chain, creating a projected 60,597 new jobs across the United States, [[Canada]] and [[Mexico]]. The number of new mines the act incentivized in 2023 was 101, the amount of battery manufacturing capacity brought up to 348 GWh, and EV manufacturing capacity brought up to 2,913,900 vehicles.<ref name="Charged 2024">{{cite web | last=Turner|first=James Morton|title=US and Canada Electric Vehicle Supply Chain Map | website=Charged | url=https://www.charged-the-book.com/na-ev-supply-chain-map|date=July 21, 2024 | access-date=July 21, 2024}}</ref>

The research firm Climate Power estimated that the act spurred $89.5 billion of investments in over 90 new projects creating 101,036 predicted clean energy-related jobs in 31 states, between August 16, 2022 and January 31, 2023, and that while Georgia, [[Michigan]], and [[Texas]] saw eight new IRA-linked projects each, the most of any states, Georgia, [[Idaho]] and [[Tennessee]] would see the largest overall investments by dollar amount (ranging from $10.4 billion to $15.3 billion), and [[Kansas]], Georgia and Tennessee would see the most jobs created.<ref name="Climate Power 2023">{{cite web | title=Clean Energy Boom – 100k Clean Energy Jobs Report | website=Climate Power | date=February 3, 2023 | url=https://climatepower.us/wp-content/uploads/sites/23/2023/02/Clean-Energy-Boom-100K-Report.pdf | access-date=May 6, 2023}}</ref><ref name="Semafor 2023">{{cite news | last=Weissmann | first=Jordan | title=How Washington underestimated Biden's big climate law | website=Semafor | date=May 4, 2023 | url=https://www.semafor.com/article/05/04/2023/biden-climate-ira-cost-inflation-reduction-act | access-date=May 6, 2023}}</ref> In its August 9, 2024 update, Climate Power had found at least 334,565 new clean energy jobs were created to date, across 646 projects and $372 billion in investments across 47 states and Puerto Rico. Georgia, Michigan and Texas saw the most projects and money, while the former two and [[New York State]] saw the most jobs at 32-24,000.<ref name="Climate Power 2024">{{cite web|url=https://climatepower.us/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/Clean-Energy-Boom-Two-Year-Anniversary-Report-RES-2024_07_30-DR.pdf|website=Climate Power|title=Two Years of the Biden-Harris Clean Energy Boom |date=August 9, 2024}}</ref> The firm's January 14, 2025 update found the numbers increased to at least 406,007 new jobs across 751 projects and $422 billion in investments across 48 states and Puerto Rico. Georgia, New York, and Texas saw the most jobs at 43-26,000; Michigan saw the most projects at 74, and New York saw the most money at $115.46 billion.<ref name="Climate Power 2025">{{cite web | title=State of the clean energy boom | website=Climate Power | date=January 14, 2025 | url=https://climatepower.us/clean-energy-boom-report/ | access-date=January 15, 2025}}</ref>

In August 2023, the Solar Energy Industries Association reported that the act had created more than 20,000 jobs and incentivized $20 billion in new solar power tech manufacturing and 155 gigawatts of generating capacity in the law's first year, and projected it would incentivize $144 billion more in such investments by 2033 than under a no-Act scenario.<ref name="SEIA 2023">{{cite web | title=Impact of the Inflation Reduction Act | website=SEIA | date=August 13, 2023 | url=http://www.seia.org/research-resources/impact-inflation-reduction-act | access-date=August 25, 2023}}</ref> In September 2024, the SEIA reported that the act had helped quadruple solar manufacturing capacity in the U.S. to 31 gigawatts since its passage. It also reported that in the first half of 2024 solar installations represented 67 percent of all new energy capacity in the U.S., and forecasted a 4 percent annual solar market growth rate through 2029, buoyed by the act's Solar for All initiative.<ref name="SEIA Q3 2024">{{cite web | title=Solar Market Insight Report | website=SEIA | date=September 9, 2024 | url=https://seia.org/research-resources/us-solar-market-insight/ | access-date=October 22, 2024}}</ref>

The trade group American Clean Power's January 2023 assessment of business announcements of IRA-linked investments in renewables and battery plants, during the period between the act's signing and November 30, 2022, yielded a figure of over $40 billion creating 6,850 jobs. 80 percent of these investments are in Republican-held districts, mostly in the Great Plains or South.<ref name="Milman 2023"/><ref name="ACP January 2023">{{cite news | title=Clean Energy Industry Sees Massive Investments Since August | website=ACP | date=January 30, 2023 | url=https://cleanpower.org/resources/clean-energy-investing-in-america-report/ | access-date=March 10, 2023 | archive-date=March 10, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230310075451/https://cleanpower.org/resources/clean-energy-investing-in-america-report/ | url-status=dead }}</ref> Its August 2023 update recorded a total of 97 manufacturing investments worth $270 billion spurred by the act between the August 16 enactment date and July 31, 2023, 83 with defined locations, with the majority of these being solar power tech plants. American Clean Power estimates these investments are worth more than all those made in the previous eight years combined, and will create 29,780 new jobs and $4.5 billion in customer savings.<ref name="ACP August 2023">{{cite news | title=Clean Energy Investing In America | website=ACP | date=August 6, 2023 | url=https://cleanpower.org/resources/clean-energy-investing-in-america-report/ | access-date=August 7, 2023 | archive-date=August 1, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230801190717/https://cleanpower.org/resources/clean-energy-investing-in-america-report/ | url-status=dead }}</ref>

In June 2024, [[CNN]] found nearly 80 percent of the act's new jobs were created in Republican-held House districts, consistent with earlier projections,<ref name="Nilsen Rigdon 2024">{{cite web | last1=Nilsen | first1=Ella | last2=Rigdon | first2=Renée | title=The biggest winners of Biden's green climate policies? Republicans. | website=CNN | date=June 16, 2024 | url=https://www.cnn.com/2024/06/16/climate/clean-energy-investment-republicans/index.html | access-date=August 14, 2024}}</ref> as well as a later Bloomberg Opinion article that found $161 billion of clean investments had gone to those districts and $42 billion to Democratic-held districts since Biden took office in January 2021.<ref name="Bloomberg June 2024">{{cite web | last1=Denning | first1=Liam | last2=Davies | first2=Jeff | last3=He | first3=Elaine | last4=Silverman | first4=Carolyn | last5=Tyson | first5=Taylor | title=Biden Is Giving Red Districts an Inconvenient Gift: Green Jobs | website=Bloomberg.com | date=June 20, 2024 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/graphics/2024-opinion-biden-ira-sends-green-energy-investment-republican-districts/ | access-date=August 27, 2024}}</ref>

According to the [[New Democrats (United States)|New Democrat]]–linked think tank [[Center for American Progress]], the act, the CHIPS and Science Act, and the Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act have together catalyzed over 35,000 public and private investments.<ref name="CAP 2023">{{cite web | last1=Ragland|first1=Will |last2=Koronowski|first2=Ryan |last3=Simhoni | first3=Shanee | title=Biden Administration Investment Tracker | website=Center for American Progress | date=June 20, 2023 | url=https://www.americanprogress.org/article/investment-tracker/ | access-date=June 29, 2023}}</ref>  Economists Noah Smith and Joseph Politano credited the three acts together for spurring booms in factory construction and utility jobs, as well as limiting geographic concentrations of key industries to ensure more dispersed job creation nationwide, though they raised issues of whether the three would serve to limit project delays and significantly increase labor productivity in the long term.<ref name="Smith 2024">{{cite web | last=Smith | first=Noah | title=Biden did stuff, and it looks like it's working so far | website=Noahpinion | date=September 2, 2024 | url=https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/biden-did-stuff-and-it-looks-like | access-date=September 5, 2024}}</ref><ref name="Politano 2024">{{cite web | last=Politano | first=Joseph | title=The Regional Impacts of America's Investment Boom | website=Apricitas Economics | date=September 4, 2024 | url=https://www.apricitas.io/p/the-regional-impacts-of-americas | access-date=September 5, 2024}}</ref> The Biden administration itself claimed that {{as of|2025|01|10|lc=y|df=US}}, the IIJA, CaSA, and IRA together catalyzed $1 trillion in private investment (including $449 billion in electronics and semiconductors, $184 billion in electric vehicles and batteries, $215 billion in clean power, $93 billion in clean energy tech manufacturing and infrastructure, and $51 billion in heavy industry) and over $756.2 billion in public infrastructure spending (including $99 billion in energy aside from tax credits in the IRA).<ref name="Invest.gov 2025">{{cite web | title=Investing In America | website=The White House | date=January 10, 2025 | url=https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/invest/?utm_source=invest.gov | access-date=January 10, 2025}}</ref>{{update after|2025|01|30}}

====Labor impact====
In October 2023, Lee Harris of ''[[The American Prospect]]'' covered one example of synergies between the act and the growth of an organizing model known as [[sectoral bargaining]]: three unions in solar power construction agreed to a nationwide deal to divide work on future projects (California being exempt because of a similar five-union agreement).<ref name="Harris sectoral bargaining 2023">{{cite web | last=Harris | first=Lee | title=Solar Could Become a Model for Sectoral Bargaining | website=The American Prospect | date=October 27, 2023 | url=https://prospect.org/environment/2023-10-27-solar-could-become-model-for-sectoral-bargaining/ | access-date=August 17, 2024}}</ref> On August 16, 2024, the [[United Steelworkers]] announced it had successfully reached an electoral neutrality agreement with solar panel manufacturer Convalt, making it easier to form a union at IRA-linked project sites in Pennsylvania and New York.<ref name="USW">{{cite web | title=USW Reaches Agreement with Convalt Energy to Respect Workers' Rights | website=United Steelworkers | date=August 16, 2024 | url=https://usw.org/news/media-center/releases/2024/usw-reaches-agreement-with-convalt-energy-to-respect-workers-rights | access-date=September 5, 2024}}</ref>

On June 25, 2024, the IRS finalized the guidance on prevailing wage and apprenticeship bonuses for the most important of the act's tax credits.<ref>{{CodeFedReg|26|1}}; see also {{FederalRegister|89|53184}}</ref>

In an article marking the law's second anniversary, reporter Emily Pontecorvo of ''Heatmap News'' found that the law increased construction union membership in areas with mostly non-union labor markets, especially in solar power. Due to the investment tax credits' rules on [[Project Labor Agreement]]s, prevailing wages and apprenticeships, the law also set up a new dynamic where energy developers have started to negotiate with unions early in their project planning, and fostered the growth of a new tax credit compliance industry. Pontecorvo also found, however, that wide disparities remained between union and non-union apprenticeships and wages, and that non-union apprenticeships were still poorly regulated.<ref name="Pontecorvo 2024">{{cite web | last=Pontecorvo | first=Emily | title=The IRA's Labor Provisions Look Like They're Working | website=Heatmap News | date=August 15, 2024 | url=https://heatmap.news/economy/ira-anniversary-labor | access-date=August 17, 2024}}</ref> She later analyzed an August 29 Energy Department report that found that even with growth in the fossil fuel workforce, unionization in clean energy grew faster than in the overall energy sector, and that unionized firms had an easier time hiring job applicants than non-unionized firms, for which she credited the act; the DOE found that clean energy job numbers grew 4.2 percent in 2023, twice the national rate for all employers, and up 3.9 percent from the previous year. Pontecorvo also reported that the energy workforce continued to suffer from a lack of diversity, particularly of gender.<ref name="Pontecorvo DOE jobs report">{{cite web | last=Pontecorvo | first=Emily | title=3 Takeaways From the Department of Energy's Big New Jobs Report | website=Heatmap News | date=August 28, 2024 | url=https://heatmap.news/economy/2023-energy-and-employment-report | access-date=September 5, 2024}}</ref>

====Fiscal impact====
The law significantly enlarged the tax credit market. It includes significant tax credits for companies making products considered environmentally-friendly, but small companies tend not to pay enough taxes, so the law does not help them. The law allows such companies to sell their tax credits to larger companies.<ref name="Buffie 2024">{{Cite report|url=https://crsreports.congress.gov/product/pdf/IF/IF12596|series=In Focus|number=12596|last=Buffie|first=Nicholas E.|date=February 26, 2024|title=Tax Credit Transfers and Direct Payments in the Inflation Reduction Act of 2022|publisher=Congressional Research Service}}</ref> The market is expected to reach $80 billion per year and help those large companies.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tankersley |first1=Jim |last2=Hirsch |first2=Lauren |title=In Biden's Climate Law, a Boon for Green Energy, and Wall Street |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/11/23/business/economy/climate-law-biden-tax-credits.html |access-date=29 November 2023 |agency=The New York Times |date=23 November 2023}}</ref>

In February 2024, ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''Energy Storage News'' reported that it was clear that companies were using the credits accorded by the law far more than was predicted. According to government officials they interviewed, the increase of revenue from improved [[Internal Revenue Service]] tax enforcement will be more than enough to cover the losses, so the deficit will still be reduced.<ref name=Jim>{{cite news |last1=Tankersley |first1=Jim |title=Why the Cost of Biden's Climate Law Keeps Going Up |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2024/02/08/us/politics/biden-inflation-reduction-act-cost.html?unlocked_article_code=1.T00.9Q50.YjKwcA0t5eJv |access-date=9 February 2024 |agency=The New York Times |date=8 February 2024}}</ref> The tax credits with the highest market value are for grid energy storage.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Murray |first1=Cameron |title=Energy storage tax credits in US priced highest among all clean energy types |url=https://www.energy-storage.news/energy-storage-tax-credits-in-us-priced-highest-among-all-clean-energy-types/ |website=Energy-Storage.News |date=16 February 2024}}</ref> The next month, the ''Times'' reported that the IRS had received from about 500 companies registrations of more than 45,500 projects attached to direct pay or possible small business sales of the IRA's energy tax credits, up from only about 1,000 in January.<ref name="Tankersley March 2024">{{cite web | last=Tankersley | first=Jim | title=Biden's Climate Law Has Created a Growing Market for Green Tax Credits | website=The New York Times | date=March 19, 2024 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2024/03/19/business/biden-climate-tax-credits.html | access-date=April 5, 2024}}</ref>

=== Environment ===
{{See also|Environmental policy of the Joe Biden administration|Green New Deal}}
According to Rhodium Group and the World Economic Forum, in the first year of implementation, the act had a significant impact on the environment. The Rhodium Group's expectations for [[Greenhouse gas emissions|GHG emissions]] reductions by the year 2030, relative to the level of 2005, moved from 17–30% to 29–42%, and to a 32–51% decline by the year 2035. More than 170,000 green jobs were created.

The sales of [[heat pump]]s exceeded the sales of [[gas boiler]]s for the first time in history. 15% of households now{{when|date=December 2025}} use a heat pump as a primary source of heating. The [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] used dozens of millions of dollars to improve [[air quality]] and hundreds of millions for [[environmental justice]] and local climate plans. The [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] spent hundreds of millions for protecting coastal communities and [[coastal ecosystems|ecosystems]] from the impact of climate change. More than $1 billion is allocated to equitable access to [[urban tree]]s.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Broom |first1=Douglas |title=The US Inflation Reduction Act one year on – what's been achieved for the green economy? |url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2023/08/inflation-reduction-act-one-year-green-jobs/ |website=World Economic Forum |date=August 21, 2023 |access-date=24 September 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Taking Stock 2021: US Emissions Outlook Under Current Policy |url=https://rhg.com/research/taking-stock-2021/ |website=Rhodium Group |date=July 15, 2021 |access-date=24 September 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Taking Stock 2023 US Emissions Projections after the Inflation Reduction Act |url=https://rhg.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/Taking-Stock-2023_Rhodium-Group.pdf |website=Rhodium Group}}</ref>

The governors of four states, [[Florida]], [[South Dakota]], [[Iowa]], and [[Kentucky]], refused to accept decarbonization money from the act's Climate Pollution Reduction Grants program. The act allows the forfeited money, $3 million per state, to go to the three largest metropolitan areas in each state instead, though cities such as [[Davenport, Iowa]], and [[Sioux Falls, South Dakota]], have still refused the money.<ref name="Lubach 2023">{{cite web | last=Lubach | first=Dave | title=Inflation Reduction Act Money Finds way to States that Refused Funding | website=Facilitiesnet | url=https://www.facilitiesnet.com/government_buildings/tip/Inflation-Reduction-Act-Money-Finds-way-to-States-that-Refused-Funding—51964 | access-date=August 16, 2023}}</ref><ref name="Aton 2023">{{cite web | last=Aton | first=Adam | title=How Biden steered climate money to red states | website=E&E News by Politico | date=July 19, 2023 | url=https://www.eenews.net/articles/how-biden-steered-climate-money-to-red-states/ | access-date=August 15, 2023}}</ref>

From June 2023 to February 2024, the EPA awarded $250 million from the CPRG (Climate Pollution Reduction Grants) program to 82 cities and 45 states to update their climate action plans.<ref name="EPA Planning Info">{{cite web | title=About CPRG Planning Grant Information | website=US EPA | date=April 22, 2024 | url=https://www.epa.gov/inflation-reduction-act/about-cprg-planning-grant-information | access-date=July 22, 2024}}</ref> On July 22, 2024, the EPA awarded from the same program $4.3 billion to 25 cities, states, tribal governments, and coalitions of the three for implementing community driven solutions to reduce [[greenhouse gas emissions]] by 148 million metric tons by 2030 and by 971 million tons by 2050. The solutions mainly belong to the domains of energy, buildings, agriculture, industry, waste, and ecosystems. The largest recipient, at $499,997,415 for vehicle decarbonization, is the [[South Coast Air Quality Management District]] in California.<ref name="Gaffney 2024">{{cite web | last=Gaffney | first=Austyn | title=E.P.A. Announcing $4.3 Billion in Funding for 25 Climate Projects | website=The New York Times | date=July 22, 2024 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2024/07/22/climate/epa-climate-change-money.html| access-date=July 22, 2024}}</ref><ref name="EPA Implementation">{{cite web | title=CPRG Implementation Grants: General Competition Selections | website=US EPA | date=June 25, 2024 | url=https://www.epa.gov/inflation-reduction-act/cprg-implementation-grants-general-competition-selections | access-date=July 22, 2024}}</ref>

==== Energy and industry ====
The act deals extensively with trade flows of clean energy and their effects on domestic manufacturing. As an example, the Treasury Department clarified on May 12, 2023, that in order to be eligible for the Sections 45, 45Y, 48 and 48E tax credits,<ref>{{USC|26|45}}, {{USC|26|45Y}}, {{USC|26|48}} and {{USC|26|48E}}</ref> solar panel manufacturers and installers need to source at least 40 percent of their components in total from within the U.S., regardless of solar cell origin, thereby creating a compromise between solar panel installers who favored keeping Chinese imports cheap and domestic solar cell manufacturers who want to build more factories in America.<ref name="Reuters Treasury solar guidance 2023">{{cite web |last1=Groom |first1=Nichola |last2=Lawder |first2=David |title=US Treasury takes middle road on solar panels 'Made in the USA' |website=Reuters |date=May 12, 2023 |url=https://www.reuters.com/markets/us/us-treasury-takes-middle-road-solar-panels-made-usa-2023-05-12/ |access-date=June 6, 2023}}</ref><ref name="U.S. Department of the Treasury 2023-05-12">{{cite web | title=Treasury Department Releases Guidance to Boost American Clean Energy Manufacturing | website=U.S. Department of the Treasury | date=May 12, 2023 | url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/jy1477 | access-date=March 30, 2024}}</ref>

Significant improvements were achieved in the domain of [[green building]] through the installation of efficient [[heating, ventilation, and air conditioning]] systems, and more.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Perkins |first1=Hannah |last2=Aston |first2=Adam |title=U.S. Inflation Reduction Act: one year on, a summary of impressive progress in the energy transition |url=https://energypost.eu/u-s-inflation-reduction-act-one-year-on-a-summary-of-the-impressive-progress-in-the-energy-transition/ |website=Energy Post |date=September 19, 2023 |access-date=24 September 2023 |archive-date=September 22, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230922095403/https://energypost.eu/u-s-inflation-reduction-act-one-year-on-a-summary-of-the-impressive-progress-in-the-energy-transition/ |url-status=usurped }}</ref>

For the first $8.5 billion in home rebate programs, the Department of Energy released its first draft guidance for states on July 27, 2023. The guidance entails the DOE distributing $4.3 billion to states to work with the DOE to create rebate programs for whole-home upgrades and $4.28 billion to states for appliance replacement rebates, with the suggestion that half the money go to households below 80 percent of area median income.<ref name="Energy.gov Home Guidance 2023">{{cite web | title=Biden Harris Administration Opens Applications For States And Territories To Implement $8.5 Billion For Home Energy Rebates As Part Of Investing In America Agenda | website=Energy.gov | date=July 27, 2023 | url=https://www.energy.gov/articles/biden-harris-administration-opens-applications-states-and-territories-implement-85-billion | access-date=August 2, 2023}}</ref><ref name="Sierra Club 2023">{{cite web | title=DOE Releases Guidance for States to Develop Electrification and Efficiency Rebate Programs | website=Sierra Club | date=July 27, 2023 | url=https://www.sierraclub.org/press-releases/2023/07/doe-releases-guidance-states-develop-electrification-and-efficiency-rebate | access-date=August 3, 2023}}</ref>

On November 17, 2023, the DOE announced $169 million funded by the act for nine projects at 15 sites to accelerate US-made heat pump manufacturing.<ref name=":12">{{Cite web |title=Biden-Harris Administration Announces $169 Million to Accelerate Electric Heat Pump Manufacturing as Part of Investing in America Agenda |url=https://www.energy.gov/articles/biden-harris-administration-announces-169-million-accelerate-electric-heat-pump |access-date=2023-11-18 |website=Energy.gov |date=November 17, 2023 |language=en}}</ref> On February 14, 2024, the DOE announced a further $63 million funded by the act to accelerate the growth of domestic manufacturing of residential heat pumps, heat pump water heaters, and other heat pump systems and components.<ref name=":13">{{cite web | url=https://www.energy.gov/articles/biden-harris-administration-announces-63-million-accelerate-electric-heat-pump | title=Biden-Harris Administration Announces $63 Million to Accelerate Electric Heat Pump Manufacturing Across America as Part of Investing in America Agenda | date=February 14, 2024 }}</ref>

On December 4, 2023, the DOE and IRS announced they had received over 46,000 applications for new energy project financing under the Section 48E bonus investment tax credit since October 29.<ref>{{USC|26|48E}}</ref><ref name="Misbrener 2023">{{cite web | last=Misbrener | first=Kelsey | title=IRS receives more than 8 GW in low-income solar bonus credit applications | website=Solar Power World | date=December 4, 2023 | url=https://www.solarpowerworldonline.com/2023/12/irs-receives-more-than-8-gw-low-income-solar-bonus-credit-applications/ | access-date=April 5, 2024}}</ref><ref name="Energy.gov on Section 48E 2024">{{cite web | title=Low-Income Communities Bonus Credit Program | website=Energy.gov | date=February 29, 2024 | url=https://www.energy.gov/justice/low-income-communities-bonus-credit-program | access-date=April 5, 2024}}</ref> The first-year selectees, the Treasury Department projected, would add 1.8 gigawatts of capacity to the nationwide grid.<ref name="U.S. Department of the Treasury March 29, 2024">{{cite web | title=U.S. Department of the Treasury, IRS Release 2024 Guidance for Second Year of Program to Spur Clean Energy Investments in Underserved Communities, As Part of Investing in America Agenda | website=U.S. Department of the Treasury | date=March 29, 2024 | url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/jy2217 | access-date=April 5, 2024}}</ref>

On March 6, 2024, the Department of Agriculture announced it would advance requests for $139 million to be approved, to five solar and battery storage projects in Arizona, Colorado, Hawaii and Nebraska, under the Powering Affordable Clean Energy (PACE) program that the act created.<ref name="USDA PACE announcement March 2024">{{cite web | title=Biden-Harris Administration Invests $2.3 Billion in Projects to Expand Affordable, Reliable, Clean Power in Rural Communities Through Investing in America Agenda | website=USDA | date=March 6, 2024 | url=https://www.usda.gov/about-usda/news/press-releases/2024/03/06/biden-harris-administration-invests-23-billion-projects-expand-affordable-reliable-clean-power-rural | access-date=April 5, 2024}}</ref> On the 11th, the IRS finalized the rules of its direct pay program allowing tax-exempt nonprofits, the [[Tennessee Valley Authority|TVA]], state and local governments and electric cooperatives to access the act's panoply of tax credits.<ref>{{Federal Register|89|17546}}</ref> On the 13th, the DOE announced the first conditional commitment of a $72.8 million loan guarantee to a Tribal energy project under the act, the Viejas Microgrid benefiting [[Kumeyaay]] residents near [[Alpine, California]].<ref name="EGov-TL24">{{cite press release | title=LPO Announces Conditional Commitment to Viejas Microgrid to Build Renewable, Utility-Scale Generation and Storage on Tribal Lands | website=Energy.gov | date=March 13, 2024 | url=https://www.energy.gov/lpo/articles/lpo-announces-conditional-commitment-viejas-microgrid-build-renewable-utility-scale | access-date=April 5, 2024}}</ref>

On March 25, 2024, the Biden administration announced the first 33 grant recipients of the Department of Energy's $6 billion Industrial Demonstrations Program to reduce embedded emissions in factories and materials processing, of which the Inflation Reduction Act funds $5.46 billion. [[Cement]] and [[concrete]] industry projects received $1.5 billion in total, [[steelmaking]] projects received $1.5 billion, and [[chemical engineering]] and refinery projects $1.2 billion. The Biden administration expected these projects to drive 1.4 million tons in carbon emissions cuts,<ref name="Gallucci 2024">{{cite web | last=Gallucci | first=Maria | title=Biden admin invests $6B to cut carbon from steel, cement | website=Canary Media | date=March 25, 2024 | url=https://www.canarymedia.com/articles/clean-industry/biden-admin-invests-6b-to-cut-carbon-from-steel-cement-and-snacks | access-date=March 25, 2024}}</ref> though it had not finalized most of the grants even by November 11, putting them at the risk of being rescinded by the succeeding Trump administration.<ref name="Gallucci 2024-11-11">{{cite web |last=Gallucci|first=Maria| title=Biden's $6B bid to clean up heavy industry at risk under Trump | website=Canary Media | date=November 11, 2024 | url=https://www.canarymedia.com/articles/clean-industry/bidens-6b-bid-to-clean-up-heavy-industry-at-risk-under-trump | access-date=November 11, 2024}}</ref> On the 27th, the DOE announced it had reached a conditional agreement for a $1.52 billion loan to [[Holtec International]] to reopen the [[Palisades Nuclear Generating Station]], the first such agreement under the act's Title 17 Clean Energy Financing Section 1706 program.<ref name="Egov-800MWNuc">{{cite press release | title=LPO Announces Conditional Commitment to Holtec Palisades to Finance the Restoration and Resumption of Service of 800-MW Nuclear Generating Station | website=Energy.gov | date=March 27, 2024 | url=https://www.energy.gov/lpo/articles/lpo-announces-conditional-commitment-holtec-palisades-finance-restoration-and | access-date=April 5, 2024}}</ref> On the 28th, the Agriculture Department revealed the 541 recipients across 44 states of $124 million from the Rural Energy for America Program, which the act greatly augmented.<ref name="REAP and FPEP announcement March 2024">{{cite web | title=Biden-Harris Administration Invests in Clean Energy and Fertilizer Production to Strengthen American Farms and Businesses as Part of Investing in America Agenda | website=USDA | date=March 28, 2024 | url=https://www.usda.gov/about-usda/news/press-releases/2024/03/28/biden-harris-administration-invests-clean-energy-and-fertilizer-production-strengthen-american-farms | access-date=April 5, 2024}}</ref> On March 29, the DOE announced over 100 recipients of the first $4 billion from the act's renewal of the Section 48C tax credit,<ref name="DOE 48C announcements March 2024">{{cite web | title=Applicant Self-Disclosed 48C Projects | website=Energy.gov | date=March 29, 2024 | url=https://www.energy.gov/mesc/applicant-self-disclosed-48c-projects| access-date=May 23, 2024}}</ref> opening the remaining $6 billion to applications on May 22.<ref name="Evergreen Action May 23, 2024">{{cite web | title=What Is the 48C Tax Credit, and How Can Communities Benefit? | website=Evergreen Action | date=May 23, 2024 | url=https://evergreenaction.com/blog/what-is-the-48c-tax-credit-and-how-can-communities-benefit-9| access-date=May 23, 2024}}</ref>

On April 4, 2024, the Biden administration announced the eight recipients of the first $20 billion of the Greenhouse Gas Reduction Fund. For the $14 billion National Clean Investment Fund, the recipients are the consumer-focused Climate United Fund ($6.97 billion to a consortium of Calvert Impact, [[Center for Community Self-Help|Self-Help Ventures Fund]] and Community Preservation Corporation), the Coalition for Green Capital ($5 billion), and Power Forward Communities ($2 billion); collectively they have pledged 60 percent of funds would go to low-income and marginalized communities, well above the 40 percent required by Biden. For the $6 billion Clean Communities Investment Accelerator program to disburse money exclusively and deep into such communities, they are four [[Community development financial institution|CDFI]]s (Opportunity Finance Network, Inclusiv, Native CDFI Network and Appalachian Community Capital) receiving a total of roughly $5.1 billion, and a coalition of community organizations called the Justice Climate Fund receiving $940 million. The Biden administration projects that they will leverage $7 from the private sector for every dollar of public investment, and slash emissions by up to 40 million metric tons by 2032 through a very wide variety of projects.<ref name="The White House GGRF announcement 2024">{{cite web | author=The White House | title=Biden-Harris Administration Announces Historic $20 Billion in Awards to Expand Access to Clean Energy and Climate Solutions and Lower Energy Costs for Communities Across the Nation | website=The White House | date=April 4, 2024 | url=https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2024/04/04/biden-harris-administration-announces-historic-20-billion-in-awards-to-expand-access-to-clean-energy-and-climate-solutions-and-lower-energy-costs-for-communities-across-the-nation/ | access-date=April 5, 2024}}</ref><ref name="St. John April 2024">{{cite web | last=St. John | first=Jeff | title=EPA's new $20B 'green bank' will benefit disadvantaged communities… | website=Canary Media | date=April 4, 2024 | url=https://www.canarymedia.com/articles/climatetech-finance/epas-new-20b-green-bank-will-benefit-disadvantaged-communities-most | access-date=April 5, 2024}}</ref><ref name="Roberts 2024">{{cite web | last=Roberts | first=David | title=How the EPA will spend $27 billion in carbon-reduction funds | website=Volts | date=April 5, 2024 | url=https://www.volts.wtf/p/how-the-epa-will-spend-27-billion | access-date=April 5, 2024}}</ref>

On April 11, the Interior Department finalized a rule cutting rents on federal lands for renewable energy development by 80 percent, in part by clarifying definitions in Section 50265(b)(1) of the act.<ref>{{CodeFedReg|43|2800}}</ref> On the 12th, the Department raised rents on federal lands for oil and gas drilling by 1000 percent (the first such raise since 1960) and royalties by 4 percentage points, and directed drillers to pump away from sensitive wildlife areas, thus formalizing more parts of the act.<ref name="Joselow Dawsey 2024">{{cite news | last1=Joselow | first1=Maxine | last2=Dawsey | first2=Josh | title=Biden hikes cost of drilling on federal lands as Trump courts oil donors | newspaper=Washington Post | date=April 12, 2024 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/climate-environment/2024/04/12/oil-drilling-federal-lands-biden/ | access-date=April 13, 2024}}</ref> On April 22, the Biden administration announced the 60 recipients of the $7 billion Solar for All program. The EPA forecasted the projects would serve a total of 900,000 low-income households, and generate them $350 million in annual savings and $8 billion cumulatively.<ref name="Solar for All announcement 2024">{{cite web | title=Biden-Harris Administration Announces $7 Billion Solar for All Grants to Deliver Residential Solar, Saving Low-Income Americans $350 Million Annually and Advancing Environmental Justice Across America | website=US EPA | date=April 22, 2024 | url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/biden-harris-administration-announces-7-billion-solar-all-grants-deliver-residential | access-date=April 22, 2024}}</ref>

In May 2024, multiple solar companies told [[Bloomberg News]] that they had faced borderline [[Dumping (pricing policy)|dumping]] of solar panels from China, and criticized the act for not providing enough tax credits to help with manufacturing upstream, including the [[ingot]]s and [[Wafer (electronics)|wafers]] of [[polycrystalline silicon]] needed to make the cells, as well as for unclear guidance that does not say whether domestic panel content incentives can go to them; as a result, several US solar manufacturers have slowed their timelines on plant construction and pressed the Biden administration to build up tariffs while they wait for better guidance.<ref name="Dlouhy 2024">{{cite web | last=Dlouhy | first=Jennifer A | title=Biden's Solar Factory Boom Slows as Cheap Imports Flood Market | website=Bloomberg.com | date=May 12, 2024 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-05-12/biden-s-solar-factory-boom-slows-as-cheap-imports-flood-market | access-date=May 15, 2024}}</ref> On May 14, the Department of Energy announced a loan guarantee of $1.66 billion under the act's expansion of the Title 17 Clean Energy Financing Program, to [[Plug Power]] to scale up clean hydrogen production in six of its facilities.<ref name="Energy.gov Plug announcement 2024">{{cite web | title=LPO Announces Conditional Commitment to Plug Power to Produce and Liquify Clean Hydrogen Fuel | website=Energy.gov | date=May 14, 2024 | url=https://www.energy.gov/lpo/articles/lpo-announces-conditional-commitment-plug-power-produce-and-liquify-clean-hydrogen | access-date=May 15, 2024}}</ref>

On July 24, 2024 the DOE's Grid Deployment Office announced it was awarding $371 million to 20 projects across 16 states for speeding up high-voltage transmission line approvals.<ref name="GDO announcement July 2024">{{cite web | title=Biden-Harris Administration Invests $371 Million in 20 Projects to Accelerate Transmission Permitting Across America | website=Energy.gov | date=July 24, 2024 | url=https://www.energy.gov/articles/biden-harris-administration-invests-371-million-20-projects-accelerate-transmission | access-date=July 24, 2024}}</ref>

In August 2024, the Treasury Department had found that in the 2023 tax year, 3.4 million households had claimed more than $8 billion against their federal income tax for home energy improvements; about 1.2 million had claimed $6 billion in credits for home clean energy, while 2.3 million had claimed $6 billion in credits for home energy efficiency improvements. The average benefit was estimated at $880 per family.<ref name="Feiveson Ashenfarb">{{cite web|last1=Feiveson|first1=Laura|last2=Ashenfarb|first2=Matthew|title=The Inflation Reduction Act: Saving American Households Money While Reducing Climate Change and Air Pollution|website=U.S. Department of the Treasury|date=August 7, 2024|url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/featured-stories/the-inflation-reduction-act-saving-american-householdsd-money-while-reducing-climate-change-and-air-pollution|access-date=August 14, 2024}}{{Dead link|date=February 2026 |bot=InternetArchiveBot }}</ref>

Based on the report, ''E&E News'' and ''The Guardian'' found households with annual incomes above $100,000 claimed energy tax credits such as the home production and efficiency credits at higher rates among their cohort, about 1.6-4 percent of all such filers, compared to those earning below, at about 0.7-0.9 percent of all such filers. Wealthier families received about 66 percent of the total $5.5 billion in credits in 2023, with households earning over $200,000 claiming $2 billion. By contrast, the poorest 25 percent received only $32 million in credits. In addition, ''E&E News'' noted that many states have yet to administer rebate programs meant for low-income households, which could further address wealth imbalances.<ref name="Frank 2024">{{cite web | last=Frank | first=Thomas | title=Wealthier homeowners nab billions in tax credits for energy efficiency | website=E&E News by POLITICO | date=August 16, 2024 | url=https://www.eenews.net/articles/wealthy-homeowners-nab-billions-in-tax-credits-for-energy-efficiency/ | access-date=September 21, 2024}}</ref><ref name="Noor 2024">{{cite web | last=Noor | first=Dharna | title=Tax credits in Biden's landmark climate law disproportionately benefit well-off | website=the Guardian | date=August 16, 2024 | url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/article/2024/aug/16/biden-inflation-reduction-act-tax-benefit-wealthy | access-date=September 21, 2024}}</ref>

Around that time, the Biden administration claimed successful implementation of a bonus credit for solar installer firms (not households) in low-income communities and Tribal country in its first year. According to Pontecorvo, the program steered nearly 48,000 solar projects to low-income areas and Tribal lands, with an estimated $270 million a year in energy savings, and 96 Tribal projects approved; no wind projects were supported. The law caps the amount of power the program can support per year at 1.8 gigawatts total, with certain types of recipients getting different subtotals. Pontecorvo found that while the program's data gathering process is difficult to assess, 98 percent of the money was allocated based mostly on installers' locations, without requirements to ensure that the savings reach low-income residents. The distribution of funds was uneven, with higher demand than expected from recipient subcategories like community solar projects, while other projects, like those on Tribal lands, generated lower demand; this unevenness continued to hold in 2024 even with some power caps being raised. The bonus credit is set to expire in 2031, though changes such as expansion to other clean energy technologies like small-scale hydroelectric and geothermal are set to take effect in 2025.<ref name="Pontecorvo September 2024">{{cite web | last=Pontecorvo | first=Emily | title=Exclusive: Treasury Report Details Mixed Success of IRA's Low Income Bonus Credit | website=Heatmap News | date=September 4, 2024 | url=https://heatmap.news/economy/low-income-ira-solar | access-date=September 5, 2024}}</ref>

The IRS is set{{update inline|date=January 2025}} to finalize the 45Q tax credit's<ref>{{USCode|26|45Q}}</ref> rules to empower [[carbon dioxide flooding]], a method of using the captured greenhouse gas to improve oil extraction in nearly depleted fields, at a level of between $60 and $130 per metric ton of carbon dioxide sequestered. Notably, [[Vicki Hollub]], CEO of [[Occidental Petroleum]], praised the Inflation Reduction Act in a 2024 earnings call for enabling the company to expand its operations, while [[ExxonMobil]] and [[Eneos]] have started reviving production in certain oil fields because of the act. Critics note the IRS relies on self-reported data from companies, verified with EPA resources not intended for tax purposes. Verifying the amount of carbon dioxide stored versus what leaks out is problematic due to gaps in data and oversight. A lack of interagency coordination between the IRS and EPA complicates accurate monitoring and reporting; investigations have revealed that significant portions of tax credits awarded under 45Q did not meet EPA's reporting requirements, raising questions about the program's integrity.<ref name="Webb 2024">{{cite web | last=Webb | first=Shelby | title=How oil companies could tap the climate law to pump more crude | website=E&E News by POLITICO | date=September 4, 2024 | url=https://www.eenews.net/articles/how-oil-companies-could-tap-the-climate-law-to-pump-more-crude/ | access-date=September 5, 2024}}</ref>

On September 5, the USDA announced that $7.3 billion in funding for 16 rural electric cooperative projects curbing 43 million tons in emissions would be approved under the act's New ERA program.<ref name="Douglas 2024">{{cite web | last=Douglas | first=Leah | title=US to spend $7.3 billion on rural clean energy projects | website=Reuters | date=September 5, 2024 | url=https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/us-spend-73-billion-rural-clean-energy-projects-2024-09-05/ | access-date=September 11, 2024}}</ref>

In October 2024, Deputy Treasury Secretary [[Wally Adeyemo]] revealed to Pontecorvo that he and his staff were planning to finalize the tax credit rules for clean hydrogen, advanced manufacturing, and tech-neutral clean power by December, and that [[bioenergy]] remained a sticking point for the latter; the reasons behind the Treasury's slow pace, he claimed, were understaffing and the review backlog of 30,000 comments on the clean hydrogen draft rule.<ref name="Pontecorvo interview of Adeyemo"/> [[Jael Holzman]] reported that soon after, experts in energy markets pointed to a lack of coordination between the IIJA's Hydrogen Hubs program and the IRA's clean hydrogen tax credits, price increases for electrolyzers, and the historically low cost of natural gas as additional reasons for the withdrawal of investment in Hub projects.<ref name="Holzman 2024">{{cite web |last=[[Jael Holzman|Holzman]] |first=Jael |date=October 30, 2024 |title=Hydrogen Hubs Are Struggling. Why? |url=https://heatmap.news/plus/the-fight/spotlight/hydrogen-hubs-problems |access-date=October 31, 2024 |website=[[Heatmap News]]}}</ref>

On November 12, 2024, the Biden administration announced the parameters of its first ever [[methane]] fee for oil and gas companies, the Waste Emissions Charge, which the act mandated. The Charge was to be set at $900 per metric ton in 2024, rising to $1,500 per metric ton in 2026, and was forecasted to remove 1.2 million tons of methane (34 million tons of carbon dioxide equivalent) by 2036, with a net benefit of $2 billion. The rule was finalized early in 2025, and believed to be difficult to overturn.<ref name="Daly 2024">{{cite web | last=Daly | first=Matthew | title=Biden EPA to charge first-ever 'methane fee' for drilling waste by oil and gas companies | website=AP News | date=November 12, 2024 | url=https://apnews.com/article/methane-fee-epa-climate-biden-oil-gas-5020fdf48c51918d42176e0a4f6093dd | access-date=November 12, 2024}}</ref><ref name="CNN methane fee report">{{cite web | last=Nilsen | first=Ella | title=Biden just finalized a major climate rule. This one could be tricky for Trump to dismantle | website=CNN | date=November 12, 2024 | url=https://edition.cnn.com/2024/11/12/climate/methane-rule-biden-trump/index.html | access-date=November 13, 2024}}</ref><ref name="Waste Emissions Charge">{{cite web | title=EPA Finalizes Rule to Reduce Wasteful Methane Emissions and Drive Innovation in the Oil and Gas Sector | website=US EPA | date=November 12, 2024 | url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/epa-finalizes-rule-reduce-wasteful-methane-emissions-and-drive-innovation-oil-and-gas | access-date=November 13, 2024}}</ref> However, the incoming Congress overturned the regulation on March 14, 2025 via resolution, effectively abolishing the charge.<ref name="Macgregor 2025">{{cite web | last=MacGregor | first=Alex | title=Congress Votes to Repeal EPA's Waste Emission Charge (WEC) Implementing Rule | website=Emissions Reduction Through Continuous Monitoring | date=March 6, 2025 | url=https://www.qubeiot.com/expert-insights/congress-votes-to-repeal-methane-fee | access-date=April 30, 2025}}</ref><ref name="WEC">{{cite web | title=Waste Emissions Charge | website=US EPA | date=March 17, 2025 | url=https://www.epa.gov/inflation-reduction-act/waste-emissions-charge | access-date=April 30, 2025}}</ref>

In December 2024, the clean power investment tax credit's rules were finalized, which clarify what qualifies as an energy project, what assets an offshore wind farm, geothermal heat pump or biogas plant owner can use to claim the credit, and what credit-qualifying stored hydrogen can be used for.<ref>{{Federal Register|89|100598}}</ref> On December 18, the DOE used the Section 1706 Program to fund [[Pacific Gas and Electric Company]]'s hydropower and energy storage expansions and enable experiments in [[virtual power plant]]s.<ref name="ESG Dive">{{cite web | last=Johnson | first=Lamar | title=PG&E gets $15B from DOE's loan office for hydropower, battery buildout | website=ESG Dive | date=December 18, 2024 | url=https://www.esgdive.com/news/pacific-gas-electric-pge-gets-15b-doe-loan-program-office-hydropower-battery-transmission/735936/ | access-date=December 20, 2024}}</ref> On January 16, 2025, the DOE used the program to lend $22.9 billion to six utility companies, the three largest recipients being [[DTE Electric Company]], [[PacifiCorp]], and [[Consumers Energy]], for similar purposes.<ref name="Walton 2025">{{cite web | last=Walton | first=Robert | title=AEP, DTE and 6 other utilities win $22.9B in conditional loan guarantees from DOE | website=Utility Dive | date=January 16, 2025 | url=https://www.utilitydive.com/news/aep-dte-utilities-conditional-guarantees-LPO/737557/ | access-date=February 4, 2025}}</ref>

On January 3, 2025, the Treasury Department finalized the 45V clean hydrogen tax credit, keeping the overall approach of the "three pillars" of hourly matching, additionality/incrementality, and deliverability. Major exemptions, however, were introduced, concerning such environmentalists as Conrad Schneider of the Clean Air Task Force and Dan Esposito of the Energy Innovation think tank. These included delaying the hourly matching requirement to 2030, advantaging nuclear power plants "at the risk of retirement", and allowing hydrogen producers more leeway to claim natural gas with carbon capture counted towards the credit, though the new rules also emphasized some exemptions only apply in states with a clean energy standard and binding emissions cap. Most environmental groups praised the rules, while industry groups were more cautious in doing so.<ref name="Pontecorvo January 2025">{{cite web | last=Pontecorvo | first=Emily | title=There's Something for (Almost) Everyone in the Hydrogen Tax Credit Rules | website=Heatmap News | date=January 3, 2025 | url=https://heatmap.news/climate/final-45v-hydrogen-tax-credit | access-date=January 3, 2025}}</ref> On the 10th, the USDA finalized $5.49 billion in New ERA grants and loans to 28 projects by rural electric cooperatives, and $565 million in PACE loans to 26 projects by solar nonprofits.<ref name="Vilsack 2025">{{cite web | title=press release: USDA Continues Historic Commitment, Partnering with Rural Communities on Clean, Affordable Energy | website=Home | date=January 10, 2025 | url=https://www.usda.gov/about-usda/news/press-releases/2025/01/10/usda-continues-historic-commitment-partnering-rural-communities-clean-affordable-energy | access-date=January 15, 2025}}</ref><ref name="New ERA 2025">{{cite web | title=USDA awards $6B to rural clean power initiatives|last=Peters|first=Keaton | website=Canary Media | date=January 15, 2025 | url=https://www.canarymedia.com/articles/policy-regulation/usda-awards-6b-to-rural-clean-power-initiatives | access-date=January 15, 2025}}</ref>

In total, $96.7 billion in clean energy grants under the act, or 84 percent of the energy grants, were finalized by the Biden administration by the 17th, leaving $11 billion to be handed out by the incoming president after the 20th.<ref name="Reuters January 2025">{{cite web | last=Gardner | first=Timothy | title=Biden protects 84% of IRA clean energy grants from being clawed back | website=Reuters | date=January 17, 2025 | url=https://www.reuters.com/sustainability/climate-energy/biden-protects-84-ira-clean-energy-grants-being-clawed-back-2025-01-17/ | access-date=January 20, 2025}}</ref>

====Transportation====

The Treasury and [[Internal Revenue Service]] published guidance on eligibility for electric vehicle owners to claim tax credits worth between $3,500 and $7,500 (the Clean Vehicle Credit, previously called the Qualified Plug-In Electric Drive Motor Vehicle Credit), aiming to not only incentivize EV adoption but also increase [[onshoring]] and [[friendshoring]] of the supply chain to 'friendly' locations. The [[United States Department of the Treasury|US Treasury Department]] has also stated that owners who purchase eligible vehicles previous to August 16, 2022, but did not possess the vehicle until after that date, also qualify for the Clean Vehicle Credit.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Lucero |first=Kat |title=Feds Spell Out EV Tax Breaks Under Inflation Reduction Act - Law360 |url=https://www.law360.com/tax-authority/articles/1521750/feds-spell-out-ev-tax-breaks-under-inflation-reduction-act |access-date=2022-08-21 |website=Law 360 |language=en}}</ref> However, because of the requirement that qualified EVs must have half or more of its battery materials built in the US,<ref name="Bikales 2023" /> "at least 40 percent of materials sourced from North America or a US trading partner by 2024" (with this minimum percentage meant to increase to 50 percent by 2025, 60 percent by 2026, and 70 percent by 2027)<ref name="Bikales 2023" /><ref name="2024 IRS 30D regulations">{{cite web | title=U.S. Treasury Releases Final Electric Vehicle Tax Credit Regulations | website=Sidley Austin LLP | date=May 10, 2024 | url=https://www.sidley.com/en/insights/newsupdates/2024/05/us-treasury-releases-final-electric-vehicle-tax-credit-regulations | access-date=June 19, 2024}}</ref> and the batteries cannot contain minerals that "were extracted, processed, or recycled by a foreign entity of concern",{{efn|A foreign entity of concern is an entity that is owned by, controlled by, or subject to the jurisdiction or direction of the governments of China, Russia, North Korea, and Iran.<ref>"[https://www.metaltechnews.com/story/2023/12/06/tech-metals/doe-redefines-foreign-entity-of-concern/1552.html Reinterpretation of FEOC widens pool of potential critical mineral sources eligible for federal tax credits, funds]". ''Metal Tech News''. December 1, 2023.</ref> }} with a final requirement for the vehicle to undergo final assembly in North America, most currently available EVs on the market will not qualify for the tax credits.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hawkins |first=Andrew J. |date=2022-08-08 |title=No electric vehicles on the market today qualify for the new EV tax credit |url=https://www.theverge.com/2022/8/8/23296678/ev-tax-credit-qualify-battery-supply-chain-china |access-date=2022-08-29 |website=The Verge |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |author1=Tim Levin |author2=Juliana Kaplan |title=Most electric cars won't qualify for Democrats' new $7,500 tax credit |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/federal-ev-tax-credit-inflation-reduction-build-back-better-tesla-2022-8 |access-date=2022-08-29 |website=Business Insider |language=en-US}}</ref> Yet, analyses show that the value of these credits are significant enough that strong incentives do exist to shift those supply chains.<ref name=alc/> The [[Department of Energy (United States)|Department of Energy]] and the [[Department of Transportation (U.S.)|Department of Transportation]] had published resources identifying vehicles that will likely meet all requirements for tax credits.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Davis |first=Jeffrey |title=Treasury Releases Initial Information On Electric Vehicle Tax Credit Under Newly Enacted Inflation Reduction Act - Tax Authorities - United States |url=https://www.mondaq.com/unitedstates/tax-authorities/1223028/treasury-releases-initial-information-on-electric-vehicle-tax-credit-under-newly-enacted-inflation-reduction-act |access-date=2022-08-21 |website=Mayer Brown}}</ref><ref name=":03" /> The [[United States Department of Energy|Department of Energy]] indicated that their list of eligible vehicles is not a guarantee for credit, and states that the [[Vehicle identification number|Vehicle Identification Number]] (VIN) will give full manufacturing details and locations.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Alternative Fuels Data Center: Inflation Reduction Act of 2022 |url=https://afdc.energy.gov/laws/inflation-reduction-act |access-date=2022-08-21 |website=US Department of Energy |language=en}}</ref> The Treasury released its next draft guidance for EV buyers on March 31, 2023, effective immediately, with finalization expected in June, and the first update taking place in May 2024; the allowed materials source list includes the 20 [[United States free-trade agreements]] partners and [[Japan]].<ref name="Bikales 2023">{{cite web |last=Bikales |first=James |title=IRS rules for electric cars unveiled after months of attacks |website=Politico |date=March 31, 2023 |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2023/03/31/treasury-tax-breaks-ev-00089883 |access-date=April 1, 2023}}</ref><ref name="2024 IRS 30D regulations"/>

On March 13, 2024, the Neighborhood Equity and Access program, which had been combined with the IIJA's Reconnecting Communities pilot program, awarded its first $3.33 billion in grants to 132 projects for removing highways and railroads that were built through poorer neighborhoods in the mid-20th century.<ref name="DOT March 13, 2024 announcement">{{cite web | title=Biden-Harris Administration Announces History-Making $3.3 Billion for Locally-Led Projects That Reconnect Communities as Part of President Biden's Investing in America Agenda | website=US Department of Transportation | date=March 13, 2024 | url=https://www.transportation.gov/briefing-room/biden-harris-administration-announces-history-making-33-billion-locally-led-projects | access-date=May 9, 2024}}</ref> On April 30, 2025, the think tank [[Transportation for America]] reported that $2.46 billion in NEaA funds across 60 projects remained unobligated.<ref name="Salerno 2025">{{cite web | last=Salerno | first=Corrigan | title=Reconnecting Communities projects are under threat. Here is what's at stake and where: | website=Transportation For America | date=April 29, 2025 | url=https://t4america.org/2025/04/29/reconnecting-communities-projects-are-under-threat-here-is-whats-at-stake-and-where/ | access-date=May 28, 2025}}</ref>

On April 30, 2024, the Treasury Department released their guidance on the Sections 40B and 6426(k) tax credits for the production of sustainable aviation fuels, specifically ethanol. "Producers of SAF are eligible for a tax credit of $1.25 to $1.75 per gallon. SAF that achieves a GHG emissions reduction of 50% is eligible for the $1.25 credit per gallon amount, and SAF that achieves a GHG emissions reduction of more than 50% is eligible for an additional $0.01 per gallon for each percentage point the reduction exceeds 50%, up to $0.50 per gallon." The IRS also released a new greenhouse gas study model for ethanol producers, and endorsed a USDA incentives program to incorporate climate-smart agriculture in corn and soybean ethanol production.<ref name="Treasury 40B announcement 2024">{{cite web | title=U.S. Department of the Treasury, IRS Release Guidance to Drive American Innovation, Cut Aviation Sector Emissions | website=U.S. Department of the Treasury | date=April 30, 2024 | url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/jy2307 | access-date=May 6, 2024}}</ref>

In June 2024, the Treasury Department announced that over 150,000 electric vehicles had seen more than $1 billion in savings by buyers since the previous January 1, through the act's tax credits.<ref name="Treasury EV announcement June 2024">{{cite web | title=U.S. Department of the Treasury Announces More Than $1 Billion in Upfront Savings for Consumers on Electric Vehicle Sales | website=U.S. Department of the Treasury | date=January 1, 2024 | url=https://home.treasury.gov/news/press-releases/jy2403 | access-date=August 27, 2024}}</ref>

In an October 2024 interview with reporter Emily Pontecorvo, Wally Adeyemo said he could not commit to a timeline for finalizing the tax credit rules on sustainable aviation fuel and electric vehicle charges, citing understaffing and the processing backlog of 30,000 comments on the clean hydrogen draft rule.<ref name="Pontecorvo interview of Adeyemo">{{cite web | last=Pontecorvo | first=Emily | title=Adeyemo: Hydrogen Tax Credit Rules Will Be Done by the End of the Year | website=Heatmap News | date=October 1, 2024 | url=https://heatmap.news/economy/final-hydrogen-tax-credit-45v | access-date=October 5, 2024}}</ref> On the 29th, the EPA and President Biden announced the 55 recipients of the $2.9 billion Clean Ports Program funded by the act; most of the money will go towards zero-emissions cargo handling equipment or [[shore power]].<ref name="Clean ports announcement">{{cite web | author=The White House | title=FACT SHEET: President Joe Biden Announces $3 Billion to Strengthen Port Infrastructure, Create Good-Paying and Union Jobs, Bring Cleaner Air to Communities | website=The White House | date=October 29, 2024 | url=https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2024/10/29/fact-sheet-president-joe-biden-announces-3-billion-to-strengthen-port-infrastructure-create-good-paying-and-union-jobs-bring-cleaner-air-to-communities/ | access-date=November 20, 2024}}</ref>

In November 2024, the DOE announced that $6.6 billion of funding from the act would be loaned to the automaker [[Rivian]] to complete its new plant in Georgia.<ref>{{cite web|last=Darmiento|first=Laurence|date=2024-11-26|title=Rivian receives conditional $6.6-billion federal loan for plant, new models|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/story/2024-11-26/rivian-6-6-billion-loan-factory-georgia-ev-market-trump-biden|website=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2024-12-03}}</ref>

Solar for All was in the process of distributing the grants in February 2024 when newly appointed EPA Administrator Lee Zeldin announced he sought to instantly terminate roughly $20 billion in clean energy grant programs. However, the Environmental Protection Agency unfroze the $7 billion fund Solar for All program on March 4, 2025.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Metea |first=Rachel |date=2025-03-04 |title=EPA unfreezes $7 billion Solar for All grant program |url=https://pv-magazine-usa.com/2025/03/04/epa-unfreezes-7-billion-solar-for-all-grant-program/ |access-date=2025-03-24 |website=pv magazine USA |language=en-US}}</ref>

==== Ecosystems ====
In 2023 an agreement between seven states ([[Arizona]], [[California]], [[Colorado]], [[Nevada]], [[New Mexico]], [[Utah]], and [[Wyoming]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Seven States Letter |url=https://www.doi.gov/sites/doi.gov/files/seven-states-letter-5-22-2023.pdf |publisher=Colorado River Basin States Representatives of Arizona, California, Colorado, Nevada, New Mexico, Utah, and Wyoming |access-date=22 September 2023}}</ref> was achieved, aiming to preserve the [[Colorado River]] water system from collapse due to poor management and climate change. The United States is heavily dependent on the river for power generation, drinking water, agriculture, wildlands restoration, and native cultural practices. Some states will reduce water use, receiving $1.2 billion in compensation for it from the federal government. Many other projects for preserving the river such as [[water recycling]] and [[rainwater harvesting]] are being advanced. The funding comes from the [[Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act]] and the Inflation Reduction Act.<ref>{{cite web |title=Biden-Harris Administration Announces Historic Consensus System Conservation Proposal to Protect the Colorado River Basin |url=https://www.doi.gov/pressreleases/biden-harris-administration-announces-historic-consensus-system-conservation-proposal |website=U.S. Department of the Interior |date=May 22, 2023 |access-date=20 June 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Jones |first1=Benji |title=Why the new Colorado River agreement is a big deal — even if you don't live out West |url=https://www.vox.com/climate/2023/5/23/23734404/colorado-river-cuts-lake-mead-deal |access-date=20 June 2023 |agency=Vox |date=23 May 2023}}</ref>

According to a Biden administration statement, in the first year of implementation, around $2 billion was allocated to protect and restore land and marine ecosystems, including [[United States National Parks|National Parks]] and the [[National Wildlife Refuge System]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Fact Sheet: One Year In, President Biden's Inflation Reduction Act is Driving Historic Climate Action and Investing in America to Create Good Paying Jobs and Reduce Costs |url=https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2023/08/16/fact-sheet-one-year-in-president-bidens-inflation-reduction-act-is-driving-historic-climate-action-and-investing-in-america-to-create-good-paying-jobs-and-reduce-costs/ |website=The White House |date=August 16, 2023 |access-date=24 September 2023}}</ref> In August 2023, $150 million was given to small and underserved forest owners, and intended to link them to [[Emissions trading|climate markets]], providing incentives to conserve the forests.<ref>{{cite web |title=Biden-Harris Administration Invests $150M to Connect Underserved and Small Acreage Forest Landowners to Emerging Climate Markets as part of Investing in America Agenda |url=https://www.usda.gov/about-usda/news/press-releases/2023/08/22/biden-harris-administration-invests-150m-connect-underserved-and-small-acreage-forest-landowners |website=U.S. Department of Agriculture |date=August 22, 2023 |publisher=United States |access-date=27 September 2023}}</ref> Another $145 million were delivered with the same goal in March 2024.<ref>{{cite news |title=Biden-Harris Administration announces $145M from Investing in America agenda to help landowners access climate markets |url=https://www.webwire.com/ViewPressRel.asp?aId=319373 |access-date=19 March 2024 |agency=Webwire |publisher=The U.S. Department of Agriculture |date=18 March 2024}}</ref> In October 2024, $265 million from the act was delivered, followed in December by $335 million, to private forest owners for similar projects in conservation.<ref name="Forest Legacy">{{cite web | title=USDA Forest Service partners with states to conserve private forestlands as part of Investing in America agenda | website=US Forest Service | date=October 29, 2024 | url=https://www.fs.usda.gov/about-agency/newsroom/releases/usda-forest-service-partners-states-conserve-private-forestlands | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241029231312/https://www.fs.usda.gov/about-agency/newsroom/releases/usda-forest-service-partners-states-conserve-private-forestlands | archive-date=October 29, 2024 | access-date=December 21, 2024}}</ref><ref name="Forest Service">{{cite web | title=USDA announces nearly $335M in grants to support private forestland management and conservation as part of President Biden's Investing in America Agenda | website=US Forest Service | date=December 11, 2024 | url=https://www.fs.usda.gov/about-agency/newsroom/releases/usda-announces-nearly-335m-grants-support-private-forestland | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241211181115/https://www.fs.usda.gov/about-agency/newsroom/releases/usda-announces-nearly-335m-grants-support-private-forestland | archive-date=December 11, 2024 | access-date=December 20, 2024}}</ref>

In November 2023, the Biden administration announced it would provide the National Parks System $166 million for ecosystem resilience and [[environmental planning]].<ref name="The White House NCA5 Announcement 2023">{{cite web | author=The White House | title=Fact Sheet: Biden-Harris Administration Releases Fifth National Climate Assessment and Announces More Than $6 Billion to Strengthen Climate Resilience Across the Country | website=The White House | date=November 14, 2023 | url=https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2023/11/14/fact-sheet-biden-harris-administration-releases-fifth-national-climate-assessment-and-announces-more-than-6-billion-to-strengthen-climate-resilience-across-the-country/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231115042003/https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2023/11/14/fact-sheet-biden-harris-administration-releases-fifth-national-climate-assessment-and-announces-more-than-6-billion-to-strengthen-climate-resilience-across-the-country/|archive-date=November 15, 2023| url-status=live |
 access-date=November 15, 2023}}</ref> In August 2024, the Biden administration provided the [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service]] $20 million from the act for helping preserve Southwest desert fish, moths, freshwater mussels, and Pacific island plants.<ref name="Fish and Wildlife Service announcement 2024">{{cite web | title=Advancing Climate Resiliency and Conservation | website=FWS.gov | date=August 16, 2022 | url=https://www.fws.gov/initiative/directors-priorities/inflation-reduction-act-advancing-climate-resiliency-and| access-date=September 13, 2024}}</ref> In October, it provided the Regional Conservation Partnership Program within the USDA $1.5 billion from the act for 92 conservation projects around the country.<ref name="RCPP award announcement">{{cite web | title=USDA Invests $1.5 Billion in 92 Partnership Projects to Advance Conservation and Climate-Smart Agriculture as Part of the Biden-Harris Investing in America Agenda | website=USDA | date=October 23, 2024 | url=https://www.usda.gov/media/press-releases/2024/10/23/usda-invests-15-billion-92-partnership-projects-advance | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241023225752/https://www.usda.gov/media/press-releases/2024/10/23/usda-invests-15-billion-92-partnership-projects-advance | archive-date=October 23, 2024 | access-date=November 15, 2024}}</ref>

==== Sustainable agriculture ====
{{Expand section|date=October 2023}}
From October 2022 to September 2023 more than $850 million was given by the [[Natural Resources Conservation Service]] to its [[Environmental Quality Incentives Program]], [[Conservation Security Program|Conservation Stewardship Program]], Regional Conservation Partnership Program and Agricultural [[Conservation Easement]] Program to advance sustainable agriculture.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fact Sheet: Marking One Year of the Inflation Reduction Act |url=https://www.usda.gov/about-usda/news/press-releases/2023/08/16/fact-sheet-marking-one-year-inflation-reduction-act |website=U.S. DEPARTMENT OF AGRICULTURE |date=August 16, 2023 |publisher=the United States government |access-date=27 September 2023}}</ref>

In January 2024, Michael Happ of the [[Institute for Agriculture and Trade Policy]] found that the act's funding was able to support 2,366 more applicants to EQIP in 2023 compared to 2022, and 3,078 more applicants to the Conservation Stewardship Program across the same years; Happ, however, found that USDA resources such as staffing were often insufficient.<ref name="Happ 2024">{{cite web | last=Happ | first=Michael | title=Opening the door for more conservation | website=IATP | date=January 29, 2024 | url=https://www.iatp.org/opening-door-more-conservation | access-date=June 10, 2024}}</ref>

Journalist [[Michael Grunwald]], writing in Canary Media a year later, revealed IRA agriculture funds were overall focused more on [[corporate farming]]-led [[soil carbon]] storage (which he claimed had less scientific rigor to back it) than on efficient methods to reduce methane and nitrous oxide emissions, the reason being that Agriculture Secretary [[Tom Vilsack]]'s political considerations prevailed over White House climate adviser David Hayes' skeptical approach.<ref name="Grunwald 2025">{{cite web | last=Grunwald | first=Michael | title=Biden's climate-smart ag program was better than nothing. Trump killed it.| website=Canary Media | date=June 4, 2025 | url=https://www.canarymedia.com/articles/food-and-farms/biden-trump-climate-smart-agriculture | access-date=June 4, 2025}}</ref>

==== Environmental justice ====
In October 2023, the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|Environmental Protection Agency]] allocated $128 million to 186 projects linked to [[environmental justice]]. $104 million comes from the Inflation Reduction Act. The projects are designed to solve [[pollution]] and climate-related disasters in underserved communities. The projects include creating [[park]]s for addressing [[flood]]s, protecting [[Duck Valley Indian Reservation]] natural and cultural resources, teaching children about [[repairing]]{{clarify|date=November 2023}} and more.<ref>{{cite web |title=Biden-Harris Administration Announces Nearly $128 Million for Environmental Justice Projects in Communities Across the Country as Part of Investing in America Agenda |url=https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/biden-harris-administration-announces-nearly-128-million-environmental-justice |website=The United States Environmental Protection Agency |date=October 24, 2023 |publisher=the United States government |access-date=30 October 2023}}</ref> The full list of projects with short descriptions has been published.<ref>{{cite web |title=2023 Environmental Justice Collaborative Problem Solving (EJCPS) Program Project Summaries |url=https://www.epa.gov/system/files/documents/2023-10/2023-the-environmental-justice-collaborative-problem-solving-ejcps-program-project-summaries_0.pdf |publisher=The Environmental Protection Agency |access-date=30 October 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=2023 Environmental Justice Government-to-Government (EJG2G) Program Project Summaries |url=https://www.epa.gov/system/files/documents/2023-10/2023-government-to-government-ejg2g-project-summaries_1.pdf |publisher=Environmental Protection Agency |access-date=30 October 2023}}</ref>

In November 2023, the Biden administration announced the Department of the Interior would be spending $20 million to establish the Kapapahuliau Climate Resilience Program, named for the process of navigating through rough seas and winds, to the [[Native Hawaiian]] community for climate adaptation and resilience. The deadline to apply for program award grants was February 29, 2024.<ref name="The White House NCA5 Announcement 2023"/><ref name="U.S. Department of the Interior 2023">{{cite web | title=President Biden's Investing in America Agenda Announces $20 Million to Bolster Climate Resilience for Native Hawaiian Community | website=U.S. Department of the Interior | date=November 14, 2023 | url=https://www.doi.gov/pressreleases/president-bidens-investing-america-agenda-announces-20-million-bolster-climate | access-date=November 15, 2023}}</ref> It also announced the EPA would spend $2 billion on its new Community Change Grants Program <ref name="US EPA Community Change Grants 2023">{{cite web | title=Inflation Reduction Act Community Change Grants Program | website=US EPA | date=November 14, 2023 | url=https://www.epa.gov/inflation-reduction-act/inflation-reduction-act-community-change-grants-program | access-date=November 15, 2023}}</ref> for partnerships between local nonprofits, governments and indigenous tribes, and colleges and universities to "deploy clean energy, strengthen climate resilience, and build community capacity to respond to environmental and climate justice challenges".<ref name="The White House NCA5 Announcement 2023"/> In July 2024 $34 million was allocated from this program to some communities in Alabama and Tennessee to improve [[wastewater]] and [[stormwater]] management, reconnect communities and expand [[urban green space]]s.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Biden-Harris Administration allocates $34M for environmental justice projects in Alabama and Tennessee |url=https://thefederalnewswire.com/stories/662262161-biden-harris-administration-allocates-34m-for-environmental-justice-projects-in-alabama-and-tennessee |website=Federal Newswire |publisher=Environment Protection Agency |access-date=8 August 2024}}</ref>

=== Drug prices ===
The Biden administration announced the first ten drugs to have their prices negotiated in 2026 by Medicare on August 29, 2023. They are [[Apixaban|Eliquis]], [[Empagliflozin|Jardiance]], [[Rivaroxaban|Xarelto]], [[Sitagliptin|Januvia]], [[Dapagliflozin|Farxiga]], [[Sacubitril/valsartan|Entresto]], [[Etanercept|Enbrel]], [[Ibrutinib|Imbruvica]], [[Ustekinumab|Stelara]], and [[Insulin aspart|Fiasp]] and [[Insulin aspart|NovoLog]]. The list selection, made by the [[Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services]], was based on whether these drugs lacked competition, how much they cost Medicare, and how long they have been on the market.<ref name="The New York Times IRA drug announcement 2023">{{cite web |last1=Gay Stolberg |first1=Sheryl |last2=Robbins |first2=Rebecca |title=Eliquis and Jardiance Among First Drugs Picked for Medicare Price Negotiations |website=The New York Times |date=August 29, 2023 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/08/29/us/politics/medicare-drug-pricing-negotiations.html |access-date=August 29, 2023}}</ref><ref name="KFF September 2023"/> The manufacturers, [[Bristol Myers Squibb]], [[Boehringer Ingelheim]], [[Janssen Pharmaceuticals]], [[Merck & Co.|Merck]], [[AstraZeneca]], [[Novartis]], [[Amgen|Immunex]], [[Pharmacyclics]], and [[Novo Nordisk]], had until October 1, 2023 to declare their intent to participate, upon penalty of a large excise tax, or they would withdraw their drugs from [[Medicaid]] and [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]].<ref name="The New York Times IRA drug announcement 2023"/> The Biden administration announced two days later that all companies had agreed to the negotiations.<ref name="HHS.gov 2023">{{cite web |title=Biden-Harris Administration Moves Forward with Medicare Drug Price Negotiations to Lower Prescription Drug Costs for People with Medicare |website=HHS.gov |date=October 3, 2023 |url=https://www.hhs.gov/about/news/2023/10/03/biden-harris-administration-moves-medicare-drug-price-negotiations-lower-prescription-drug-costs-people-medicare.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231003130949/https://www.hhs.gov/about/news/2023/10/03/biden-harris-administration-moves-medicare-drug-price-negotiations-lower-prescription-drug-costs-people-medicare.html |archive-date=October 3, 2023 |access-date=October 14, 2023}}</ref> The administration made its initial offer on February 1, 2024, as part of a negotiation process that continued until August 1, 2024.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Not stated--> |title=Biden-Harris Administration to Make First Offer for Drug Price Negotiation Program, Launches New Resource Hub to Help People Access Lower-Cost Drugs |url=https://www.hhs.gov/about/news/2024/02/01/biden-harris-administration-make-first-offer-drug-price-negotiation-program-launches-new-resource-hub-help-people-access-lower-cost-drugs.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240201143847/https://www.hhs.gov/about/news/2024/02/01/biden-harris-administration-make-first-offer-drug-price-negotiation-program-launches-new-resource-hub-help-people-access-lower-cost-drugs.html |archive-date=February 1, 2024 |location= |publisher=[[United States Department of Health and Human Services|US Dept of Health and Human Services]] |agency= |date=1 February 2024 |access-date=2024-07-03}}</ref>

The Medicare drug price negotiation provisions are facing eight protest lawsuits filed by drug manufacturers and the [[U.S. Chamber of Commerce]], variously claiming that the federal government is violating the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First]], [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth]], and [[Eighth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Eighth]] Amendments to the Constitution, which deal with [[Freedom of speech in the United States|freedom of speech]], [[just compensation]] for [[Eminent domain|takings]], and excessive fines.<ref name=Kansteiner/><ref name="Gardner 2023" /> [[Larry Gostin]], a public health and legal scholar, told ''The New York Times'' that he does not expect the provisions to be upheld by the [[Supreme Court of the United States]].<ref name="The New York Times IRA drug announcement 2023"/><ref name="The New York Times drug lawsuits 2023">{{cite web |title=Drugmakers Throw 'Kitchen Sink' to Halt Medicare Price Negotiations |last1=Gay Stolberg |first1=Sheryl |last2=Robbins |first2=Rebecca |website=The New York Times |date=July 23, 2023 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/07/23/us/politics/medicare-drug-price-negotiations-lawsuits.html |access-date=August 29, 2023}}</ref><ref name="Gardner 2023">{{cite web |last=Gardner |first=Lauren |title=Drugmakers, trade groups push back against Medicare drug price negotiations |website=Politico |date=August 29, 2023 |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2023/08/29/drugmakers-trade-groups-push-back-against-medicare-drug-price-negotiations-00111936 |access-date=August 29, 2023}}</ref> A "second wave" of lawsuits, likely focusing on the price negotiations' bureaucratic process, was predicted to ensue, according to Stephen Ubl, CEO of the pharmaceutical industry lobbying group [[Pharmaceutical Research and Manufacturers of America|PhRMA]].<ref name="Lopez 2023">{{cite web |last=Lopez |first=Ian |title=Pharma Industry Readies for Drug Pricing Lawsuit Second Wave |website=Bloomberg Law News |date=October 24, 2023 |url=https://news.bloomberglaw.com/health-law-and-business/pharma-industry-readies-for-drug-pricing-lawsuit-second-wave |access-date=November 6, 2023}}</ref> Some legal commentators speculate the cases are intended to produce a variety of rulings across the federal courts, making it more likely for the Supreme Court to hear them.<ref name="Gardner Pharma">{{cite web |last=Gardner |first=Eric |title=Pharma Poised to Intensify Legal Battle Over Drug Price Negotiations |website=More Perfect Union (Substack) |date=November 4, 2023 |url=https://substack.perfectunion.us/p/pharma-poised-to-intensify-legal |access-date=November 6, 2023}}</ref> While the healthcare consulting firm Avalere claimed in July 2022 that $455 billion in revenue would be lost by drug manufacturers<ref name="Avalere 2022">{{cite web | title=Drug Pricing Bill Could Reduce Manufacturer Revenue by Over $450B | website=Avalere | date=July 27, 2022 | url=https://avalere.com/insights/drug-pricing-bill-could-reduce-manufacturer-revenue | access-date=August 29, 2023}}</ref> and the trade group Vital Transformation claimed 139 fewer new drugs would be approved over the next decade due to the act,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gassuli|first1=Daniel|last2=Bowen|first2=Harry|last3=Schulthess|first3=Duane|url=https://vitaltransformation.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/VT-BIO_IRA_v12.2.pdf|title=IRA's Impact on the U.S. Biopharma System|date=June 1, 2023|access-date=August 29, 2023|website=Vital Transformation}}</ref> the Congressional Budget Office projects only one fewer drug will be approved than without the act over the next decade, five fewer over the succeeding decade, and seven fewer over the decade after that.<ref name="The New York Times drug lawsuits 2023"/><ref name="KFF 2022"/>

===Health insurance subsidies===
The Inflation Reduction Act extended the American Rescue Plan's modifications to the [[Affordable Care Act]]'s health insurance subsidies, namely the Advanced Payment for Premium Tax Credit, through 2025. The [[Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services]] attributed increases in ACA health insurance enrollment after the 2022 enrollment period in part to the IRA. The 2023 Open Enrollment period, the first one under the IRA, saw an increase in new consumers of 3,699,749, compared to the previous year's increase of 3,066,360. The CMS saw an increase in approvals for financial aid from the act (90% of consumers compared to 2021's 85%, meaning the act and ARP helped roughly 14.72 million people in calendar year 2022) and estimated national averages of $824 per year and 46% in IRA savings on premiums, in addition to finding that 1.4 million people making up to four times the poverty line were still able to access subsidies thanks to the ARP and IRA.<ref>{{cite report |author=CMS staff |date=January 25, 2023 |title=Health Insurance Marketplaces 2023 Open Enrollment Report |url=https://www.cms.gov/files/document/health-insurance-exchanges-2023-open-enrollment-report-final.pdf |publisher=Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services |access-date=May 3, 2024}}</ref> The 2024 Open Enrollment period saw 5,215,764 new consumers sign up for the exchanges, an increase of 31% from the previous year's 3,699,749. 92% of consumers (roughly 19.73 million people) received aid from the act. The average annual premium savings figure now stood at $705 and 48%; the ARP and IRA had now helped 1.5 million people avoid subsidy ineligibility.<ref>{{cite report |author=CMS staff |date=January 24, 2024 |title=Health Insurance Marketplaces 2024 Open Enrollment Report |url=https://www.cms.gov/files/document/health-insurance-exchanges-2024-open-enrollment-report-final.pdf |publisher=Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services |access-date=May 3, 2024}}</ref> The 2025 Open Enrollment period saw an increase in new consumers of 3,938,907, a slowdown from last year's figure.<ref name="Open Enrollment 2025">{{cite web |author= CMS staff| title=Marketplace 2025 Open Enrollment Period Report: National Snapshot | website=CMS | date=January 15, 2025 | url=https://www.cms.gov/newsroom/fact-sheets/marketplace-2025-open-enrollment-period-report-national-snapshot-2 | access-date=June 4, 2025}}</ref> The IRA was credited with allowing 80 percent of users to find a plan for $10 a month or less.<ref name="CMS four out of five">{{cite web | title=Over 24 Million Consumers Selected Affordable Health Coverage in ACA Marketplace for 2025 | website=CMS | date=January 17, 2025 | url=https://www.cms.gov/newsroom/press-releases/over-24-million-consumers-selected-affordable-health-coverage-aca-marketplace-2025 | access-date=June 4, 2025}}</ref>

=== IRS reform ===
Treasury Secretary [[Janet Yellen]] directed [[IRS Commissioner|IRS commissioner]] [[Charles Rettig]] to not use the new funding allocated in the act to increase the rate of audits of those making less than $400,000 a year above historical levels, but to instead focus on "high-end noncompliance".<ref>{{Cite web |author=Kate Sullivan |title=Yellen directs IRS not to use new funding to increase chances of audits of Americans making less than $400,000 |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/08/10/politics/yellen-new-irs-funding-audits/index.html |access-date=2022-08-11 |website=CNN|date=August 11, 2022 }}</ref> A Treasury report indicated that half of the funding would be allocated to preventing tax evasion from large corporations and wealthy individuals.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rappeport|first=Alan|date=6 April 2023|title=I.R.S. Unveils $80 Billion Plan to Overhaul Tax Collection|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/04/06/business/economy/irs-tax-treasury.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=6 April 2023}}</ref>

Due to larger than expected use of the act's tax credits, the administration of Joe Biden has begun to reevaluate how much in unpaid taxes the IRS can collect to cover the costs.<ref name=Jim/> According to its new findings, full reorganization of the IRS will result in $851 billion in new revenue from 2024–2034 without having to add tax burdens to those who earn annual incomes less than $400,000; it notes that "the top 10 percent of the income distribution is responsible for 64 percent of unpaid taxes."<ref>{{cite web |title=Empowering the IRS: Understanding the Full Potential of the Inflation Reduction Act's Historic Investment in the Internal Revenue Service |url=https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/cea/written-materials/2024/02/08/empowering-the-irs-understanding-the-full-potential-of-the-inflation-reduction-acts-historic-investment-in-the-internal-revenue-service/ |website=The White House |date=February 8, 2024 |access-date=16 February 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Return on Investment: Re-Examining Revenue Estimates for IRS Funding |date=February 2024 |publisher=Department of the Treasury Internal Revenue Service |pages=1, 2 |url=https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-pdf/p5901.pdf |access-date=16 February 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Matthews |first1=Dylan |title=Biden invested big in more tax audits. A new IRS analysis claims it's working. |url=https://www.vox.com/politics/2024/2/7/24063380/irs-inflation-reduction-act-audit-returns |access-date=16 February 2024 |agency=Vox |date=7 February 2024}}</ref>

=== Per state ===
{{POV section|date=April 2024}}

==== Florida ====
The state of [[Florida]] received $3.75 million for [[Urban forestry|urban forests]] and nature conservation, $209,000 for fighting [[pollution]], and $78.7 million to protect the state from [[climate change impacts]] (the third amount is from the [[Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act]] and the Inflation Reduction Act combined).

However, Florida's governor, [[Ron DeSantis]], refused to accept $346 million for rebates to homeowners who will want to [[home energy upgrades from public utilities|retrofit]] their houses for [[energy conservation in the United States|energy efficiency]], $3 million to fight pollution, a program for helping low income people buy solar panels as well as $24 million from the Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act for improving [[sewage systems]] in rural areas.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Natter |first1=Ari |title=DeSantis Says No Thanks to $377 Million in Federal Energy Funds |url=https://www.bnnbloomberg.ca/desantis-says-no-thanks-to-377-million-in-federal-energy-funds-1.1944205 |access-date=6 September 2023 |agency=BNN Bloomberg |date=11 July 2023}}</ref>  DeSantis later reversed course and attempted to reclaim some of the rejected home energy rebate funds.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/2023/12/18/desantis-seeks-energy-saving-rebates-in-apparent-change-of-heart/ | title=DeSantis seeks energy-saving rebates in apparent change of heart | date=December 18, 2023 }}</ref>

The money can go to local cities and authorities. Three cities in Florida accepted some amounts. Other states want to take the money forfeited by Florida for themselves, namely [[Rhode Island]] and [[Kentucky]].<ref name=Haberkorn/>

The funds for the rebates were requested by the Florida state energy office and the legislature, but DeSantis vetoed them. He is the only governor who did so. The program was intended to help people to lower their energy bills and create jobs. Half of the money would have gone to low-income households.<ref name=Haberkorn>{{cite web |last1=Haberkorn |first1=Jennifer |title=DeSantis tells Biden: Keep your IRA money |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2023/08/30/desantis-refuses-biden-climate-ira-money-00113397 |website=Politico |date=August 30, 2023 |access-date=4 September 2023}}</ref> Making a house more energy efficient can cut utility bills by 25% for an average family in Florida.<ref>{{cite web |title=How much does energy efficiency cost? |url=https://www.energysage.com/energy-efficiency/why-conserve-energy/cost-of-ee/ |website=Energy Sage |date=April 5, 2023 |access-date=6 September 2023}}</ref> Part of the money would have gone to [[weatherization]] of houses.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Calder |first1=Meta |title=Veto of energy-efficiency funding falls squarely on the poor |url=https://www.theinvadingsea.com/2023/08/21/inflation-reduction-act-florida-desantis-veto-energy-rebates/ |website=The invading sea |date=August 21, 2023 |access-date=6 September 2023}}</ref>

==== Texas ====
Some aspects of the law are the same as in other states, while some are specific to [[Texas]]. Considerable tax credits and tax rebates are afforded. [[weatherization|House weatherization]], [[solar energy]], [[electric vehicle]]s, are advanced. House weatherization can save around $283 per year for an average family in Texas, while raising the value of the property and reducing air pollution in the same time. Some improvements can be made for free to low income households. The cost of an [[energy audit]] is reduced by 30% and some can even get it for free.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchings |first1=Kimberly |title=Beyond The Inflation Reduction Act: A Texas Guide |url=https://www.ohmconnect.com/blog/saving-money/beyond-the-inflation-reduction-act-a-texas-guide#:~:text=The%20Inflation%20Reduction%20Act's%20Energy,%24150%2C%20now%20through%20December%202032. |website=OhmConnect |access-date=6 September 2023}}</ref>

A third of Texas households can get a 100% rebate for installing a [[heat pump]] (generally costing US$8,000).<ref>{{cite web |last1=HENSON |first1=BOB |title=Heat pumps are catching on. New rebates, tax breaks may turbocharge the trend |url=https://texasclimatenews.org/2023/03/02/heat-pumps-are-catching-on-new-rebates-tax-breaks-may-turbocharge-the-trend/ |website=Texas Climate News |access-date=6 September 2023}}</ref> Forest protection is advanced, and farms that adopt climate-friendly practices get economic incentives.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Inflation Reduction Act Delivers Affordable Clean Energy for Texas |url=https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/Texas.pdf |website=The White House |access-date=6 September 2023}}</ref>

==== Alaska ====
In February 2024, $1 million was delivered to [[Alaska]] [[remote communities]]. The aim is to strengthen resilience and [[food security]], improve cooperation with indigenous tribes, and use [[traditional knowledge|their knowledge]].<ref>{{cite news |title=$1 Million to Support Climate Resilience in Remote Alaska Communities |url=https://www.ecomagazine.com/news/policy/1-million-to-support-climate-resilience-in-remote-alaska-communities |access-date=25 February 2024 |agency=ECO Magazine |date=22 February 2024}}</ref>

== Reactions ==
Senator [[Joe Manchin]] (D-[[West Virginia|WV]]) issued a statement for his support of the bill.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Raju |first1=Manu |last2=Luhby |first2=Tami |title=Manchin and Schumer announce deal for energy and health care bill |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/07/27/politics/schumer-manchin-deal-build-back-better/index.html |access-date=July 27, 2022 |work=CNN}}</ref> President [[Joe Biden]] also stated his support for the proposed Inflation Reduction Act.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |date=July 27, 2022 |title=Statement from President Biden on Inflation Reduction Act of 2022 |url=https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2022/07/27/statement-from-president-biden-on-inflation-reduction-act-of-2022/ |access-date=July 27, 2022 |website=The White House}}</ref> 
Later on, Biden said, "I wish I hadn't called it that because it has less to do with reducing inflation than it has to do with providing alternatives that generate economic growth."<ref name="biden_wishes"/>

On August 4, Senator [[Kyrsten Sinema]] (D-[[Arizona|AZ]]) issued a statement indicating that she would support the bill after striking a deal with fellow Democrats to change several tax provisions.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Democrats, Sinema reach deal on new taxes in Inflation Reduction Act |newspaper=The Washington Post |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/us-policy/2022/08/04/inflation-reduction-act-sinema/ |access-date=2022-08-05 |issn=0190-8286}}</ref>

Congressional Republicans voiced unanimous opposition to the bill, claiming the legislation would do little to combat inflation, or would exacerbate it. Senate minority leader [[Mitch McConnell]] (R-[[Kentucky|KY]]) denounced the legislation as "reckless spending" and Ranking Member of the Senate Budget Committee [[Lindsey Graham]] (R-[[South Carolina|SC]]) called it "insanity".{{citation needed|date=October 2024}}

In a letter sent to congressional leadership and touted by Senate Democrats, 126 economists including [[Robert Rubin]], [[Jack Lew]], [[Jason Furman]], [[Lawrence Summers]], [[Mark Zandi]], and [[Joseph Stiglitz]], wrote that the bill is more than fully paid for, lowers prices for consumers and will lower inflation.<ref>{{Cite web |author=Betsy Klein |title=First on CNN: Top economists say Democrats' health care and climate package will put 'downward pressure on inflation' |url=https://www.cnn.com/2022/08/02/politics/economists-democrats-package-downward-pressure-inflation/index.html |access-date=2022-08-14 |website=CNN|date=August 2, 2022 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=August 1, 2022 |title=The Inflation Reduction Act Will Reduce Inflation |url=https://www.democrats.senate.gov/dpcc/press-releases/the-inflation-reduction-act-will-reduce-inflation |access-date=2022-08-05 |publisher=Senate Democratic Leadership}}</ref>
Furman also said, "I can't think of any mechanism by which it would have brought down inflation to date."<ref name="biden_wishes">{{Cite web |last=Boak|date=2023-08-13 |title=Even Joe Biden wishes he hadn't called his signature law the Inflation Reduction Act |url=https://fortune.com/2023/08/13/inflation-reduction-act-not-big-factor-in-bringing-down-inflation-say-economists/ | website=Fortune |access-date=2025-06-03 |language=en}}</ref>

In a letter sent to congressional leadership, 230 economists including [[Vernon L. Smith|Vernon Smith]], [[H. Robert Heller|Robert Heller]], [[Kevin Hassett]], and [[James C. Miller III|Jim Miller]], wrote that the bill will increase prices for consumers and will increase inflation.<ref>{{Cite web |last=rbradley |date=2022-08-05 |title=Economists Letter to the U.S. Congress on the "Inflation Reduction Act of 2022" |url=https://www.masterresource.org/inflation-reduction-act-of-2022/economists-letter-inflation-reduction-act-2022/ |access-date=2023-04-02 |website=Master Resource |language=en}}</ref><ref name="Laco">{{Cite web |last=Laco |first=Kelly |date=2022-08-04 |title=Over 230 economists warn Manchin's spending bill will perpetuate inflation |url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/politics/230-economists-warn-manchins-spending-bill-will-perpetuate-inflation |access-date=2023-04-02 |website=FOXBusiness |language=en-US}}</ref>

Tom Philpott, an agriculture journalist writing in [[Wired (magazine)|''Wired'']], praised the bill's investments in climate-smart agriculture and remedies for USDA loan discrimination, but heavily criticized Sinema's deletion of the carried interest loophole modification and the lack of provisions to expand funding for the [[National School Lunch Act]] and improvements to child nutrition (as expressed in the original [[Build Back Better Act]]) and for [[soil erosion]] prevention programs (which enhance small-scale [[carbon farming]] and encourage a shift away from [[monoculture]]-dependent farming for [[ethanol fuel in the United States]]).<ref name="Philpott 2022"/>

=== Public organizations ===
[[Darren Woods]], the CEO of oil and gas energy giant [[ExxonMobil]], called the bill "a step in the right direction" and endorsed its provisions related to oil and gas.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Crowley |first1=Kevin |date=July 30, 2022 |title=Exxon CEO Loves What Manchin Did for Big Oil in $370 Billion Deal |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-07-29/exxon-s-woods-calls-manchin-bill-step-in-the-right-direction |access-date=July 30, 2022 |website=Bloomberg}}</ref> Multiple coal industry groups, including the West Virginia Coal Association, criticized the bill for "[obviating] any need to innovate coal assets" and doing "nothing for coal or coal generation".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Alexander |first1=Bolton |title=Coal industry 'shocked and disheartened' by Manchin climate deal |url=https://www.wfxrtv.com/news/regional-news/west-virginia-news/coal-industry-shocked-and-disheartened-by-manchin-climate-deal/ |website=WFXRtv |publisher=The Hill |date=August 4, 2022|access-date=August 9, 2022}}</ref>

Many mainstream environmental organizations supported the bill, such as the [[The Nature Conservancy|Nature Conservancy]], the [[National Wildlife Federation]], and [[American Forests]].<ref name=":6">{{Cite news |last=Dennis |first=Brady |date=14 August 2022 |title=As Congress funds high-tech climate solutions, it also bets on a low-tech one: Nature |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/climate-solutions/2022/08/14/nature-climate-solutions-inflation-reduction-act/ |access-date=16 August 2022}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=A "New Day for Climate Action in the United States" as U.S. Congress Passes Historic Clean Energy and Climate Investments |url=https://www.nature.org/en-us/newsroom/us-house-passes-landmark-climate-bill/ |access-date=2022-08-17 |website=The Nature Conservancy |language=en-US}}</ref> The director of North America policy for the Nature Conservancy, Tom Cors, called the legislation "historic", while Aviva Glaser of the NWF called the infusion of spending "transformative." The [[Natural Resources Defense Council]] argued that despite continued acceptance of fossil fuels in the IRA, its climate mitigation policies would outweigh their impact ten times over.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Plumer |first1=Brad |last2=Friedman |first2=Lisa |date=2022-07-30 |title=Democrats Got a Climate Bill. Joe Manchin Got Drilling, and More. |language=en-US |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/07/30/climate/manchin-climate-deal.html |access-date=2022-08-17 |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Health and environmental justice organizations like [[Earthjustice]] have welcomed the law.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Jaffe |first=Susan |date=2022-09-03 |title=Health organisations welcome US climate crisis law |url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(22)01663-4/abstract |journal=The Lancet |language=English |volume=400 |issue=10354 |pages=719–720 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(22)01663-4 |issn=0140-6736 |pmid=36058212|s2cid=251984511 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>

However, not all environmental groups expressed unqualified support. Some environmentalists noted that the bill contained more "[[Carrot and stick|carrots]]", or incentives for positive behavior, than "[[Carrot and stick|sticks]]", or new regulations.<ref name=":6" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Leber |first=Rebecca |date=2022-08-16 |title=4 underrated parts of the Inflation Reduction Act |url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2022/8/16/23306588/biden-inflation-reduction-act-climate-pollution-energy |access-date=2022-08-17 |website=Vox |language=en}}</ref> Several groups argued that as the legislation did not seek to eliminate fossil fuels entirely, it was inadequate to meet the threat of climate change. Jean Su, the energy justice program director at the [[Center for Biological Diversity]], called the legislation "a backdoor take-it-or-leave-it deal between a coal baron and Democratic leaders in which any opposition from lawmakers or frontline communities was quashed."<ref name="More harm than good">{{cite web |last1=Lakhani |first1=Nina |date=August 9, 2022 |title=Landmark US climate bill will do more harm than good, groups say |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2022/aug/09/us-climate-bill-fossil-fuel-harm-environment-biden |url-status=live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20220812091207/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2022/aug/09/us-climate-bill-fossil-fuel-harm-environment-biden |archive-date=August 12, 2022 |access-date=August 12, 2022 |work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> The [[Climate Justice Alliance]] criticized the IRA, saying that "the strengths of the IRA are outweighed by the bill's weaknesses and threats posed by the expansion of fossil fuels and unproven technologies such as carbon capture and hydrogen generation."<ref name="More harm than good" />

Cycling organizations criticized the IRA for removing the incentives for [[electric bicycle]]s in the original Build Back Better Act, having a better energy-per-incentive ratio and reaching a wider demographic, than for [[electric car]]s remaining in the IRA.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Toll |first1=Micah |date=8 August 2022 |title=The new climate bill abandoned the type of electric vehicle that can make the biggest difference |url=https://electrek.co/2022/08/07/the-new-climate-bill-abandoned-the-type-of-electric-vehicle-that-can-make-the-biggest-difference/ |url-status=live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20220808181648/https://electrek.co/2022/08/07/the-new-climate-bill-abandoned-the-type-of-electric-vehicle-that-can-make-the-biggest-difference/ |archive-date=8 August 2022 |website=[[Electrek]]}}</ref> Sean Jeans-Gail, Vice President of Government Affairs and Policy at the [[Rail Passengers Association]], criticized the IRA saying, "It's a bitter pill in terms of rail and transit, which is the one clearly established, low-carbon emission transportation systems we have going". He also criticized the bill for being car centric.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Weinberg |first1=Harrison |title='It's so blatant': Transit groups bemoan Dems' car-centric climate deal |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2022/07/28/transit-democrats-car-climate-deal-00048599 |access-date=August 26, 2022 |website=Politico |date=July 28, 2022 |publisher=Alex Daugherty}}</ref>

===Relationship with foreign policy===
Biden's national security advisor [[Jake Sullivan]] has been identified as the staffer in charge of ensuring the act does not conflict with American foreign policy interests.<ref name="Kuttner 2023"/>

Among American foreign policy analysts and officials, Anna McGinn of the think tank [[Environmental and Energy Study Institute]] praised the act for helping the U.S. meet its commitments to the [[Paris Agreement]], but criticized the act for lacking commitments to [[loss and damage (climate change)|loss and damage]] and other forms of climate-related [[foreign aid]] as well as to creating a cohesive national climate strategy.<ref name="McGinn 2022"/> [[Jason Bordoff]], writing on the [[International Monetary Fund]]'s website, cautioned that it could expose the U.S. to the beginnings of [[trade war]], but if implemented deftly, the act could strengthen diplomacy with Europe and help create special rules to advance the trade of clean energy.<ref name="IMF 2022">{{cite web | last=Bordoff|first=Jason|title=America's Landmark Climate Law | website=IMF | date=December 1, 2022 | url=https://www.imf.org/en/Publications/fandd/issues/2022/12/america-landmark-climate-law-bordoff | access-date=March 24, 2023}}</ref> Commentators at the [[Center for Strategic International Studies]] and in ''[[The Diplomat (magazine)|The Diplomat]]'', along with [[United States Trade Representative]] [[Katherine Tai]] and John Podesta himself have acknowledged increased economic competition with [[China]] as one of many motivators behind the act.<ref name="Mazzocco 2022">{{cite journal | last=Mazzocco | first=Ilaria | title=Why the New Climate Bill Is Also about Competition with China | website=Center for Strategic International Studies| date=August 25, 2022 | url=https://www.csis.org/analysis/why-new-climate-bill-also-about-competition-china | access-date=March 24, 2023}}</ref><ref name="Agrawal 2023">{{cite web | last=Agrawal | first=Ravi | title=The White House's Case for Industrial Policy | website=Foreign Policy | date=March 24, 2023 | url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2023/03/02/live-industrial-policy-katherine-tai-trade-economy-chips-inflation/ |publisher=Graham Digital Holding Company| access-date=March 24, 2023}}</ref><ref name="Shi 2023">{{cite web | last=Shi | first=Jiachen | title=Conflicting Economic Ideologies May Impact Future China Policy in the US | website=The Diplomat | date=March 9, 2023 | url=https://thediplomat.com/2023/03/conflicting-economic-ideologies-may-impact-future-china-policy-in-the-us/ | publisher=Diplomat Media|access-date=March 24, 2023}}</ref><ref name="Podesta 2024">{{cite web | last=Podesta | first=John | title=Remarks as Prepared for John Podesta Columbia Global Energy Summit | website=The White House | date=April 16, 2024 | url=https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/briefing-room/speeches-remarks/2024/04/16/remarks-as-prepared-for-john-podesta-columbia-global-energy-summit/ | language=en-US | access-date=November 26, 2024}}</ref>

Internationally, reactions were mixed. [[Fatih Birol]], the head of the [[International Energy Agency]], called it "the single most important climate action since the Paris Agreement in 2015". However, some were concerned about the law's provisions favoring American industry. In an interview with ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' [[Amitabh Kant]], the chairman of the 2023 [[G20]] meeting in India, called it "the most protectionist act ever drafted in the world", asking American officials, "You believed in market forces and now you do this?" Other countries have begun to create their own similar laws.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Worland|first1=Justin|title=How the Inflation Reduction Act Has Reshaped the U.S.—and The World |url=https://time.com/6304143/inflation-reduction-act-us-global-impact/ |access-date=16 February 2024 |website=Time Magazine|publisher=TIME USA, LLC |date=11 August 2023}}</ref> China requested [[Dispute settlement in the World Trade Organization|WTO dispute consultations]] with the United States.<ref>{{cite news |title=China opens WTO dispute against US subsidies to protect its EV industry |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/china-opens-dispute-against-us-wto-over-discriminatory-subsidies-2024-03-26/ |work=Reuters |date=26 March 2024}}</ref>

27 [[European Union]] finance ministers have expressed "serious concerns" about the financial incentives of the Inflation Reduction Act, and are considering challenging it. They have listed at least nine points in the legislation, which they say could be in breach of [[World Trade Organization]] rules. They were opposed to the subsidies for consumers to buy North American-assembled [[electric car]]s, as EU officials believe the subsidies discriminate against European carmakers. One EU official told [[CNBC]] that, "there is a political consensus (among the 27 ministers) that this plan threatens the European industry"<ref name="CNBC 2022"/><ref name="Kuttner 2023">{{cite web | last=Kuttner | first=Robert | title=Reclaiming U.S. Industry | website=The American Prospect | date=January 24, 2023 | url= https://prospect.org/economy/2023-01-24-biden-american-industrial-policy/| access-date=February 22, 2023}}</ref><ref name=Blenkinsop>{{cite web |last1=Blenkinsop |first1=Philip |title=EU seeks to arrest industry decline in green transition |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/sustainable-business/eu-seeks-arrest-industry-decline-green-transition-2023-03-10/ |website=Reuters |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230311144739/https://www.reuters.com/business/sustainable-business/eu-seeks-arrest-industry-decline-green-transition-2023-03-10/ |archive-date=11 March 2023 |language=en |date=10 March 2023 |quote=engaged in a subsidies race |url-status=live}}</ref> and its supply of raw materials.<ref name=lemonde>{{cite web |title=US and EU begin negotiations on critical minerals access for EV batteries |url=https://www.lemonde.fr/en/international/article/2023/03/10/us-and-eu-begin-negotiations-on-critical-minerals-access-for-ev-batteries_6018894_4.html |website=[[Le Monde]].fr |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230311141350/https://www.lemonde.fr/en/international/article/2023/03/10/us-and-eu-begin-negotiations-on-critical-minerals-access-for-ev-batteries_6018894_4.html |archive-date=11 March 2023 |language=en |date=10 March 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref> In February 2023, the [[European Commission]] announced it would propose the "Net Zero Industrial Act", similar to the IRA,<ref name=Oraan>{{cite web |last1=Marc |first1=Oraan |title=Do the U.S. Multi-Billion Battery Subsidies Put the European Battery Production at Risk? |url=https://www.autoevolution.com/news/do-the-us-multi-billion-battery-subsidies-put-the-european-battery-production-at-risk-211491.html |website=autoevolution |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230311204035/https://www.autoevolution.com/news/do-the-us-multi-billion-battery-subsidies-put-the-european-battery-production-at-risk-211491.html |archive-date=11 March 2023 |language=en |date=11 March 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref> in turn putting pressure on the United Kingdom<ref>{{cite web |title=Political Concern Grows Over UK's Lost 'Green Economy' Edge – OpEd |url=https://www.eurasiareview.com/12032023-political-concern-grows-over-uks-lost-green-economy-edge-oped/ |website=[[Eurasia Review]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230311231358/https://www.eurasiareview.com/12032023-political-concern-grows-over-uks-lost-green-economy-edge-oped/ |archive-date=11 March 2023 |date=11 March 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=helm>{{cite web |last1=Helm |first1=Toby |title=Labour planning £8bn Biden-style green energy revolution |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/mar/12/labour-planning-8bn-green-revolution-for-uk-industry-in-deprived-regions |website=[[The Observer]] |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230312122149/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2023/mar/12/labour-planning-8bn-green-revolution-for-uk-industry-in-deprived-regions |archive-date=12 March 2023 |date=12 March 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref> and South Korea.<ref name=invkor/>

On March 10, 2023, President Biden and [[President of the European Commission]] [[Ursula von der Leyen]] announced they would be initiating top-level talks to mitigate issues of [[Tax competition|subsidy competition]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Corner |first1=The |title=US and EU initiate steps to resolve Inflation Reduction Act dispute {{!}} The Corner |url=https://thecorner.eu/54/us-and-eu-initiate-steps-to-resolve-inflation-reduction-act-dispute/104965/ |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230312115256/https://thecorner.eu/54/us-and-eu-initiate-steps-to-resolve-inflation-reduction-act-dispute/104965/ |archive-date=12 March 2023 |date=12 March 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=lemonde/><ref name=Blenkinsop/>

Representatives from [[South Korea]] have also voiced similar concerns to Europe, given that the legislation can also restrict [[Hyundai Motor Company|Hyundai's]] and other South Korean carmakers' business in the American market.<ref name=invkor>{{cite web |title=Korean auto, battery sectors brace for EU-first act |url=https://www.theinvestor.co.kr/view.php?ud=20230312000025 |website=www.theinvestor.co.kr |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230312030508/https://www.theinvestor.co.kr/view.php?ud=20230312000025 |archive-date=12 March 2023 |language=en |date=11 March 2023 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Best |first=Paul |date=2022-09-01 |title=EU hits US for Inflation Reduction Act electric vehicle tax credit requiring final assembly in North America |url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/economy/eu-hits-us-electric-vehicle-tax-credit-requires-final-assembly-cars-north-america |access-date=2022-09-03 |website=FOXBusiness |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Palmer |first=Doug |title=USTR shrugs off EU criticism of EV tax credit |url=https://politi.co/3C8qKYS |access-date=2022-09-03 |website=Politico |date=August 15, 2022 |language=en}}</ref><ref name="CNBC 2022">{{Cite web |last=Amaro |first=Silvia |title=Europe shows a united front against Biden's Inflation Reduction Act, says it threatens industry |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2022/11/09/europe-shows-a-united-front-against-bidens-inflation-reduction-act.html |access-date=2022-12-25 |website=CNBC |date=November 9, 2022 |language=en}}</ref>

===Implementation criticisms, concerns===
====Relationship with asset managers====
Geographer and political writer [[Brett Christophers]] pointed out, after a renewables project was funded by [[Brookfield Corporation]] upon the act's passage, that [[asset management]] companies would likely see the act as a windfall for taking over public works, citing their poor track records with British and South Korean infrastructure and American housing.<ref name="Christophers 2023">{{cite web | last=Christophers | first=Brett | title=The Inflation Reduction Act Will Allow an Asset Manager Takeover of Our Infrastructure | website=The New York Times | date=May 8, 2023 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2023/05/08/opinion/inflation-reduction-act-global-asset-managers.html | access-date=October 31, 2024}}</ref>

====Labor rules====
Some members of the trade union [[United Auto Workers]], including former vice president [[Cindy Estrada]], have obliquely commented to ''[[The American Prospect]]'' that the Inflation Reduction Act's implementation regarding [[prevailing wage]] requirements and [[collective bargaining]] rights (particularly at electric vehicle factories owned by startup companies) may be weakened, and if not properly implemented, the act could be linked to poor hiring practices and working conditions.<ref name="Harris 2022">{{cite web | last=Harris | first=Lee | title=Industrial Policy Without Industrial Unions | website=The American Prospect | date=28 September 2022 | url=https://prospect.org/api/content/aff4b44e-3e71-11ed-9b46-12274efc5439/ | access-date=5 October 2022}}</ref> Other labor union representatives, from the [[AFL–CIO]], Southwest Laborers District Council, Ironworkers Local 848 and [[United Steelworkers]], told Reuters in March 2023 that investments announced due to the act have not improved labor unions' ability to organize particularly in right-to-work law states, but that they were hopeful in pushing ahead.<ref name="Reuters right-to-work 2023">{{cite web | last=Groom | first=Nichola | title=Biden's clean energy factory jobs may elude U.S. union workers | website=Reuters | date=March 7, 2023 | url=https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/bidens-clean-energy-factory-jobs-may-elude-us-union-workers-2023-03-06/ | access-date=March 9, 2023}}</ref>

====Environmental justice concerns====
Climate activists Miriam Nielsen, Raya Salter and Heather Tanana examined the act's effects eight months after passage, and raised questions on whether the act would provide tax credits and grants equitably, mentioning the home energy upgrade grants and the Biden administration's [[Justice40]] initiative for [[racial justice]], whether the act would disproportionately help larger environmental groups with more resources rather than smaller ones, and how it would implement $4 billion in Western drought resilience grants and make accessing them easier.<ref name="Zentouro 2023 whole video">{{cite AV media|people=Nielsen, Miriam| title=What's going on with the Inflation Reduction Act?|location=New York, NY |type=YouTube video | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=g9x3UeYOJn4|date=May 24, 2023|publisher=Zentouro | access-date=May 24, 2023}}</ref>

====EV rules====
The ''Prospect''{{'}}s editor, [[Robert Kuttner]], commented in January 2023 that the Treasury Department's interpretation of the act regarding electric vehicle leasing could also potentially undermine the act's U.S. domestic supply provisions in favor of European or Chinese suppliers.<ref name="Kuttner 2023"/> Manchin expressed disappointment with the Treasury's new guidance and its more lenient provisions for foreign trading partners upon its release on March 31.<ref name="Bikales 2023"/> On December 18, he wrote a letter to [[Gene Dodaro]], head of the [[Government Accountability Office]], asking for a legal opinion on if Congress can overturn the Treasury guidance on Section 30D, on the basis that it is technically a proposal and not finalized, but is being enforced as the latter.<ref name="Cama 2023">{{cite web | last=Cama | first=Timothy | title=Manchin opens new front in war on Biden EV policies | website=E&E News by POLITICO | date=December 19, 2023 | url=https://www.eenews.net/articles/manchin-opens-new-front-in-war-on-biden-ev-policies/ | access-date=December 19, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite letter|last=Manchin|first=Joe|url= https://www.energy.senate.gov/services/files/5FEE5924-6E0B-47DE-97A6-FEE0B345BBE7|recipient=Gene L. Dodaro|date=December 18, 2023|subject=Request for legal opinion on Section 30D guidance|language=English|author-link=Joe Manchin|format=PDF|publisher=United States Senate Committee on Energy and Natural Resources|location=Washington, DC}}</ref>

====Clean hydrogen rules====
On December 13, 2023, Manchin also expressed his disappointment with the Biden administration's implementation of his Section 45V tax credit<ref name="45V"/> for clean hydrogen after the draft guidelines were leaked, claiming it was "horrible" and too stringent beyond his intent for the credit.<ref name="Natter 2023">{{cite web | last=Natter | first=Ari | title=Joe Manchin Says 'Horrible' Hydrogen Tax Credit Rules Coming Next Week | website=Bloomberg.com | date=December 13, 2023 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-12-13/manchin-says-horrible-hydrogen-tax-credit-rules-coming-next-week | access-date=December 19, 2023}}</ref> Manchin later said he would bring a lawsuit against the Biden administration upon release of the guidelines. [[Constellation Energy]], the United States' largest nuclear power plant operator, said it would pull back on green and pink hydrogen projects if the guidelines were released.<ref name="Kaufman 2023">{{cite web | last=Kaufman | first=Alexander C. | title=Democrats And Industry Are At War With Themselves Over A Controversial Energy Plan | website=Yahoo News | date=December 17, 2023 | url=https://news.yahoo.com/democrats-industry-war-themselves-over-130037079.html | access-date=December 22, 2023}}</ref> Staffers for Governor [[Gavin Newsom]] (D-CA) also asked the Treasury Department in May 2024 for an "alternative compliance pathway" that lifted emissions restrictions on the state's hydrogen hub, ostensibly to better align with their [[100% renewable energy]] adoption goal.<ref name="Cantú 2024">{{cite web | last=Cantú | first=Aaron | title=California's Dream of a Green Hydrogen Future Could Backfire | website=The American Prospect | date=May 9, 2024 | url=https://prospect.org/environment/2024-05-09-californias-dream-green-hydrogen-future-could-backfire/ | access-date=May 11, 2024}}</ref> Lobbying against the proposed Treasury rules has only intensified since then, according to Pontecorvo.<ref name="Pontecorvo three pillars rule">{{cite web | last=Pontecorvo | first=Emily | title=The Hydrogen Tax Credit Rules Are Effectively Dead | website=Heatmap News | date=2024-07-15 | url=https://heatmap.news/economy/hydrogen-tax-credit-rules | access-date=2024-09-05}}</ref> In her interview with Deputy Treasury Secretary [[Wally Adeyemo]], Adeyemo promised a "middle of the road" approach between environmentalists' and Manchin and lobbyists' concerns, in the run-up to the tax credit's finalization, then expected by December 2024.<ref name="Pontecorvo interview of Adeyemo"/>

On January 3, 2025, the Treasury Department finalized the 45V credit's rules. Most environmental groups that commented, and Governor Newsom's administration, praised them, though expressed concern about its new exemptions and delaying of the hourly matching provision, while industry groups were more cautious in welcoming them.<ref name="Pontecorvo January 2025"/>

====Sustainable aviation fuel rules====
In April 2024, the Section 40B tax credit guidance was released. While biofuel producers, trade groups and [[United Airlines|United]] and [[American Airlines]] fully welcomed the guidance, farmers and lower-level ethanol producers said the guidance was too prescriptive and did not reflect the full range of agricultural approaches to climate policy, while environmentalists criticized the guidance for not going far enough to account for all lifecycle emissions from ethanol fuel.<ref name="Gallucci May 6, 2024">{{cite web | last=Gallucci | first=Maria | title=Can corn ethanol really help decarbonize US air travel? | website=Canary Media | date=May 6, 2024 | url=https://www.canarymedia.com/articles/air-travel/can-corn-ethanol-really-help-decarbonize-u.s.-air-travel| access-date=May 6, 2024}}</ref><ref name="Walter 2024">{{cite web | last=Walter | first=Cassidy | title=Agriculture and biofuel industries react to new rules for sustainable aviation fuel tax credit | website=Successful Farming | date=April 30, 2024 | url=https://www.agriculture.com/biofuels-industry-reacts-to-new-rules-for-sustainable-aviation-fuel-tax-credit-8641511 | access-date=May 6, 2024}}</ref>

==Trump administration actions and the courts==
{{expand section|date=April 2025}}
On January 20–23, 2025, the [[Trump administration]] issued executive direction leading federal agencies to pause disbursements and payments of funds appropriated under the IRA and the [[Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act]]. The directive instructed agency heads to review grants, loans, contracts, and other disbursements to determine consistency with the administration's policy priorities and temporarily halted payments to recipients that had already been awarded funding.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Federal Agencies Ordered to Pause Spending of Inflation Reduction Act, Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act Funds |url=https://www.morganlewis.com/pubs/2025/01/federal-agencies-ordered-to-pause-spending-of-inflation-reduction-act-infrastructure-investment-and-jobs-act-funds |access-date=2026-01-22 |website=www.morganlewis.com |language=en}}</ref>

Later in 2025, the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|U.S. Environmental Protection Agency]], under Administrator [[Lee Zeldin]], took steps to terminate or retract certain IRA-funded grant programs. Among these actions were efforts to cancel awards under the Greenhouse Gas Reduction Fund (GGRF) and reports that EPA was drafting termination notices for awards under the Solar for All program, totaling billions of dollars in climate-related grants. These internal agency actions have been the subject of separate litigation and legal challenge.<ref>{{Cite web |title=EPA Contemplating Purported Termination of All $7 Billion in Solar for All Grants |url=http://foleyhoag.com/news-and-insights/publications/alerts-and-updates/2025/august/epa-contemplating-purported-termination-of-all-$7-billion-in-solar-for-all-grants/ |access-date=2026-01-22 |website=foleyhoag.com |language=en}}</ref>

On April 15, 2025, federal judge [[Mary S. McElroy|Mary McElroy]] of Rhode Island ruled in a case brought by local conservation groups that some of the act's funding had to be unfrozen nationwide.<ref name="Guillén 2025">{{cite web | last=Guillén | first=Alex | title=Federal judge orders immediate thaw of climate, infrastructure funds | website=POLITICO | date=April 15, 2025 | url=https://www.politico.com/news/2025/04/15/judge-orders-immediate-thaw-of-ira-infrastructure-funds-00292111 | access-date=April 30, 2025}}</ref> On the same day, District of Columbia federal judge [[Tanya Chutkan]] issued a preliminary injunction forcing the EPA and the Treasury Department's designated distributor, [[Citibank]], to unfreeze the Greenhouse Gas Reduction Fund.<ref name="Juhasz 2025">{{cite magazine | last=Juhasz | first=Antonia | title=The Court Battle to Stop Trump's $20 Billion Climate Clawback | magazine=Rolling Stone | date=April 17, 2025 | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/politics/politics-features/trump-climate-clawback-court-green-bank-20-billion-1235319866/ | access-date=April 30, 2025}}</ref>

In a court filing for another case involving New England conservation groups, the EPA indicated it would plan to cut 781 further environmental justice grants related to the IRA and other Biden-era policies.<ref name="WaPo Trump EPA next court date">{{cite news | last1=Joselow | first1=Maxine | last2=Ajasa | first2=Amudalat | title=The EPA is canceling almost 800 environmental justice grants, court filing reveals | newspaper=The Washington Post | date=April 29, 2025 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/climate-environment/2025/04/29/epa-environmental-justice-grants-canceled/ | access-date=April 30, 2025}}</ref>

The [[One Big Beautiful Bill Act]] repealed many IRA provisions.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Worland |first=Justin |date=2025-05-16 |title=The Clean Energy Tax Debate Will Shape America's Economic Future |url=https://time.com/7285948/clean-energy-inflation-reduction-act-budget-debate-tax-cuts/ |access-date=2025-05-20 |website=TIME |language=en}}</ref><ref name="Grunwald 2025"/><ref name="Bikales Tamborrino 2025">{{cite web | last1=Bikales | first1=James | last2=Tamborrino | first2=Kelsey | title=Senate Republicans look to curb House rollback of IRA tax credits | website=POLITICO | date=May 23, 2025 | url=https://www.politico.com/news/2025/05/23/senate-republicans-house-rollback-ira-tax-credits-00366212 | access-date=June 4, 2025}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=How Trump's 'big, beautiful bill' impacts Canada and the clean energy push - National {{!}} Globalnews.ca |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/11271924/trump-big-beautiful-bill-canada-impact-clean-energy/ |access-date=2025-07-05 |website=Global News |language=en-US}}</ref>

